<1ST_LINE>r a AM-RoarkRelease     07-02 0278</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Roark Release,0285</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Charleston Mayor Earns Early Release For Good Behavior</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLY P. KISSEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Charleston Mayor Mike Roark will
be released from federal prison 18 days early because he has been a
model prisoner while serving time for cocaine possession,
authorities said Friday.
   Roark, who was sentenced to 179 days in prison in November after
pleading guilty to cocaine possession, will be released July 20,
said Frank Sizer, director of the Federal Correctional Institution
at Petersburg, Va.
   The former Republican mayor and Kanawha County prosecutor will
be credited with 16 days of time for good behavior and two days for
time served after his arrest, Sizer said.
   Roark, who earned the nickname ``Mad Dog'' for his zealous
prosecution of drug offenders during his days as Kanawha County
prosecutor, had just started his second four-year term when he was
indicted.
   Roark was indicted in July 1987 on 27 cocaine-related counts and
three charges of conspiracy to obstruct justice. All but six
misdemeanor possession counts were dropped in a plea bargain in
which he agreed to resign his office.
   A spokesman for the State Bar this week said Roark will be
called in for a hearing soon after his release. The bar is deciding
whether to revoke or suspend his license as a result of his guilty
plea.
   Roark served as an assistant U.S. attorney in western
Pennsylvania in the mid-1970s before returning to West Virginia's
largest city to begin his political career in 1978.
   He never lost an election and had been talked up as a future GOP
candidate for governor or Congress before his legal problems
started.
</TEXT>
