<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Secrets Bjt   07-02 0500</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Secrets, Bjt,0516</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ligachev Reveals Secrets Behind Rise Of Gorbachev</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Yegor K. Ligachev, the No. 2 man in the Kremlin,
provided an unprecedented look into the inner workings of the
Soviet leadership with his description of the events that brought
Mikhail S. Gorbachev to power.
   Ligachev said Friday at the Communist Party conference that
Gorbachev had crucial support from himself, Andrei A. Gromyko and
KGB chief Viktor G. Chebrikov when he became party general
secretary in March 1985. Gromyko, now president, was foreign
minister at the time.
   Ligachev, recounting emotions and experiences in a manner rare
for a member of the traditionally stoic party Politburo, disputed
claims from ousted Moscow Communist Party boss Boris N. Yeltsin
that he had slowed reform.
   He said he had been deeply worried about the fate of the country
during the final days of Leonid I. Brezhnev, who ruled from 1964 to
1982 in a ``time of stagnation.''
   More ``very disquieting days and hours'' came when the party
elite assembled to choose a successor to Konstantin U. Chernenko in
March 1985, Ligachev said.
   ``Fate put me in the center'' of action, he said. ``We could
have made quite different decisions. And, sometimes I think: What
would have happened to the country after that?'' he told the
conference delegates.
   With the support of Chebrikov, Gromyko, Politburo member Mikhail
S. Solomentsev and some regional party leaders, ``the only correct
decision was taken,'' he added.
   Gromyko made the nominating speech proposing Gorbachev as
general secretary after Chernenko's death, but Ligachev's account
was the first to suggest Solomentsev had supported Gorbachev.
   His comments appeared to confirm rumors that circulated at the
time that former Moscow party boss Viktor V. Grishin, an ally of
Chernenko and Brezhnev, had made a last-minute attempt to secure
the leadership.
   Ligachev's statements, which were televised, also could boost
Gromyko and Solomentsev a day after they were criticized by name at
the four-day conference, which ended Friday.
   Gromyko, 78, was foreign minister for 28 years before accepting
the largely ceremonial presidency in July 1985. He and Solomentsev
have sat on the policy-setting Central Committee since the early
1960s.
   ``The country came to a crisis'' before Gorbachev became leader,
Ligachev said. He spoke of corruption, lack of discipline and
alcoholism.
   Because of a lack of frankness, even ``the party was in
danger,'' he said.
   ``All revolutionary parties that died did so because they were
afraid to talk about their weaknesses,'' he said.
   Ligachev spoke of his career during the Brezhnev years.
   ``In the years of stagnation I worked and lived in Siberia,''
said Ligachev, the Communist Party leader in the Siberian city of
Tomsk from 1965-83. ``I say with pride that I built socialism. And
there were millions of such people.''
   Referring with a touch of humor to the Russian practice of
sending misfits and disidents to Siberia, Ligachev said, ``Perhaps
we worked like that because we knew that they wouldn't send us
farther than Siberia.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880702-0009 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-02-88 0018EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Afghanistan Bjt   07-02 0643</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Afghanistan, Bjt,0661</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Commander Says Soviets Not Defeated in Afghanistan</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Soviet-Party, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The commander of Soviet troops in Afghanistan said
they served with honor and were not defeated, but two influential
officials criticized the decision to intervene in the fight against
U.S.-backed rebels.
   ``We came to Afghanistan not to win battles, but to defend women
and children, villages and cities. And we have performed our duty
with honor,'' Lt. Gen. Boris Gromov told the national Communist
Party conference on Friday.
   The Red Army entered in Afghanistan in December 1979, and more
than 100,000 troops were helping the Marxist government fight the
Moslem guerrillas until a withdrawal agreement was signed in April.
   Gromov, who told reporters this week that the Red Army is no
longer taking active part in the fighting, rejected claims that the
Soviet force was beaten.
   Grigory Baklanov, editor of the literary journal Znamya, said
the decision to intervene was made ``in defiance of the machinery
of democracy.'' He said some non-voting members of the ruling
Politburo learned about the decision only by reading the newspapers.
   ``I receive many letters from mothers,'' he said in remarks
broadcast by Soviet television. ``They ask, `How did this happen?
Who supported it?' ''
   Yevgeny Primakov said the decision under late President Leonid
I. Brezhnev was made ``without a proper examination of the possible
alternatives of a political resolution.''
   The remarks by Primakov, head of the Institute of World
Economics and International Relations of the Soviet Academy of
Sciences, were provided by the Tass news agency.
   The discussion of Afghanistan on the fourth and final day of the
conference lacked the sharp character of debates on the bolder news
media, the economy and other issues.
   But coupled with Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev's own
critique and some personal criticism during the conference of
President Andrei A. Gromyko _ the foreign minister for 28 years _
it indicated serious dissatisfaction with the conduct of foreign
policy earlier this decade.
   Soviet military officials have refused to criticize the orders
to fight in Afghanistan, which cost them more than 13,000 dead and
35,000 wounded.
   According to the terms of an April 14 agreement signed in
Geneva, a fifth of the 100,000 Soviet soldiers have left
Afghanistan and the remainder must be gone by Feb. 15, 1989.
   In his opening address to the party conference Tuesday,
Gorbachev praised the soldiers who served in Afghanistan, but the
criticism of Baklanov and Primakov echoed other remarks of
Gorbachev.
   ``It sometimes happened that even decisions of vital importance
were taken by a narrow circle of people without collective,
comprehensive examination of analysis, on occasion without properly
consulting friends either. This led to an inadequate reaction to
international events and to the policies of other states, if not to
mistaken decisions,'' he said.
   The Geneva agreement and withdrawal from Afghanistan ``have
become an international milestone in the political settlement of
regional conflicts, which are fraught with a danger to the world as
a whole and which hinder the progress of the nations,'' Gorbachev
said.
   He said the Soviet Union too often in the past has emphasized
military strength rather than political skill. He has been
extremely critical of the rule of Brezhnev as a period of
stagnation and corruption.
   In an address Thursday, a local party official called for a pair
of officials long influential in foreign affairs to step down
because they had been part of Brezhnev's administration.
   Prompted by Gorbachev to name names, Vladimir I. Melnikov of the
Siberian Komi region called for Gromyko and Georgy Arbatov, head of
the U.S.A.-Canada Institute for the past 21 years, to step down.
   Other Soviet officials in recent months have suggested that the
decision to send soldiers into Afghanistan was a mistake, but their
comments were in less- influential and less-public forums.
</TEXT>
