<FILEID>AP-NR-07-02-88 0133EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Soviet-EastBloc     07-02 0389</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-East Bloc,0401</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Bloc Allies Generally Praise Party Conference</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Soviet-Party, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIOREL URMA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Communist Party conference in Moscow
generally brought praise from Eastern Europe, where the Kremlin's
new policies are pressuring leaders to reform their own countries.
   ``In Poland, in our party, we are deeply satisfied with the
course of the CPSU (Soviet Communist Party) conference,'' said a
commentary of the official Polish news agency PAP. ``With
satisfaction we receive the changes brought by perestroika and new
thinking.''
   Poland and Hungary have gone the farthest in matching or even
exceeding Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev's reforms in the
economy and politics.
   Gorbachev, who closed the four-day conference Friday, will be
paying a six-day visit to Warsaw beginning July 11.
   The ``new thinking'' at the conference ``creates fresh
possibilities of a gradual demilitarization and humanization of
international relations,'' Polish Foreign Ministry spokesman Stefan
Staniszewski told a news conference Thursday.
   In Czechoslovakia, where officials privately say they are
waiting to see whether Gorbachev will strengthen his position at
the conference, the Communist Party daily Rude Pravo said the event
``will be an inspiration and a source of practical enlightment for
us.''
   If the Kremlin leader gets a mandate for more radical reforms,
it would increase pressure on Czechoslovakia's leaders _ installed
after Moscow crushed Gorbachev-like reforms with tanks 20 years ago
_ to adopt political change and to reform economic structure more
quickly.
   ``The ideas ... are worth thinking about,'' Rude Pravo said.
   In Yugoslavia, which broke with Moscow over ideological issues
40 years ago, the state press carried lengthy reports from the
conference describing it as ``historic, dramatic and exceptionally
open.''
   Yugoslav media pointed to Gorbachev's words that there will be
no prosperity for socialism without fundamental and deep
democratization of the Soviet society.
   All the Communist leaderships in Eastern Europe, many of them
now more secretive and orthodox than the modern Kremlin, have
followed the conference debate over the Stalinist past and the need
to open up Communist Party life.
   One exception was Romania, whose leader Nicolae Ceausescu has so
far rejected any need to reform his rigid economic and political
system.
   The Communist Party daily Scinteia carried a four-paragraph
report about the conference opening without any comment and did not
publish any excerpts from Gorbachev's speech.
</TEXT>
