<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Soviet-PartyTV     07-02 0525</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Party TV,0539</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Television Gets into Glasnost Act with Live Interviews</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Soviet-Party, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State-run television interrupted its usual bland
fare for spicy, live interviews after a disgraced leader pleaded
for forgiveness in a dramatic speech at a national Communist Party
conference.
   One delegate told a television correspondent that the conference
discussion about ousted Moscow party chief Boris N. Yeltsin was a
healthy sign that democracy and ``glasnost,'' leader Mikhail S.
Gorbachev's policy of openness, was taking hold.
   ``We can speak our minds openly and directly, without being
afraid of anything,'' said Ivan I. Maximov, a balding metalworker
from the Siberian town of Biisk.
   During a Friday afternoon break in the final session of the
first party conference in 47 years, Soviet television broadcast the
live interviews in the lobby of the Kremlin's Palace of Congresses
with some of the 5,000 delegates.
   Most of the discussion during the broadcast focused on what one
delegate called the highlight of Friday's session of the four-day
conference, the speech by Yeltsin, a former Gorbachev protege.
   ``It's the most heated discussion we have heard in a long
time,'' a gray-haired delegate told the television correspondent.
   A studio anchorman began the 30-minute broadcast and then
switched live to the correspondent on the scene.
   Delegates had just ended floor debate about Yeltsin's speech, in
which he asked to be cleared of blame for criticizing other Soviet
leaders and saying reform was proceeding too slowly.
   The discussion spilled over into the television interviews. Some
delegates told viewers they supported Yeltsin, while others
condemned his remarks as ``politically incorrect.''
   Yeltsin was fired as Moscow party boss and removed from his post
as a non-voting member of the ruling Politburo after a bitter
speech to the party's Central Committee last October, in which he
complained that economic reforms had stalled and asked to be
relieved of his duties. His speech at that meeting has never been
published.
   Maximov, the delegate from Biisk, said it is difficult for
people to make up their minds about whether Yeltsin's criticism was
justified because his Central Committee speech remains secret.
``Glasnost must be deep; then such questions wouldn't arise,'' he
told the television interviewer.
   During the conference, Soviet television and radio provided
periodic newsbriefs with highlights of speeches and live interviews
with delegates.
   The popular evening news program ``Vremya,'' which reportedly
has a nightly audience of tens of millions of Soviets, departed
from its usual fare of dull reports about the latest beet harvest
or other economic achievement to carry extensive coverage on the
party conference.
   The nightly program normally runs 45 minutes but Friday it
continued for three hours with extensive clips of Yeltsin's address
and remarks by his critics.
   Videotape showed Yeltsin appealing for political rehabilitation,
and when there was a roar from the delegates Gorbachev waved his
hands and asked that Yeltsin be allowed to continue.
   ``Vremya'' directors apparently felt the Yeltsin issue was so
important that they continued showing the taped reports even after
Gorbachev began his speech closing the conference. Soviet radio
carried Gorbachev's speech live and Vremya later broadcast a
recording.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
