<HEAD>Names In The News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COSTA MESA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Teen pop star Tiffany, about to embark
on her first world tour, says that unlike many sudden success
stories, her career has not gone to her head.
   ``I'm real cautious about staying a regular teen-ager,'' said
Tiffany, 16, who is scheduled to perform here Saturday night at the
Pacific Amphitheatre.
   With 5 million copies of her first album sold and a second album
on the way, it's easy to see how a young singer could get heady.
   ``I've had other friends who hit it big with a record or
something, and they changed completely. I don't want that to happen
to me,'' she said recently.
   Tiffany, who recently petitioned a court to have herself legally
recognized as an adult, withdrew the petition in an out-of-court
settlement with her mother. However, a legal battle between her
mother and manager is still being waged over who will control the
teen's growing fortune.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SOUTH BURLINGTON, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John Zaccaro Jr. has begun his
four-month house arrest for selling a quarter-gram of cocaine to an
undercover officer.
   Zaccaro, the 24-year-old son of former vice presidential
candidate Geraldine Ferraro, was booked Friday at Chittenden
Community Correctional Center and then left to begin Vermont's
special house arrest program for non-violent criminals.
   Zaccaro will live in a state-approved apartment during the
sentence. He will not be allowed to consume alcohol and must
request permission to have visitors.
   In addition to the four-month sentence, Zaccaro was ordered to
serve 300 hours of community service and pay a $1,500 fine.
   Zaccaro was arrested two years ago after selling $25 worth of
cocaine to an undercover officer at Middlebury College, where he
was a student at the time. Zaccaro's lawyers plan to appeal his
conviction to the Vermont Supreme Court.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>OLYMPIA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Booth Gardner has his own version of
independence to celebrate this July 4th weekend.
   The governor and his wife, Jean, are giving away their daughter,
Gail, in marriage.
   Ms. Gardner, 24, was to become the bride of John Nettleton, 24,
of Albany, N.Y., in a wedding today at the Raynor Chapel at Annie
Wright School in Tacoma. Ms. Gardner attended Annie Wright for
eight years. A reception was planned follow at the governor's
mansion in Olympia.
   Ms. Gardner and Nettleton met while they were undergraduates at
Dartmouth College in New Hampshire.
   Nettleton, who is working on the Gardner re-election campaign,
plans to enter law school this fall. Ms. Gardner is completing work
on a graduate degree in education at the University of Washington.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Canadian who claims Eddie Murphy's new
``Coming to America'' movie was based on his idea has filed a $10
million copyright lawsuit against the actor, two writers and
Paramount Studios.
   Shelby M. Gregory, 38, now living in Hollywood, said he filed
the U.S. District Court suit because Murphy and the two writers
allegedly used his ideas without compensation.
   Robert Wachs, Murphy's manager, said Friday he had not seen the
suit, but denied any wrongdoing. ``It's Murphy's story,'' Wachs
said.
   Murphy was reported to be unavailable for comment and Paramount
Pictures spokeswoman Deborah Rosen said the studio does not comment
on lawsuits.
   The suit states that Lassine Ousseni, a Nigerian who claimed to
be an actor-producer, offered Gregory $5,000 in 1983 to write a
treatment, or detailed outline, and a story. Gregory said he
registered a federal copyright for the completed ``Toto, The
African Prince.''
   Gregory was never paid, according to the suit filed Wednesday.
   Ousseni then submitted a redrafted copy of the work to Murphy in
1986, which Murphy rejected, the suit says.
   Murphy and the two writers eventually turned out a screenplay
that became ``Coming to America,'' the suit alleges.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Peter Garrett, lead singer for the
Australian rock group Midnight Oil, says his 11-year-old band is
finally making it big in America after passing up a chance at
national exposure six years ago.
   In 1982, Midnight Oil turned down an offer to be the opening act
on The Who's farewell tour, partly because Garrett and his five
fellow band members didn't approve of the tour's sponsorship by a
beer company, Schlitz.
   ``We had never been sponsored by anyone and we never will,''
Garrett said. ``We can't understand why someone who's already
famous and wealthy would turn their faces and names over to a
drinks company or whatever.''
   Midnight Oil, which played here Friday night, is on the American
charts now with its million-selling album ``Diesel And Dust'' and
the hit single ``Beds Are Burning,'' which champions the rights of
Australia's aborigines.
   ``We believe in the human potential to organize and resolve
problems. We believe in hope,'' said Garrett, a 35-year-old former
lawyer whose 6-foot-5 frame and clean-shaven head make him an
atypical rock star.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Although probable presidential candidate Gov.
Michael Dukakis is still shopping for a Democratic running mate,
his wife, Kitty, has already made her choice for the convention.
   She's selected a three-piece silk suit by Boston designer David
Josef.
   Mrs. Dukakis also will wear several other outfits by Josef, 31,
during the Democratic National Convention in Atlanta July 18-21.
   ``Kitty is an issue-oriented woman and her approach to fashion
is more casual,'' said Josef, whose original name is Joseph
Prignano. ``Fashion is not the be-all and end-all to her and I
respect her for that. Mrs. (Nancy) Reagan is very fashion-first.''
   Josef would not disclose the price for Mrs. Dukakis' outfits.
His designs normally sell for $300 to $770 in stores such as Neiman
Marcus and Saks Fifth Avenue.
   Mrs. Dukakis left Massachusetts General Hospital last month
wearing one of Josef's jackets after undergoing spinal surgery.
</TEXT>
