<FILEID>AP-NR-07-02-88 0217EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Reagan-Drought     07-02 0357</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-Drought,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lyng Says Government Wants to Help Distressed Farmers</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Agriculture Secretary Richard Lyng says the
government will likely extend ``a helping hand'' to
drought-stricken farmers as soon as there's a solid assessment of
crop damage.
   But Lyng said despite stark evidence of the havoc wreaked by the
dry spell, ``I think it would be premature to start putting dollars
up there.''
   After briefing President Reagan on the findings of an
interagency task force on the drought, the secretary told reporters
Friday that long-range weather forecasts are discouraging.
   ``We did have some showers in the last few days that helped in
some places and the weather's cooler, so those are good signs,'' he
said, ``but the weather forecasts indicate that it (the drought)
has not broken and is continuing and is still very, very serious.''
   Meanwhile, it was disclosed by a senior administration official
that Reagan will fly to Davenport, Iowa, July 14 to view drought
damage.
   Lyng, who heads a drought-relief task force Reagan set up last
month, said that ``sooner or later I suspect that the Congress and
the administration will see that we need to help with money if the
thing continues as bad as it's been. Just how you do that is very
complex.''
   Lyng would not speculate on whether aid money might be available
from the roughly $17 billion in the commodity price support
payments the administration requested for the new budget year
starting Oct. 1. There had been indications that because of the
drought, not all of the $17 billion would be needed for subsidies
and that the excess money might be used for aid purposes.
   ``To get into writing checks to farmers for relief to help tide
them over almost needs to await the normal harvest period so that
they can compare what they are harvesting, what happened to them,''
he said. ``At that time, we should be standing there with a helping
hand.''
   It was the fourth briefing that Lyng has given Reagan, who
established the task force in mid-June to recommend steps the
government can take.
</TEXT>
