<FILEID>AP-NR-07-02-88 0220EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-CNWStrike     07-02 0401</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CNW Strike,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Emergency Board Proposes Compromise To Avert Strike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID FOX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A presidential panel trying to resolve a
dispute between the Chicago & Northwestern Transportation Co. and
one of its unions is offering a compromise that would preserve some
jobs and prevent a threatened strike.
   The White House released a 29-page report late Friday in which
an emergency board said both sides should make sacrifices.
   The report also recommended arbitration if the nation's
eighth-largest railroad and the United Transportation Union cannot
agree on specific personnel cuts.
   At issue is a CNW proposal to eliminate the jobs of 1,050 UTU
brakemen by cutting the size of its train crews from four to two
workers _ an engineer and conductor _ in most cases.
   Spokeswoman Leslie Cleveland said Chicago & Northwestern could
save about $51 million a year by reducing manpower, calling it a
necessary step to remain competitive.
   However, the union characterized the cuts affecting half its CNW
members as a contract violation and demanded no change from the
status quo.
   It threatened to strike on April 22, prompting President Reagan
to appoint the emergency board under the Railway Labor Act.
   ``The carrier, unlike many of the other railroads in the
industry, has an economic need for relief from its present
crew-consist rules. ...,'' the board said. ``This is not to say
that the employees, alone, should be expected to bear the burden.''
   Although the board said CNW should be allowed to eliminate one
brakemen per train, it recommended that further reductions be
decided by an arbitration board case-by-case.
   The panel also said CNW should be able to terminate some workers
if not enough accept voluntary separation allowances. But it also
recommended raising the railroad's proposed $25,000 allowance to
$50,000 for employees leaving voluntarily and $45,000 for those
forced into separation.
   Company officials said they had not seen the report and had no
immediate comment Friday.
   Donald F. Markgraf, the union's general chairman, said: ``These
things work out in strange ways sometimes. We're still hoping for a
settlement.''
   A strike cannot begin before 12:01 a.m. Aug. 4, said Roland
Watkins, an administrative assistant to the emergency board.
   Chicago & Northwestern ranks eighth among U.S. railroads in
revenue and handled nearly 1.5 million carloads of traffic in 1986.
It also provides the principal daily rail service for about 40,000
commuters in the Chicago area.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
