<DOCNO> AP880702-0022 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-02-88 0227EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-DefenseProbe-Chappell     07-02 0542</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Defense Probe-Chappell,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Martin-Marietta Says It Bought Club</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense contractor Martin Marietta Corp. says
it bought a Florida health club once owned in part by a congressman
who chairs a military appropriations subcommittee because the
purchase ``appears to have been a good investment.''
   Martin Marietta disclosed Friday it bought the club in Ocala
little more than a year after a company executive and other
partners reportedly rescued Rep. Bill Chappell from foreclosure on
the property.
   Martin Marietta issued a statement saying that a company
subsidiary bought Fun and Fitness of Ocala Inc., on May 30, 1986,
for $200,000 ``from a group of five private investors who had
purchased the property for $175,000'' in a bank foreclosure process.
   The company said the corporation was aware at the time that
Chappell, D-Fla., ``had held a prior interest in the racquet club.''
   One of the five private investors had been George L. Dalferes,
vice president of government affairs at Martin Marietta
headquarters in Bethesda, Md., just outside Washington.
   Martin Marietta said its purchase ``appears to have been a good
investment because the property has a market value in excess of the
purchase price.''
   Chappell said Friday he had kept an ``arm's length'' away from
the transaction in which the investors, all representatives of
defense contractors, reportedly intervened for him.
   Chappell, chairman of the House Appropriations defense
subcommittee, refused to discuss details of the complex
transaction, reported Friday by The Washington Post.
   But in a statement issued by his office, he said: ``If you are
going to do something wrong, you don't do it on the public record.
This entire transaction is a matter of public record. It has been
since its inception several years ago.''
   Chappell has said he is not a target in the ongoing criminal
investigation of Pentagon weapons-buying. That investigation
involves allegations that defense contractors and consultants, many
of them former military men, bribed Pentagon officials for
contracting details that could be vital in winning contracts worth
billions of dollars.
   The Post reported that the Racquet Club of Ocala Inc. intervened
in late 1984 to cancel Chappell's and his partner's personal
liability for a large part of their indebtedness and also removed
the two men as defendants in a suit related to the health club's
foreclosure.
   The principal officers of Racquet Club of Ocala were Leonard
Killgore and Dalferes. Killgore, a former Chappell aide, was then
an official with the Washington office of Avco Corp., a rocket
builder, the newspaper said.
   A Florida court had ruled in November 1984 that Chappell and his
partner, William W. Austin, personally had guaranteed some $172,000
of the overall obligation in the failed club, the Post said.
   The December 1984 settlement resulted in Killgore and his
investment partners obtaining the health club and its properties
for $175,000, Chappell's statement noted.
   Chappell's statement said: ``This property was appraised by the
bank at $425,000. According to public record, the purchaser sold
the property for at least a $20,000 profit 13 months later.''
   ``There was absolutely no benefit to me either way,'' he said.
``The transaction changed no legal responsibilities with reference
to Bill Chappell, no consideration of any sort passed to Bill
Chappell. It was an arm's length transaction, as supported by
public record.''
</TEXT>
