<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SriLanka 1stLd-Writethru   07-02 0578</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sri Lanka, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0438,0593</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tamil Sources Say Negotiations Stalled</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: INSERTS two grafs after 13th, `Neither the...' to UPDATE with
deaths. Pick up 14th pvs, `The Tamil...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tamil militants in Sri Lanka are ready
to surrender, but negotiations have stalled because the rebels are
demanding $38.4 million from the Indian government, Tamil sources
said.
   Sources close to the rebels in Colombo, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said Friday the militants were not willing to allow
monitoring of how the money was spent.
   In the southern Indian city of Madras, Sadasivam Krishnakumar, a
senior member of the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam, was quoted
as saying the group was willing to surrender but awaited final
orders from its commander.
   The Tigers, the largest rebel group in Sri Lanka, have been at
the forefront of the five-year guerrilla war with the ethnic
Sinhalese-dominated government for an independent Tamil homeland.
   India, which has 50,000 peacekeeping troops in Sri Lanka, has
been trying to negotiate an end to the separatist war in the
neighboring island nation.
   The Sri Lankan government on Thursday offered amnesty to the
rebels and promised to conduct provincial elections by the end of
July in northern and eastern Sri Lanka, where the rebels want a
separate homeland.
   The United News of India quoted Krishnakumar as telling
reporters in Madras that the Tigers would participate in the
provincial elections.But he said no decision had been made on
whether the Tigers' organization would participate in the elections
itself or would form a new political party, the news agency said.
   It quoted Krishnakumar as saying the Tigers would hand over
their weapons as soon as an agreement was reached on the timing of
a surrender and the number of arms to be given up.
   He also said a final decision would be taken only after
consultations with the Tigers' commander, Velupillai Prabhakaran.
   Prabhakaran is based in Sri Lanka and has successfully eluded a
series of manhunts by Indian troops.
   Last July 29, India and Sri Lanka signed a peace accord aimed at
ending the ethnic warfare in the island nation off India's southern
coast. The Tigers accepted the accord but reneged in October.
   The accord was accompanied by a payment of $384,600 by the
Indian government to the rebels for rehabilitation of people
affected by the fighting.
   Since October, more than 400 Indian soldiers have been killed in
ambushes and battles with the Tamil rebels, according to the Indian
government.
   Neither the Indians nor the Tamils have estimated the number of
rebel deaths.
   In the latest reported violence, seven Indian soldiers were
killed in two ambushes Thursday, said Sri Lankan military officials
who spoke on condition of anonymity. They said four were killed
near Trincomalee, 150 miles north of Colombo; and three were killed
near Vavuniya, 110 miles north of Colombo.
   Two Tamils were killed in Vavuniya during search operations
launched Friday by the Indians, the officials said.
   The Tamil insurgency grew out of the belief the community was
being discriminated against by the Sinhalese ethnic majority, which
controls the country's government and armed forces.
   Tamils comprise 18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million people and
the Sinhalese form 75 percent. Most Tamils are Hindus, like the
majority of Indians, while most Sinhalese are Buddhists.
   India became involved in the Sri Lankan ethnic strife because of
the sympathies of its own 60 million Tamils to the rebel cause.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880702-0025 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-02-88 0248EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Brazil-Constitution     07-02 0689</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Brazil-Constitution,0715</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>Brazil Steeps its New Constitution in Controversy
^By JORGE MEDEROS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   National lawmakers are preparing
for final voting on the draft of a new constitution that would
reject sweeping land reform but liberalize work rules and end
foreign control of mining.
   The new charter for South America's largest country would also
give President Jose Sarney and his successors a five-year term, a
victory for the national leader.
   The proposed document was born in five months of heated debate
in the Congress, doubling as a Constitutional Convention. It has
come up 235 articles that will be the basis for the eighth
constitution in the 166 years of Brazil's independence from
Portugal.
   The final round of voting is expected to start near the end of
July. But the document appears largely to have assumed its final
form because a hefty 280 votes in the 559-member convention would
be needed to change it.
   The convention, made up of representatives and senators picked
in free elections in 1986, began rewriting the current
constitution, dictated during a 1964-1985 military regime, in
February 1987.
   The project started with a computer-generated document touching
nearly every aspect of life imaginable in this country of about 140
million people. It then progressed to a first draft of more than
3,000 articles, which critics derided as an ``encyclopedia.''
   The real paring began last February with article-by-article
voting, in which a majority of 280 was needed for approval.
Lawmakers debated vociferously, sometimes violently, especially
about issues like land reform, workers' rights and the role of
foreign capital.
   Other hotly contested matters involved how long Sarney, the
civilian who assumed office in 1985, should stay there; and whether
Brazil should have a U.S.-type presidential form of government or a
European-style prime minister system.
   As it stands, the proposed constitution contains these
provisions:
   _ Sarney and future presidents will serve for five years,
compared to the six years of former military presidents. The
presidential system remains in place.
   _ Wide-ranging land reform, in a country where 4 percent of the
people own 50 percent of the farmable land, was rejected.
   _ Workers appear headed for a shorter work week and more liberal
vacation benefits. But a liberal maternity leave program might not
survive the final vote because businesses view it as too expensive.
   _ Foreign companies involved in mining will have to leave Brazil
in four years or transfer financial control to residents of the
country.
   _ Risk contracts allowing foreign companies to drill for oil
probably won't be continued.
   _ The return of legalized casino gambling was rejected.
   The biggest fight broke out between Sarney and convention
members over the length of the presidential term.
   Tancredo Neves, a moderate who said he wanted only four years as
president before holding elections, died before taking office in
1985. Brazil's last presidential election was in 1960. Sarney, vice
president-elect and former chief of the military regime's official
party, moved into the presidency.
   He made it clear he believed he had inherited the six-year term
of his military predecessor, Gen. Joao Figueiredo, but said he
would consider stepping down after five years.
   However, many congressmen wanted Sarney out after four years,
with presidential elections in November 1988.
   Sarney won his five years in the constitutional debating, but at
the cost of splitting his Brazilian Democratic Movement party.
   Various groups are still seeking changes in the final form of
the document.
   A conservative block, known as the ``Big Center,'' is trying to
gain support to strike the anti-foreign articles involving mining
and oil prospecting and a proposition allowing civil servants
strike under certain circumstances.
   Leftists, including members of Brazil's two small Communist
parties, want to try to knock out conservative provisions on land
reform and one that lets civilian powers call in the armed forces
to deal with internal problems.
   There is no time limit for the last round of debate.
   But Rep. Ulysses Guimaraes, speaker of Brazil's House and
president of the constitutional convention, says he would like
officially to proclaim the new constitution on Sept. 7, the
national holiday that commemmorates independence.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
