<1ST_LINE>u w PM-DefenseProbe-Glance     07-02 0415</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Defense Probe-Glance,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Highlights of Developments in The Defense Probe</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Defense Probe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are some of the major developments Friday
in the investigation of Defense Department procurement practices.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>PAYMENTS SUSPENDED</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary Frank Carlucci, declaring ``we do not need to
wait (for) convictions, or even trials,'' in the Pentagon
procurement affair, suspended payment on $1 billion worth of
potentially tainted military contracts.
   Carlucci acted on the basis of information included in
search-warrant affidavits that were unsealed by a federal
magistrate in Dallas on Thursday. In the documents, the FBI said it
eavesdropped as one consultant obtained and passed along inside
information on nine contracts worth more than $522 million. They
heard a Navy procurement official read off 10 sealed bids in a $120
million contract.
   Carlucci also announced that the Pentagon was beginning
suspension procedures against three individuals and a company named
in the documents.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>CONGRESSMAN COMMENTS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   Rep. Bill Chappell said he had kept an ``arm's length'' away
from a transaction in which a company headed by representatives of
defense contractors reportedly intervened for him in a foreclosure
case. Chappell, chairman of the House Appropriations defense
subcommittee, refused to discuss details of the complex transaction.
   But in a statement issued by his office, the Florida Democrat
said, ``If you are going to do something wrong, you don't do it on
the public record. This entire transaction is a matter of public
record. It has been since its inception several years ago.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>DEFENSE CONTRACTOR REVEALS PURCHASE</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   Martin Marietta Corp., a defense contractor, says it bought Fun
and Fitness of Ocala Inc. little more than a year after a company
executive and other partners reportedly rescued Chappell from
foreclosure on the property. The company said the corporation was
aware at the time that Chappell, ``had held a prior interest in the
racquet club'' but said the purchase ``appears to have been a good
investment.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>PAISLEY AFFIDAVITS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   Defense consultant Melvyn Paisley went to court in a bid to
obtain the affidavit secretly filed by government investigators to
search his office for evidence in the Pentagon bribery probe.
Paisley's lawyers asked U.S. District Judge John H. Pratt to
expedite consideration of their motion, saying they needed the
affidavit to help advise their client on how to comply with
``numerous subpoenas'' issued in the case. The Justice Department,
meanwhile, took steps to ensure that no additional affidavits or
search warrants are disclosed in the Pentagon bribery probe.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
