<1ST_LINE>r w PM-ArtificialHeart Bjt 1stLd-Writethru 07-02 0570</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Artificial Heart, Bjt, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0428,540</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS lede to correct verb tense; SUBS last graf to indicate
which Jarvik-7 heart patients have died</NOTE>
<HEAD>Government To Continue Program To Develop Artificial Heart</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Institutes of Health plans to
continue a $20 million artificial heart research program that had
been scheduled to be shelved in the fall, according to Senate and
administration officials.
   The reversal means that research contracts at centers in six
states won't be halted at the end of September, but rather will
continue for about 5{ years as originally planned. The program's
goal is to develop a totally implantable electric heart.
   The National Heart, Lung and Blood Institute, part of NIH, said
in May that it was suspending the program at the end of the fiscal
year and shifting its focus instead to developing a left
ventricular assist device, which would help a diseased heart pump
blood.
   The decision provoked an outcry from senators in the states
where the research centers are located. They called the decision
``an alarming U-turn'' and said the artificial heart program was a
key component of the nation's leadership in biotechnology.
   Sens. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, and Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., had
threatened in a letter to insert an amendment into an
appropriations bill to compel the heart, lung and blood institute
to continue the contracts prior to undertaking new obligations.
   Word that the contracts were being revived first came from
Hatch, who relayed the news to a Utah center with a $5.5 million
contract at stake.
   ``We heard and confirmed that the contract had been reinstated
as of the end of the fiscal year, so that there will be no
(funding) break,'' Roger Bliss of the University of Utah's
Institute for Biomedical Engineering said in a telephone interview
Friday.
   ``It was originally announced by Senator Hatch and confirmed
through our contacts at NIH,'' Bliss said.
   Hatch told The Deseret News in Utah that he was told by Claude
Lenfant, director of the NIH institute, that artificial heart
funding was being restored. Hatch called the decision ``good news
for the millions who will need artificial hearts or their
components.''
   There has been no announcement yet by NIH that the program is
being resumed.
   However, an NIH official speaking on condition of anonymity
said, ``The practicality is that a decision has been made'' and
that an announcement was expected as soon as next week.
   The official stressed that the decision was not just a quick
fix, and that it was anticipated that the program would continue as
originally planned.
   Besides the University of Utah, the other centers conducting the
research are the Hershey Medical Center of Pennsylvania State
University; Abiomed Inc. of Danvers, Mass., which is working with
the Texas Heart Institute of Houston; and the Nimbus Co. of Rancho
Cordova, Calif., which is working with the Cleveland Clinic in Ohio.
   The contracts begin early this year. In announcing that the
pacts were being suspended, the NIH institute cited budgetary
constraints and said it was not abandoning the total artificial
heart concept.
   So far, all five patients who received the Jarvik-7 artificial
heart as a permanent implantation have died within two years. The
Jarvik-7 runs on compressed air and uses a portable power pack or
other external machine. The program temporarily suspended by NIH is
for development of an electric, totally implantable heart.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
