<HEAD>Reagan To Nominate Stalon To Additional Time On FERC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The White House has announced that President
Reagan intends to nominate Charles Stalon, a holdover member of the
Federal Energy Regulatory Commission, to serve additional time on
the commission.
   Stalon, 58, filled an unexpired term when he came to the
commission in 1984. That term ran out last October, but the law
permits him to stay on for a year as long as no successor has been
sworn in.
   Friday's announcement said Stalon, who fills one of the two
mandatory Democratic seats, would fill the remainder of Michael
Naeve's term which would have expired in October 1989 had he not
resigned in March.
   The commission's membership remains uncertain because Martha O.
Hesse has not been confirmed as chairman a year after her
nomination, Anthony Sousa has resigned effective later this month
and Charles Trabandt's term expires in October.
