<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Peru-Violence     07-02 0197</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Peru-Violence,0203</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police-Rebel Shootout on Bus Kills Three</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maoist guerrillas and police fought a
gunbattle aboard an interstate bus carrying 80 passengers, killing
three people, police said.
   A policeman, a Shining Path rebel and a bus passenger were
killed and another policeman was wounded in Friday's shootout,
police said.
   The violence occurred before dawn on Peru's major coastal route
near Pisco, 135 miles south of Lima. The bus was traveling along
the Pan American Highway to Lima from Ica, 180 miles south.
   Police said six Shining Path guerrillas forced the privately
owned bus to stop by firing machine guns into the air and boarded
the vehicle, demanding to see the passengers' papers.
   The bus riders dived for cover behind their seats as two
policemen passengers opened fire. The rebels fired back and fled
moments later.
   Maoist guerrillas frequently halt buses and steal passengers'
valuables as an ``insurgency tax.'' The rebels normally check
documents and kill any police or government officials they find.
   The government says nearly 600 policemen have been among the
more than 10,000 people slain in violence related to the Shining
Path's eight-year fight to impose Marxist rule in Peru.
</TEXT>
