<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Obit-Barbosa     07-02 0418</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Barbosa,0434</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Popular Brazilian Television Star Was Known for Wild Antics</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE HANDLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Abelardo Barbosa, a free-wheeling
comic who liked to say his goal was to confuse everything but who
worked to forge a distinctly Brazilian style of television, died of
a heart attack. He was 70.
   Barbosa, known on his amateur hour as ``Chacrinha,'' or barnyard
in Portuguese, succumbed at his home in Rio de Janeiro late
Thursday, his family announced Friday. He had been ill for several
months.
   His body lay in state Friday at City Hall, where hundreds of
fans and well-wishers, mostly poor, lined up to pay respects. Riot
police took positions outside to prevent any emotional tumult among
mourners.
   The entertainer was born in Brazil's poor northeast region and
graduated from medical school there. But he never practiced as a
doctor, gravitating in the 1940s to Rio de Janeiro and radio. He
became a disc jockey and emcee.
   The entertainer delighted generations of Brazilian radio and
television fans with his own brand of unpredictable antics.
   When television came to Brazil in the 1960s, Barbosa became a
legend with a amateur show called ``Chacrinha's Horn.''
   His nonsense slogans and silly rhymes caught on throughout the
country. Media critics said he represented the essence of
``Brazilian-ness'' and prevented television here from turning into
an American clone.
   In a rare serious moment in an interview years ago, Barbosa said
he felt he had brought a certain Brazilian originality to
television, which he viewed as subject to foreign _ mostly American
_ influence.
   On ``Chacrinha's Horn,'' Chacrinha, an overweight man with thick
glasses and curly, white hair, generally sported an outlandish
outfit making him look like a clown. If he did not appreciate
performers, he would honk a horn in their faces and send them away
in disgrace, prompting thunderous laughter from the audience.
   The program also highlighted Brazil's leading pop music singers
and rock groups. Go-go girls gyrated in the background, smoke bombs
exploded on stage, and cameras cut crazily from one shot to another
with no apparent logic.
   ``I've come here to confuse everything,'' he often said in
nose-tight closeups, and the phrase caught on nationwide.
   He also delighted fans with such gratuitous behavior as
brandishing a pineapple or a slab of dried codfish and taunting the
audience: ``Who wants this?''
   ``Me, me,'' everyone would shout.
   ``Well, you can't have it. This stuff's expensive,'' he would
retort and lob the item out of reach.
</TEXT>
