<1ST_LINE>r a PM-VesselSeized     07-02 0372</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Vessel Seized,0384</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Coast Guard Seizes Ship Off Washington Coast With Marijuana Aboard</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREA BLANDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Panamanian ship believed to be carrying more
than 50 tons of marijuana was under tow today after the Coast Guard
opened fire on the vessel, boarded it and arrested the crew, the
Coast Guard said.
   The ``Encounter Bay,'' a 180-foot converted oil-drilling vessel,
was seized Thursday after it refused to stop and was expected to
reach Seattle on Wednesday, Coast Guard spokesman Lt. Eldo DeLong
said Friday.
   A patrolling Coast Guard C-130 aircraft spotted the ship
Thursday several hundred miles off the Washington coast in
international waters, said Coast Guard spokesman Petty Officer 1st
Class Craig Herlihy.
   The ship's home port on the stern was partly covered with white
paint, DeLong said.
   Because the vessel was suspicious-looking, the U.S. State
Department contacted the Panamanian embassy and got permission to
board the ship and enforce U.S. laws, DeLong said.
   Crew members aboard the Coast Guard cutter ``Boutwell'' tried to
contact the master of the vessel by radio, flag hoist, and waving,
Herlihy said. When those methods failed, the Boutwell fired 60
rounds of .50-caliber bullets into the vessel's engine room. No one
was injured, and there was no further resistance, he said.
   Damage to the vessel was minimal, DeLong said.
   Coast Guard crew members then boarded the vessel and immediately
found four containers of marijuana on deck, DeLong said.
   ``There is believed to be in excess of 50 tons of marijuana
(aboard),'' Lt. Paul Ferguson said.
   The seizure, worth an estimated $220 million, is one of the
largest ever for the Coast Guard, Herlihy said. Authorities in 1985
seized 160 tons of marijuana off the coast of Virginia.
   All the crew members on board were arrested, DeLong said, adding
that he did not know how many crew members there were.
   The crew members will be taken into U.S. Customs custody when
the vessel arrives in port, Ferguson said. Coast Guard, Customs and
drug enforcement officials will examine the ship and its cargo.
   The Coast Guard began towing the ship Thursday night, and
Herlihy estimated the vessels would be traveling at six to eight
knots, or seven to 10 mph.
</TEXT>
