<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PaisleyProbe     07-02 0478</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Paisley Probe,0491</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Assistant Navy Secretary Paisley Target Of '83 FBI Probe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense fraud scandal figure Melvyn R.
Paisley was the subject of an FBI probe while he was assistant Navy
secretary in 1983 that examined allegations of bribery and
electronic eavesdropping, the Los Angeles Times reported today.
   However, a U.S. attorney declined to prosecute Paisley following
the probe that covered a time when he was an executive for the
Boeing Company, the newspaper reported in today's editions.
   Paisley's attorney, E. Lawrence Barcella Jr., dismissed the
report as ``a regurgitation of unfounded allegations that have been
examined many times.''
   According to the Times, Paisley's main accuser was James E.
Durst, who was an executive with Paisley at the Boeing Co. Durst,
who left Boeing in 1977, said he told the FBI that Paisley
presented ``an extraordinary risk to the security of the United
States.''
   The FBI presented its findings on Paisley's activities while at
Boeing to then-U.S. Attorney Elsie Munsell, whose Alexandria, Va.,
office is heading a nationwide investigation into defense
procurement fraud.
   The newspaper, citing an unidentified source familiar with the
investigation, said Ms. Munsell declined to prosecute Paisley in
part because the statute of limitations on the electronic
eavesdropping, which allegedly took place in 1970, had expired.
   She also declined to prosecute, the source said, because Boeing,
on whose behalf Paisley had allegedly paid bribes, had already
pleaded guilty to charges of failing to disclose at least $7
million in commissions it paid to overseas agents to help win
airline orders.
   Paisley, who has worked as a consultant since he left his Navy
post last year, is one of the central figures in the ongoing
defense procurement fraud probe. Federal investigators contend that
after leaving the Pentagon, Paisley obtained classified information
about defense contracts and sold it to his clients.
   Ms. Munsell declined to discuss the investigations conducted
during her five-year tenure as U.S. attorney.
   Henry E. Hudson, who succeeded her in 1986, and who is managing
the Pentagon fraud investigation, also declined to comment.
   Barcella, who had worked as a federal prosecutor for 16 years,
minimized the significance of FBI agents presenting their
investigation of Paisley to a U.S. attorney.
   ``That doesn't necessarily indicate the FBI thought there was a
case,'' he said. ``There were thousands of petty things agents came
to me with.''
   Barcella also described Durst as ``a disgruntled former employee
whose record on credibility is pretty thin.''
   In addition to naming Paisley, Durst also implicated James E.
Gaines, Paisley's aide at Boeing, in a three-page letter dated Oct.
10, 1983, that he sent to the FBI.
   Gaines, who also worked for Paisley as a deputy at the Pentagon,
is accused of supplying classified material to Paisley when the
former Navy official left the service to become a defense
consultant, according to sources close to the investigation.
</TEXT>
