<HEAD>Paisley Seeks to See Government Evidence</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Defense Probe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense consultant Melvyn Paisley has gone to
court to get the affidavit secretly filed by federal investigators
to search his office for evidence in the Pentagon bribery probe.
   Paisley's lawyers in their request Friday for U.S. District
Judge John H. Pratt to expedite consideration of their motion said
they needed the affidavit to help advise their client on how to
comply with ``numerous subpoenas'' issued in the case. Those
subpoenas are due on July 19, according to the court papers.
   E. Lawrence Barcella and Robert Plotkin, attorneys representing
Paisley and his wife, Vicki, asked Pratt to convene a July 8
hearing to consider their request to obtain the supporting
affidavit.
   ``Additionally, the massive and pervasive publicity given this
matter already may have irreparably tainted the decision-making
process of the grand jury and seal may prevent further taint,'' the
lawyers said in asking the judge to keep under seal their detailed
request to see the affidavit.
   In a related development, The Los Angeles Times reported in
today's editions that sources have told the newspaper Paisley was
the subject of a 1983 FBI probe that examined allegations of
bribery and electronic eavesdropping.
   The newspaper, citing an unidentified source familiar with the
1983 investigation, said then-U.S. Attorney Elsie Munsell declined
to prosecute Paisley following the probe in part because the
statute of limitations on the electronic eavesdropping, which
allegedly took place in 1970, had expired.
   She also declined to prosecute, the source said, because the
Boeing Company, on whose behalf Paisley had allegedly paid bribes,
had already pleaded guilty to charges of failing to disclose at
least $7 million in commissions it paid to overseas agents to help
win airline orders.
   Both Ms. Munsell and Henry E. Hudson, who succeeded her in 1986
and is now managing the Pentagon fraud investigation declined
comment.
   Barcella dismissed the report as ``a regurgitation of unfounded
allegations that have been examined many times.''
   The Justice Department, meanwhile, took steps to ensure that no
additional affidavits or search warrants are disclosed in the
Pentagon bribery probe.
   Most of the affidavits which the FBI is required to submit to
justify a search remain sealed. But two were released Thursday by a
U.S. magistrate in Dallas. They reveal that court-ordered wiretaps
and office bugging devices captured the relay of confidential,
inside information on nine defense contracts worth more than $522
million.
   The magistrate in Dallas released the two affidavits because the
government had asked that they remain sealed for 14 days, until
June 30.
   The government also has opposed a motion by United Technologies
and Eugene Tallia, head of Pratt & Whitney's Washington offices, to
allow them and their legal counsel to view an affidavit that
supported a search warrant for the offices. The facilities were
searched June 14. The search focused on the relationship between
Tallia and two consultants, Paisley and William Galvin.
   The government's request, also filed Friday in U.S. District
Court, said that to disclose any but small portions of the
affidavit would jeopardize an ongoing criminal investigation.
   The affidavit pertaining to Paisley has been kept under court
seal since federal investigators obtained the warrant to search
Paisley Associates, Inc. in Washington on June 14.
   His lawyers said that unless they have an opportunity to inspect
the affidavit, they ``will be substantially hindered and delayed in
providing effective advice and representation to applicant and in
determining the appropriate response to the subpoenas and to the
propriety of the search warrant.''
   Paisley, a former assistant Navy secretary for research, left
the Pentagon in 1987 to become a consultant to several defense
contractors.
   Paisley's telephone has been tapped and his consulting office
bugged during much of the two-year investigation.
   Federal authorities this week opposed another request to unseal
an unrelated search-warrant affidavit in New York City on the
grounds that evidence sought in the case had been destroyed before
it could be examined by investigators.
   Justice Department spokesman Patrick Korten said that ``we'll
double-check and make sure we don't encounter similar problems'' in
other courts around the country containing more than 40 sealed
search warrants and affidavits that are part of the investigation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
