<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-MTM     07-02 0377</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-MTM,0387</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>British TV Company Reportedly Buying MTM</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Television South PLC, a British production
company, has agreed to buy MTM Entertainment Inc., an independent
U.S. company co-founded by actress Mary Tyler Moore, in a deal
worth about $325 million, a newspaper reported.
   The British company, known as TVS, said it could neither confirm
nor deny Friday's report in the Financial Times, but said its chief
executive James Gatward would make a statement at a news conference
here on July 6.
   The Financial Times said the deal was struck in London on
Thursday after all-night negotiations, prompting a suspension of
trading in TVS shares on the London Stock Exchange.
   MTM, a private Los Angeles company which takes its name from
Miss Moore's initials, had planned a $100 million initial public
stock offering last year but withdrew those plans after the October
stock market crash.
   At that time, the company was valued at around $450 million and
had after-tax profits of $26.1 million in the 1987 financial year,
down from $30.6 million the previous year, according to the Times.
   Since MTM was founded in 1970, it has produced about 30
television series and more than a dozen made-for-TV movies. Among
its hit TV series have been ``Hill Street Blues'' and ``St.
Elsewhere,'' which have a large audience in Europe.
   In addition, MTM develops and produces theatrical movies and
operates a record and music publishing company, MTM Music Group of
Nashville, Tenn.
   TVS, although relatively small, screens its productions in
southern England, the most prosperous area of Britain. TVS
productions are aired by Independent Television (ITV), Britain's
two-channel national commercial network. The non-commercial British
Broadcasting Corp. runs the other two channels.
   TVS showed a pre-tax profit of 21.8 million pounds, or about $37
million, in the fiscal year ending last October. Revenue totaled
171.9 million pounds,or about $292.2 million.
   The Financial Times said TVS has more than 25 million pounds, or
$40 million, in cash and will finance the deal by issuing stock
underwritten by the British merchant bank County NatWest.
   It said the deal would give TVS production capacity in the
United States, potential access to the U.S. networks ``and a
library of programs to sell across Europe to television stations
and cable and satellite.''
</TEXT>
