<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Philippines 1stLd-Writethru a0457 07-02 0623</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0457,0641</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Human Rights Lawyer Killed</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with human rights groups suggesting
motive in slayings and possible involvement of authorities, new
subversion charges against Europeans, ADD background on Mendoza, no
pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gunmen pulled a motorcycle beside the
car of a human rights lawyer and shot him to death on a downtown
street today.
   Emmanuel Mendoza, 57, was the third human rights lawyer killed
in the Philippines in as many weeks. A human rights group today
suggested that the police or military could be involved in the
unsolved slayings.
   Police Cpl. Porfirio Olais said two unidentified men on a
motorcycle opened fire on Mendoza when he stopped his car at a busy
intersection. A bystander brought the lawyer to a nearby hospital,
where he died minutes later, police and hospital officials said.
   Mendoza's wife, Emilia, said in a radio interview that her
husband had received several death threats from unidentified
callers.
   The independent Philippine Alliance of Human Rights Advocates
said Mendoza's shooting could be related to his work as defense
lawyer for slum residents whose communities have been raided by
police in search of communist hitmen.
   Mendoza was a legal counsel of the left-wing BAYAN organization
and chairman of the Manila Solidarity Alliance, a federation of
Manila slum residents' groups.
   His killing came two days after a failed assassination attempt
on Nemesio Prudente, the left-wing president of the state-run
Polytechnic University of the Philippines.
   Two weeks ago, gunmen also shot and killed human rights lawyer
Ramon Cura in his home near U.S. Clark Air Base north of Manila. A
colleague, Alfonso Surigao, was shot and killed in his residence in
the central Philippine island of Cebu last week.
   ``This series of killings has victimized personalities who have
been associated with the legal left,'' a statement released by the
human rights group said.
   ``That this could go on without the government being able to
solve any single case raises the strong possibilities that certain
segments of the police and the military could be involved in
them,'' the statement added.
   Investigators have yet to publish findings on an earlier ambush
on Prudente in November.
   Human rights groups blamed rightist death squads for that
attack. It occurred a week after soldiers and policemen chanted
``Kill Prudente'' during a funeral for a police captain and three
other people killed by communist assassins in the capital.
   The military and police had accused Prudente, an outspoken human
rights activist, of using his school to shelter communist
guerrillas. Prudente denied the charge.
   Also today, a government-run news agency said military
authorities have filed a new subversion complaint against two
Europeans and a Filipino of German descent accused of aiding
communist rebels.
   Swedish national Stellan Hermansson, West German Protestant
minister Klaus Schmidt, and Filipino businessman Antonio Bosch were
arrested June 8 and later held at a military camp, the Philippine
News Agency said.
   On Thursday, the Supreme Court rejected the petition of the
three men to drop charges of rebellion and kidnapping. It agreed,
however, to place them under the custody of a church group while
awaiting trial.
   In the new charges, the military said the three men were seen
with communist New People's Army guerrillas in four Quezon province
towns from May 23 to 25 and on June 2 this year and instructed new
rebel recruits, the agency said.
   Earlier, the military had accused them of taking part in a Feb.
3 raid in San Francisco town in Quezon and taking hostage two
policemen after the attack.
   Hermansson has said he arrived in the Philippines for the first
time in mid-May, and the other two said they were in the capital on
the day of the Feb. 3 raid.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
