<DOCNO> AP880702-0042 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-02-88 0527EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CopterCrash     07-02 0481</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Copter Crash,0492</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report Says Pilot Error Most Likely Caused Helicopters' Collision</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TED M. NATT JR.</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORT CAMPBELL, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   No action is warranted against anyone
as a result of a collision of two Army helicopters in March, even
though pilot error probably caused the accident that killed 17
soldiers, an Army report says.
   The accident happened March 8 when a UH-60 Black Hawk returning
from a solo instruction flight collided with the lead helicopter in
a formation of three returning from a night training mission to
pick up soldiers in the field.
   ``Up to the point of impact, the missions were formed just as
briefed,'' said Maj. Randy Schoel, public-affairs officer at the
Army base.
   The report found that the collision ``was the result of the two
air crews' being unable to see each other in the final moments of
flight,'' according to a statement read by Schoel at a news
conference Friday.
   The approximately 175-page report concluded, ``Pilot error, to
wit, a reasonable mistake in judgment is the most probable
explanation for the cause of this accident.''
   But the report, compiled by an investigation board of six Fort
Campbell officers _ all aviators, said: ``There should be no action
taken against anyone as no foundation for negligence can be
established. The accident was not due to lack of diligence, nor
unreasonable or unprofessional conduct.''
   The investigation board found no evidence of a mechanical
malfunction in the two Black Hawks involved in the crash. ``Nor can
it be confirmed that there were any procedural errors on the part
of either crew,'' Schoel said.
   The report, however, cited other factors, including exterior and
interior design characteristics of the UH-60 Black Hawks and
limited pilot training using night-vision goggles. The report noted
a lack of lighting on the helicopters, and said the number and the
size of position lights on the outside of the $4.6 million Black
Hawk were inadequate.
   The helicopters were made by Sikorsky Aircraft division of
United Technologies Corp., said Staff Sgt. Dan Moore of the public
information office at Fort Campbell.
   In Stratford, Conn., late Friday, Robert Stangrone, a Sikorsky
spokesman, said: ``All aircraft have some degree of field-of-view
limitation. Obviously, the ideal cockpit is a glass bubble with an
unobstructed view. It's a matter of design tradeoffs that consider
structural integrity, ballistic tolerance, survivability and so on.
... Design and operational tradeoffs also determine the extent and
intensity of exterior aircraft lighting.''
   The report said one of the two helicopters may not have had its
anti-collision strobe light turned on as required at the time of
the accident.
   ``That's the only item in question _ the strobe light,'' Schoel
said.
   The lead helicopter, struck broadside, carried 13 soldiers. The
other craft carried four. All 17 victims belonged to the 101st
Airborne Division at Fort Campbell. The other two helicopters
landed safely.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
