<HEAD>Crop-Eating Elephants Relocated</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seventeen elephants were captured
and relocated over the past three months because of complaints they
had been eating up young rubber and palm oil trees and other crops,
an official said today.
   The elephants came out of the jungle were eating the crops in
the Maran, Raub and Temerloh areas about 60 miles northeast of
Kuala Lumpur, said the spokesman of the Wildlife and National Park
Department.
   They were sent to a national park about 120 miles northeast of
the capital, he said.
</TEXT>
