<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Japan-Markets     07-02 0226</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0234</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stock Prices Fall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices fell for the second day on the Tokyo
Stock Exchange today after prices fell on Wall Street and the
dollar posted strong gains against the yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which lost
265.87 points Friday, fell another 141.01 points, or 0.5 percent,
to end today's half-day session at 27,362.52.
   Traders said the loss was due mainly to the appreciation of the
dollar, which ended the week's trading in Tokyo Friday at 134.50
yen, its highest level this year, and because of concerns over
possible higher interest rates.
   ``The strength of the dollar and profit-taking were behind the
market's fall yesterday (Friday), and the market is still
adjusting,'' said Michio Katsumata, a spokesman for Nomura
Securities, Japan's largest brokerage.
   A trader who spoke on condition of anonymity said worry over
higher interest rates led to losses for some large-capital issues,
while the lower yen pushed some export-oriented issues higher.
   Among the gainers were Hitachi, Fujitsu, NEC, TDK, Pioneer and
Sony.
   Volume on the market's first section was estimated at 900
million shares. On Friday, 2.6 billion shares were traded.
   On Wall Street Friday, the Dow Jones industrial average lost
10.13 points as traders took to the sidelines for the Fourth of
July holiday.
   The Tokyo foreign exchange market is closed on Saturdays.
</TEXT>
