<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     07-02 0356</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0369</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTAGE, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A funeral home that extended credit to a
Detroit woman may have had to wait a bit longer than it expected
for payment _ 57 years.
   A letter with a Nov. 17, 1930, postmark surfaced recently,
delivering a note of thanks and a check for $100 to the Truesdale
Funeral Home.
   The letter had a 2-cent stamp and was addressed to funeral home
founder George P. Truesdale. It was delivered to H. Sam Ansell Jr.,
who now owns the mortuary.
   The letter probably encounterd a fate common to long-delayed
mail, said David Mastervich, an account representative at the post
office in nearby Kalamazoo.
   ``We probably moved some equipment that's been there 50 years
and they found a letter under it,'' he said. ``At least no one can
say it didn't get delivered.''
   The woman's note thanked Truesdale for extending credit for the
funeral of her mother.
   ``You have been most kind in letting us have this time to pay
and we sincerely thank you,'' she said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>JASPER, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Robert and Lana Wessel can say their newborn
daughter is truly one in a million: She shares the birthday of her
two older sisters.
   Audrey was born Thursday at Memorial Hospital and Health Care
Center. Natalie, 4, and Ashton, 2, also were born on June 30.
   ``I thought I would either have her the day before or the day
after,'' said Mrs. Wessel. ``And that morning was a big surprise
when I went into labor.''
   Audrey was due June 15, and her two sisters also were about two
weeks late, Mrs. Wessel added.
   ``I didn't think it would happen the second time, much less the
third time,'' she said. ``I told my girls they were getting a baby
sister for their birthday and that was fine.''
   Next June 30, the family will have three cakes, three parties
and sing ``Happy Birthday'' three times, Mrs. Wessel said.
   The odds of having three same-sex children born on the same date
are about one in one million, said computer scientist Douglas
Miller at Naval Avionics in Indianapolis.
</TEXT>
