<2ND_LINE>PM-India-Sikhs,0189</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Suspected Sikhs Kill Two, Including Governing Party Leader</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Teams of gunmen shot and killed two men
in Punjab state, including an official in Prime Minister Rajiv
Gandhi's party, police and newspaper reports said today. Both
attacks were blamed on Sikh militants.
   Police identified the slain party representative as Manjit Singh
Verka, a district general secretary of the governing Congress Party.
   He was killed in his home about three miles south of Amritsar by
six men who burst in and shot him today while he drank his morning
tea, said district police chief Suresh Arora.
   At Sotal village about 25 miles northwest of Punjab's state
capital of Chandigarh, five Sikhs shot and killed Gurdev Singh,
reported the United News of India. It gave no details.
   More than 1,400 people have been killed in Punjab so far this
year by Sikh militants agitating for a separate homeland.
   Sikhs make up less than 2 percent of India's population of 800
million, but they are a majority in Punjab. They claim they are
discriminated against by the country's Hindu majority.
