<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SaltyRiver 1stLd-Writethru a0460 07-02 0632</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Salty River, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0460,0648</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gulf Salt Water Threatens New Orleans River Water</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Corrects saltwater to salt water thruout, except where
adjectival</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALBERTO S. FRANCO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A wedge of salt water creeping up the
Mississippi River could begin tainting New Orleans' water supply in
a week despite federal efforts to build a dike to slow the
intrusion, a university professor says.
   The salt water from the Gulf of Mexico, flowing upstream because
the worst drought in decades has weakened the Mississippi's flow,
is traveling about two miles per day and was within 17 miles of New
Orleans on Friday.
   When the salt water first reaches the city, on about July 10,
the contamination will be minimal, but by July 20 the salinity of
the city's water could hit 200 parts per million, said Louisiana
State University professor emeritus Raphael Kazmann.
   That would make the water drinkable but ``make the coffee taste
lousy,'' he said.
   In addition, the salt water could corrode appliances such as
water heaters and dishwashers, he said.
   By the end of the month, the salinity probably will reach 300
ppm, which is above federal drinking water standards although it
can be tolerated by most healthy people, he said.
   By the end of June the salt water had traveled as far upriver as
it had on Oct. 8, 1965, a severe drought year, Kazmann said.
   The river is usually at its lowest point in the fall, and that
doesn't bode well for Louisiana in 1988, he warned.
   The U.S. Army Corps of Engineers began construction Thursday on
a $947,000 sand and clay barrier that will stretch 1,200 feet along
the contours of the river bottom about 63 miles from where the
river meets the Gulf of Mexico.
   Construction is expected to take less than a month, spokesman
Bruce Sossaman said Friday.
   Salt water hugs the river bottom because it is heavier than
fresh water. It is advancing up the river because the
drought-induced low flow is not rapid enough to push it back to the
Gulf.
   The upper point of the saltwater wedge is about 15 miles past
the dike the Corps is building, Sossaman said.
   ``The levee is not as good an idea as it was before,'' said
Frederic Chatry, chief of the Corps' Engineering Division. ``But
we're not trying to solve the saltwater intrusion problem. We're
just trying to mitigate the part of saltwater intrusion caused
because we deepened Southwest Pass 5 feet ... last fall and
winter.''
   Southwest Pass is a primary navigation channel for entering the
river from the Gulf of Mexico.
   To compensate for the salt water's movement and to make up for
lost time, the Corps might build the sand and clay sill slightly
higher than originally planned, Chatry said.
   Residents of New Orleans and the several other communities who
get their drinking water from the Mississippi River shouldn't
panic, Sossaman said.
   At first, the salt water will not perceptibly change the taste
of the city's water supply, he said. If the salinity increases, it
should only pose problems for those under salt-restrictive diets.
   So far, abnormal salinity has not registered at the city's water
intakes, said Sewerage and Water Board spokesman Joe Puglia. The
board is working with the state and the Corps but has no citywide
plan, he said.
   Saltwater intrusion in the Mississippi River is not uncommon,
Sossaman noted. Communities close to the Gulf of Mexico experience
the problem every summer with varying degrees of severity.
   ``Because of the drought, this summer it will probably go up
higher and stay longer,'' he said, adding it could go as far as 75
miles upstream to Baton Rouge, La.
   Autumn rains should help force the salt water back to the Gulf,
he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
