<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Dukakis-PrisonProbe 1stLd-Writethru a044massaidhehopestosettlethemanagingquestionforthelast-placeclubbytheAll-Starbreak
07-02 0655</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis-Prison Probe, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0441,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sources: Appraisals Value Prison Site Far Below Dukakis' Proposed
Payment</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Recasts lead to focus on Dukakis element, edits thruout.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New appraisals of a proposed prison site for which
Gov. Michael Dukakis' administration has asked $10 million to buy
from developers put the value of the land at under $6 million,
according to sources.
   The state wants to build a 500-bed prison on the hilltop land in
New Braintree. Developers, who one critic of the project alleges
are friends of the Democratic presidential candidate, sought $9.5
million for the land two years ago.
   The FBI is conducting a preliminary inquiry into allegations
that the Dukakis administration leaked word to the developers of
state interest in the land. They bought it from a church for $3
million.
   Dukakis, who the FBI says is not under investigation himself,
and the developers deny the allegation or any association with each
other.
   Dukakis, asked about the controversy in recent weeks, has
reiterated his position that the state will ``not pay one dime
more'' than the fair market value of the property.
   Three sources, all speaking on the condition of anonymity, told
The Associated Press on Friday that two appraisals listed the value
of the hilltop land in the $5 million to $6 million range. The
sources would not provide exact figures on the appraisals but one
said they were ``not far apart.''
   The appraisals are being reviewed by a third company, which is
scheduled to submit its estimate of the property's worth next week.
All three will be used by the state to determine how much to offer
for the 782 acres bought by two developers in December 1985.
   Selection of the New Braintree site in 1986 by Dukakis for a
medium security prison has been controversial from the outset, with
local residents claiming a prison would ruin the tiny central
Massachusetts community.
   The land _ which houses a defunct church academy, 20 homes and
more than 700 acres of farmland _ is owned by developers Danial
Striar and Dr. Gary Jacobson.
   If they reject the state's offer for the land, the state can
take it by eminent domain, a move that likely would end up in
court. The developers could not be reached Friday for comment.
   The chief critic of the prison project, Dorothea Thomas-Vitrac
of New Braintree, has made the allegation that the men are close
associates of Dukakis and were tipped off about the state's plans.
   In denying the allegations, Striar and Dukakis have said they
met once, at a 1986 ground-breaking ceremony. Jacobson grew up in
the same neighborhood as Dukakis and has donated to his campaigns.
Dukakis has said he knows of Jacobson from childhood but has no
personal or business dealings with him.
   In April 1986, nearly two years after the administration began
eyeing New Braintree for a prison but a month before Dukakis
officially announced the siting, a Springfield company hired by the
state put the value of the land at $8.7 million.
   The appraiser, the R.J. Greely Co., told the state in a report
that its review ``is not to be considered a complete appraisal. Due
to time constraints and other limiting conditions, we are doing
this report in `broad brush' terms, without having time to do our
own research.''
   As part of a larger prison funding package, Dukakis in May 1986
requested $22 million for New Braintree, $10 million of which was
to be set aside to purchase the land. Striar and Jacobson offered
it to the state for $9.5 million.
   Critics of the prison, led by Thomas-Vitrac, complained that
Striar and Jacobson stood to make more than $6 million on the deal
without improving the site.
   Dukakis and other administration officials said they sought the
$10 million appropriation to avoid waiting another year to have the
money included in the next state budget.
</TEXT>
