<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Korea 1stLd-Writethru   07-02 0449</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Korea, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0464,0460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>National Assembly Votes Down Roh's Nomination Of Chief Justice</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with four grafs to UPDATE with Assembly approving a Roh
nominee; picks up 4th graf pvs, ``The one-house ...; adds byline</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PAUL SHIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Assembly today voted down
President Roh Tae-woo's nomination for chief justice in the first
test of power in the new legislature.
   The rejection of Chung Ki-sung was the first time in South
Korea's 40-year constitutional history that a president's
nomination of a chief justice has been turned down by the National
Assembly.
   It also was the first serious political setback for Roh since he
took office on Feb. 25 with a narrow victory in December's
presidential elections. Roh's government lost its majority in the
legislature during elections in April.
   In another vote, the Assembly approved by a narrow margin Roh's
nomination of former lawyer Kim Young-jun as head of the
government's Board of Audit and Inspection, a Cabinet-level post.
   The one-house Assembly rejected Roh's nomination of Chung as
chief justice by a narrow margin. Roh backers mustered 141 votes,
seven votes short of a simple majority required for approval. There
were 295 lawmakers present in the 299-member Assembly.
   Six lawmakers voted against Chung while 134 others, mostly from
the nation's two major opposition parties headed by Kim Dae-jung
and Kim Young-sam, abstained from voting in a coordinated
anti-government gesture. There were 14 invalid votes.
   Roh's governing Democratic Justice party, which controls 125
sets, had been confident that it could muster enough votes with the
help of a conservative opposition group.
   Kim Jong-pil's New Democratic Republican Party, with 35
lawmakers, had publicly endorsed Roh's nomination, but some of its
members rebelled and voted against Chung.
   The nation's two major opposition groupings, the Party for Peace
and Democracy and the Reunification Democracy Party, questioned
Chung's background under past authoritarian governments.
   Chung, 60, was named a Supreme Court judge in 1986 after holding
various judicial posts for 29 years.
   The governing party lost its parliamentary majority in the April
26 elections for the first time since South Korea was established
in 1948.
   Also today, 101 Assembly members introduced a resolution urging
North Korea to take part in this year's Olympic Games in Seoul and
said it could build momentum for national unification.
   The resolution, sponsored by lawmakers from the governing and
opposition parties, is to voted on next week.
   The North, which has demanded to be made a co-host of the
Olympics, has said it will boycott the Olympics unless its request
is met. The International Olympic Committee and South Korea have
refused, but have offered to let it stage several events.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
