<FILEID>AP-NR-07-02-88 0949EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Cambodia     07-02 0539</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cambodia,0555</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Search For Cambodian Peace Intensifying</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENIS D. GRAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Plans for peace in Cambodia are piling
up as Vietnam withdraws its troops from the country and opposition
groups prepare to meet for informal talks this month.
   The intensified search for a political settlement appears to
have been sparked by fears from several sides that the Khmer Rouge
could return to power. The communist Khmer Rouge defeated a
U.S.-backed government in 1975 and, according to some estimates,
killed 3 million Cambodians before they were toppled by the
Vietnamese invasion of 1978.
   Special U.N. envoy Rafeeuddin Ahmed has returned from Cambodia
after presenting a peace plan, the details of which have not been
disclosed. And the foreign ministers of the Association of
Southeast Nations reportedly will unveil another plan when they
meet in Bangkok next week.
   China proposed Friday that all Cambodian factions form a
coalition government before a total Vietnamese pullout. The Beijing
plan, which includes a call for all Cambodian parties to freeze
their force levels, is an apparent effort to keep the Khmer Rouge
from becoming dominant.
   Western analysts say China, the main weapons supplier to the
Khmer Rouge, is a key to the success of any negotiated settlement.
   The anti-Vietnamese resistance, a coalition of three groups led
by Prince Norodom Sihanouk, on June 25 issued proposals stressing
international supervision of a Cambodian agreement.
   The plan is directly tied to the informal talks scheduled for
July 25 in Jakarta, Indonesia. Vietnam and the Sihanouk coalition,
which includes the Khmer Rouge, have already accepted invitations
to the talks.
   The coalition includes the Khmer Rouge and the non-communist
Khmer People's National Liberation Front.
   he official Cambodian news agency SPK said Friday that Prime
Minister Hun Sen received an invitation but did not say whether the
government would attend.
   The resistance has proposed that Vietnam withdraw its forces in
three stages under international supervision. It also said the
coalition and the Phnom Penh government should be dissolved and a
four-party coalition government set up and headed by Sihanouk. The
coalition would then hold free elections.
   Vietnam has promised a total withdrawal of its forces from
Cambodia by 1990 and has begun a partial pullout of 50,000 troops
and withdrawn top military command. Vietnam said the conduct of the
anti-guerrilla war now will be directed by the Cambodians.
   According to local newspapers, the Southeast Asian foreign
ministers will consider a plan worked out by senior officials of
their bloc. It includes a general ceasefire; the pullout of all
Hanoi forces in three phases; the end of all foreign military
support for combatants and an international peacekeeping force that
would remain in Cambodia for five years.
   A Phnom Penh broadcast made available today indicated some
problems with the proposal brought to Cambodia by the U.N. envoy.
   Hun Sen was quoted by the official broadcast as describing the
meeting as an ``initial'' one and urged the United Nations to
``continue seeking to understand all the points upon which all the
Cambodian parties agree or do not agree with each other.''
   Hun Sen ``stressed that all solutions to the Cambodian problem
must absolutely guarantee'' the Khmer Rouge does not return to
power, the radio said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
