<HEAD>Arab Teen-ager Killed, Another Wounded In Clashes</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 13 grafs to UPDATE with Arab teen-ager killed,
another wounded, army denial, curfews reported; picks up 5th graf
pvs, ``Israeli analyst ...'' edits thereafter to trim</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RONI RABIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli troops shot and killed an Arab youth in
a demonstration today in the occupied West Bank ton of Jenin,
Israeli radio said. Protests broke out in at least four other West
Bank towns.
   Arab assailants also hurled a firebomb today at troops in Gaza
City but no injuries were reported, the army said.
   An army spokeswoman denied soldiers opened fire in Jenin, where
the death was reported, or in the West Bank town of Kalandia, where
a youth was said to have suffered a bullet wound.
   ``We have had a report from the hospital that a man died and the
army is checking if there is a connection,'' the military
spokeswoman, speaking on condition of anonymity. ``The army did not
see a body; the army used gas and rubber bullets only.''
   Israeli radio said the Jenin youth was shot in the head and his
body was taken from the hospital by his family. It said the clash
with soldiers erupted after masked men entered schools and brought
schoolchildren out to demonstrate.
   A hospital official in Jenin confirmed the death, and an Arab
reporter identified the dead boy as 17-year-old Na'el Youssef
Muhamad Hamaisi. Both spoke on condition of anonymity.
   A man in his 20s was treated and released for a bullet wound in
the thigh after a demonstration in Kalandia, officials at
Jerusalem's Mokassed Hospital said.
   The military spokeswoman said the army clamped a curfew on Jenin
and on the West Bank refugee camp of Jelazoun and town of Kalkilya,
where there also were brief protests.
   In Gaza City, an unidentified attacker hurled a firebomb at an
army vehicle, the army spokeswoman said. She said the bomb damaged
the car, but no one was injured.
   Since the anti-occupation unrest began in the West Bank and Gaza
Strip on Dec. 8, 215 Palestinians have been killed. Four Israelis
also have died.
   On Friday, the Israeli general in charge of the Gaza Strip
promised to release dozens of Arab prisoners from areas where
rioting has ceased and called on aspiring Palestinian leaders to
cooperate with Israeli authorities.
   Maj. Gen. Yitzhak Mordechai used Israel's Arabic television
services to appeal to Gaza's 650,000 residents in what appeared to
be an attempt to reward residents for the relative calm of recent
weeks.
   Also Friday, former U.N. Ambassador Benyamin Netanyahu said
Israel should deport hundreds of Arabs who instigate riots and have
a policy of opening fire at people who throw rocks and firebombs.
   Israeli analyst Ron Ben-Yishai, military correspondent for the
Yedioth Ahronot Hebrew newspaper, said anti-Israeli attacks are now
being carried out by small numbers of highly trained Palestinians.
This is in contrast to the early months of the uprising, when
hundreds of residents took part in frequent mass protests.
   Mordechai's statements indicated Israeli authorities are ready
to use a carrot as well as a stick approach, now that the massive
violent demonstrations that characterized the first months of the
uprising have waned.
   ``I have intentions to release dozens of prisoners, including
administrative detainees, next week, and they will mostly be
released if they are from places where there is quiet and security
and where there has been a return to routine life,'' Mordechai said.
   Last month Maj. Gen. Amram Mitzna, who is in charge of the West
Bank, released 89 Palestinian prisoners, a step military officials
said was taken ``to contribute to restoring normal life to the
area.''
</TEXT>
