<HEAD>Thai Prime Minister Inaugurates U.S. Jets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Prem Tinsulanonda today
annointed six U.S.-made F-16 jet fighters as Buddhist monks
sprinkled holy water on the aircraft that Thailand purchased from
the United States.
   Thailand is acquiring a total of 18 F-16s for $475 million in an
effort to bolster its defense capabilities against Vietnamese
forces in neighboring Cambodia. Thailand also bought two U.S.-made
Gates Learjets, at a cost of $10.7 million, to be used as
reconnaissance aircraft.
   During the ceremony at Don Muang military airport, six F-5E
fighter-bombers flew overhead while a Buddhist monks chanted and
sprinkled holy water on the F-16s. Prime minister Prem placed
garlands around the nose of each aircraft.
   At the ceremony, Prem thanked the United States government for
selling the jets to Thailand. In Asia, the only two other countries
to which the United States has offered its advanced fighters are
South Korea and Singapore.
   Attending the ceremony were U.S. Ambassador William Brown and
about 100 senior military and police officers.
   American pilots last month flew the F-16s from the General
Dynamics plant in Fort Worth, Texas, where they were manufactured,
to an air base in the northeastern city of Nakhon Ratchasima.
</TEXT>
