<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Low-Speed Chase,0188</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Charged After `Low-Speed' Chase</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MARTINSBURG, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man was arrested Saturday after what
authorities described as a low-speed chase through Pennsylvania,
Maryland and West Virginia.
   Jackie Leroy Thayer, 34, was pursued through three states on
suspicion of being involved in a hit-and-run accident in
Pennsylvania and finally was caught here after being trapped on a
dead-end street, said Sgt. K.M. Ambrose of the West Virginia state
police.
   Thayer, who is from Martinsburg, refused to stop and chase ran
several cars off the road, Ambrose said. Despite the pursuit,
speeds never were excessive, the sergeant said.
   ``To me, a high-speed chase is in excess of 100 miles per
hour,'' Ambrose said, adding that in this case, the driver simply
refused to stop.
   Thayer was charged with speeding in a 35 mph zone, third-offense
driving while intoxicated, driving with suspended license,
resisting arrest, having no proof of insurance, reckless driving,
driving left of center, failure to yield to an emergency vehicle,
and improper registration, Ambrose said.
   The sergeant said he expected Maryland and Pennsylvania
authorities to file charges later.
</TEXT>
