<HEAD>Plane Flying for West German Army Crashes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PLOEN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A civilian airplane participating in
West German army maneuvers crashed into a house and exploded,
killing the pilot, police said.
   A woman inside the house managed to flee her home before it was
destroyed in Friday's crash, police said. She was slightly injured.
   It was the third military-related accident in two days in West
Germany.
   On Wednesday, three U.S. Air Force F-16s crashed in two separate
incidents. Two of the F-16s collided in flight and killed a U.S.
pilot. The other F-16 crashed into the Black Forest after the pilot
parachuted to safety.
   West German police in Ploen said the light Bronco OV-10 plane
went down just outside the town about 60 miles north of the port
city of Hamburg. The aircraft was being used for spotting during
army artillery exercises.
   Police were still investigating the cause of the crash.
   The plane belonged to an aviation company in Luebeck, and its
pilot was West German.
   In Bordeaux, France, a West German air force Transall transport
plane made a crash landing today near the Bordeaux-Meringac
airport, injuring all six men aboard, officials said.
   The Transall was arriving in Bordeaux to pick up West German
soldiers who had been involved in military exercises in the region,
French military officials said.
   The reason for the crash landing was not immediately known.
</TEXT>
