<HEAD>Trawler Hauls British Shipwreck's Bell in Its Nets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>REYKJAVIK, Iceland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The bell from a British ship that sank
in stormy seas nearly 33 years ago has resurfaced in the nets of an
Icelandic trawler.
   The bronze bell, inscribed H.M.T. Grayling, belonged to the
Grayling, a British transport vessel commissioned by the navy in
1942 during World War II.
   The ship, which was sold after the war and renamed Barry Castle,
sank while fishing off Iceland's west coast in November 1955. Five
of the 19 crew members died.
   The crew of the trawler Pall Helgi said last week that they
pulled in the bell June 22. It was caught near the shipwreck, which
lies in water 360 feet deep.
