<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Hungary 1stLd-Writethru   07-02 0489</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hungary, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0424,0501</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hungary Accuses Romania of Human Rights Violations</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs with Grosz appealing for talks with
Romania; picks up 2nd graf pvs, ``The action ...;'' DELETES 11th
graf pvs, ``Hungarian Premier ...'' to conform</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TEDDIE WEYR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist Party chief Karoly Grosz has
appealed for talks with Romania following heightened tensions
between the two Warsaw Pact allies, a government newspaper reported
today.
   In an interview with the newspaper Magyar Hirlap, Grosz was
quoted as stressing the ``political necessity and moral
obligation'' for direct talks with Romania to find an end to the
dispute.
   The newspaper said Grosz, who also is premier, wants to go to
Romania for talks but did not know when.
   Grosz was quoted as saying there have been no contacts between
he and Romanian leader Nicolae Ceausescu but considered it
important that Ceausescu had called for a meeting between
representatives of the two nations to improve relations.
   On Friday, the Hungarian Parliament passed a resolution accusing
Romania of violating the human rights of ethnic Hungarians and
other minorities in the neighboring East-bloc country.
   The action was taken at the end of a week of escalating tensions
over Romania's planned demolition of 7,000 villages with the
residents to be resettled in ``agro-industrial'' centers.
   Budapest newspapers said some Hungarians were being prevented
from entering Romania.
   The resolution adopted by Parliament with only one abstention
said Romania is violating ``the fundamental human, national and
nationalities-related rights.''
   It called on Romania to re-examine its resettlement plan.
   There are about 1.7 million ethnic Hungarians living in Romania
and about 220,000 ethnic Germans as well as thousands of Serbs.
Most of the Hungarians live in Transylvania, many in villages to be
destroyed.
   Romania claims the resettlement will provide higher living
standards and gain productive agricultural land where houses now
stand.
   ``The annihilation of the values of the settlements doomed to
destruction ... would mean an irreparable loss not only to the
Hungarian, German and other ethnic minorities, but also to the
Romanian people themselves,'' the resolution said.
   Earlier this week Romania expelled several Hungarian diplomats
from an area inhabited by many ethnic Hungarians, closed a
Hungarian consulate in Cluj and began turning back Hungarian
tourists.
   Matyas Szueroes, the head of the foreign relations committee who
presented the resolution to Parliament, said Hungary's leadership
would ``always be cooperating partners'' and was prepared to go
ahead with preparations for a meeting of the two countries'
premiers.
   Hungarian newspapers quoted officials and travelers as saying
Hungarians wishing to enter Romania were being turned back at the
border.
   In some cases only those traveling through Romania to other
destinations were allowed to cross into the country, the papers
said.
   Romania's decision to close the Hungarian consulate in Cluj in
Traynsylvania followed a demonstration by some 50,000 people who
marched past the Romanian Embassy in Budapest to protest the
resettlement plan.
</TEXT>
