<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Mozambique-Rebels     07-02 0222</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mozambique-Rebels,0228</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>RENAMO Reports Capturing Two Army Barracks, Ambushing Convoy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mozambican rebels said Saturday they
captured two army barracks and ambushed a military convoy, killing
38 Mozambican and five Zimbabwean soldiers.
   The Mozambique National Resistance, known by the Portuguese
acronym RENAMO, said its fighters seized the barracks in southern
Maputo and central Sofala provinces.
   The rebels said they ambushed a convoy of 37 vehicles outside
the capital, Maputo, and killed 10 Mozambican soldiers and captured
206 Soviet-made weapons.
   The statement, distributed in Lisbon, said the fighting took
place from Monday to Thursday.
   RENAMO also claimed 3,700 Zimbabwean soldiers had recently
entered Mozambique and were deployed in the northern-central
provinces of Nampula, Zambezia and Tete. The statement alleged that
Mozambique government forces were ``losing control of the military
situation.''
   There was no independent confirmation of the rebel claims nor
any indication of RENAMO casualties in the reported attacks. The
rebels have been waging a hit-and-run guerrilla campaign since 1977
to topple the Marxist government.
   Troops from neighboring Zimbabwe, Tanzania and Malawi fight in
Mozambique alongside the army, mainly to protect vital transport
routes and an oil pipeline from rebel attack.
   The rebel statement said the alleged Zimbabwean reinforcments
brought the total number of Zimbabwean soldiers in Mozambique to
8,700. It claimed 32,300 foreign soldiers were stationed in
Mozambique.
</TEXT>
