<FILEID>AP-NR-07-02-88 1055EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FBIDiscipline     07-02 0413</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-FBI Discipline,0424</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Documents Reveal FBI Agents Not Fired For Breaking Laws</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   FBI agents who broke drug and customs laws
were reprimanded and suspended but not fired, according to court
documents in a lawsuit filed by an agent who was dismissed.
   The previously confidential documents were obtained by an
attorney for former agent Anthony P. Rezza, who was fired three
years ago after using federal money and a car in a gambling spree
in Atlantic City, N.J.
   The 22-year veteran filed suit last year contending that the
action against him was overly harsh.
   Court files on the suit contain six disciplinary cases. In
addition, government lawyers have conceded, without supplying
files, the details of four other cases mentioned in Rezza's
complaint.
   Allegations include reports of an agent who was suspended for 30
days after being arrested when he entered the country with
marijuana and drug paraphernalia.
   There is also a report of a supervisor who was demoted,
suspended for 45 days and put on probation for a year for placing
bets with a bookie while supervising a gambling investigation of
the same bookie.
   FBI officials declined to comment on the documents. Spokesman
William Carter said the bureau does not comment on pending
litigation. He added that disciplinary cases ``are confidential, an
employer-employee administrative matter.''
   In court documents, government lawyers have contended that
Rezza's dismissal _ regardless of his compulsive gambling problem
or the FBI's record of discipline with other agents _ was an
acceptable option.
   In a motion filed June 14, Alice W. Ballard, Rezza's attorney,
said, ``The bureau's past practice is inconsistent with the
categorical rule it now asserts.
   ``The FBI disciplinary files produced in this case are replete
with examples of agents who remained in service ... despite the use
of drugs, misuse of credit cards, customs violations, illegal
gambling, drunken driving, sexual misconduct, a hit and run
accident and other illegal behavior.''
   Ballard would not discuss the case, tentatively scheduled for
trial in November.
   Some lawyers believe disparities in discipline are the result of
an internal struggle between moderate elements in the FBI and
conservative followers of the late J. Edgar Hoover.
   ``There is this gap between those elite elements who believe in
a concept of government service and those elite elements who have
more military mentality,'' said Antonio V. Silva, one of the
lawyers in a class-action discrimination suit filed last year by
agent Bernardo Perez and now joined by 300 Hispanic FBI agents.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
