<2ND_LINE>AM-Toy Commando,0232</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Surround Boy Armed With Realistic Squirt Gun</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANCHESTER, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 12-year-old boy playing in a park
dropped his realistic squirt gun and raised his arms when
confronted by police who had received a call about a commando armed
with a machine gun.
   A witness called police about noon Friday and reported seeing a
man dressed in military fatigues carrying a gun in Wickham Park,
police Lt. John Mott said.
   Eight police cars from Manchester and East Hartford surrounded
the park preparing to search for the gunman when Mott spotted the
boy, who was wearing camouflage clothing, a backpack, a military
belt and a helmet.
   ``As I got out of the car, he dropped the gun and put up his
hands up,'' Mott said. ``That was the smart thing for him to do.''
   ``When he saw the other cops pull up, he looked a little
bewildered, a little nervous,'' Mott said.
   Mott, who had not drawn his own handgun, said he realized the
boy's gun _ resembling an Uzi submachine gun _ was a toy as soon as
he saw it.
   After the commotion was over, Mott said they ``let the kid go
play.''
   The General Assembly last session approved legislation
restricting the sale of realistic toy guns that have been blamed in
several accidental deaths elsewhere in the country.
</TEXT>
