<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Drought-Faith     07-02 0447</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought-Faith,0462</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Church Leaders Think Drought May Reaffirm Religious Faith</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THOMAS P. WYMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SOUTH BEND, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The drought withering farm crops may be
nourishing religious faith in rural communities in Indiana, where
parched lands threaten farm families' spirits as well as their
livelihood.
   While praying for rain, members of small town congregations are
being challenged to look deeper into their faith, some religious
leaders say.
   Although a selection of churches around Indiana reported no
significant increase in Sunday attendance, special services to pray
for rain have drawn well.
   ``People make more of an attempt for a deeper prayer life
because of this, because it's a challenge,'' says the Rev. John
Boeglin of St. Celestine Roman Catholic Church in Dubois County in
southern Indiana.
   ``I don't think this is bringing people back to the church,''
said Boeglin, who is in charge of rural church affairs for 12
counties in the Evansville Diocese. ``Most people on the land are
already regular churchgoers because they know they're dependent on
God for their success in agriculture. They have to have a bountiful
rain that they can't control.''
   One effort to exert influence has been the prayer services to
plead for rain.
   A recent service in Tipton, a town between Kokomo and
Indianapolis in Tipton County, drew about 200 people to a town park.
   ``We don't even get that many people for our Good Friday service
or our Thanksgiving service,'' said the Rev. Jayna Powell, the
minister for youth and family education at West Street Christian
Church. ``People are seeing a need to express their concern about
the drought to God.''
   A recent issue of a diocesan newspaper carried an article by
Boeglin entitled, ``Should We Pray For Rain?''
   ``I jokingly wrote in the article maybe God needs a hearing aid,
or we're not praying loud enough,'' he said.
   The priest answered his own question by organizing a prayer
meeting for Wednesday.
   ``We're not trying to wheel and deal with God. We can't say,
'OK, if we pray for rain, it's going to rain,' '' he said.
   In the past, such prayers were a formal part of the church
calendar, he said. During Rogation days, the three days before
Ascension Day, congregations used to pray for good weather and
bountiful crops.
   ``Now I see there is something in that tradition that we should
keep going, because we see the serious need,'' he said.
   The drought highlights the Christian teaching that hope survives
even in misery and suffering, he said.
   ``I think people need to hear the story God has not abandoned us
because of the drought,'' he said. ``We will make it through. We
will.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880702-0079 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-02-88 1120EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Gorbachev-Grosz     07-02 0098</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gorbachev-Grosz,0100</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Party Leader to Visit Moscow</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist Party chief Karoly Grosz will
pay a brief visit to the Soviet Union for talks with Mikhail S.
Gorbachev this week, Radio Budapest reported Saturday.
   In a radio interview from parliament, where Grosz was addressing
leading industrial managers, the Hungarian leader said he would
leave Budapest on Monday and meet with the Kremlin leader Tuesday.
   He didn't say when he would return to Hungary.
   Grosz said he planned to discuss with Gorbachev ``the principles
of Soviet-Hungarian economic ties, including future projects.'' He
did not elaborate.
</TEXT>
