<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-JulyFourth     07-02 0393</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-July Fourth,0407</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Americans In Beijing Celebrate Fourth Of July</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLENE L. FU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans in China celebrated Independence Day on
Saturday with dragon dances, Chinese acrobats, an Air Force band
and 3,000 McDonald's Big Macs.
   More than 1,500 Americans living in China, from Beijing to the
far northwestern Xinjiang province, gathered at the U.S. Embassy in
the capital.
   Chinese guards were posted outside the embassy compound, and a
metal detector was set up at the main entrance.
   Authorities last month warned Americans in Beijing that they
might be the target of terrorists from another country. The third
country was never identified, and the warning was eventually lifted.
   ``We're as safe as in Main Street, U.S.A.,'' said an embassy
official, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Each year for the past five years, McDonald's in Hong Kong has
flown in thousands of Big Macs for the Fourth of July. But this
year, the McDonald's monopoly over the embassy party was broken by
Kentucky Fried Chicken, which opened its largest restaurant in the
world here in the fall.
   Kentucky Fried Chicken donated 1,000 meals for the celebration,
while 14 McDonald's employees from Hong Kong flipped 3,000 patties
for Americans desperate for a taste of Big Macs.
   The festivities started with an afternoon parade by 70 children
riding bicycles festooned with red, white, and blue streamers or on
roller skates.
   Ambassador Winston Lord, dressed as a cowboy in a white vest,
red shirt and straw hat, called on Americans to exercise their
right to vote in this fall's presidential elections.
   ``There is one important, almost mystical right that Americans
carry wherever our roads may lead. The right to vote,'' he said.
``I encourage you to vote .... There is nothing quite like this
American expression of will.''
   Lord's 10-minute speech ended in a deafening roar of
firecrackers. Two teams of dragon dancers, accompanied by clanging
cymbals, then took over the show.
   Next came the U.S. Air Force pop band, ``Spectrum.'' The band
was flown in from Washington for the occasion.
   Filling the breaks in the band's performance were a lip-sync
contest, a raffle and a performance by a children's chorus from
Beijing's International School.
   Ticket sales covered the cost of the $41,000 event, with a $20
admission for students, teachers and embassy staff, and $30 for
everyone else.
</TEXT>
