<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Pilgrimage-Accident     07-02 0198</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pilgrimage-Accident,0202</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Car Plows Into Group En Route to Religious Festival, Policeman
killed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEIDEN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A car plowed into a group of 87 West
Germans walking to a religious festival, killing a policeman
escorting them and injuring 12 of the pilgrims, officials said
Saturday.
   The accident occurred late Friday near Weiden, about 45 miles
northeast of Nuremberg in Bavaria state.
   The Roman Catholic pilgrims were walking along the side of a
road, en route to nearby Amberg for a religious festival Saturday,
police said.
   Police said a 25-year-old man lost control of his vehicle and
plowed into the group. A 39-year-old policeman was killed, and some
of the pilgrims suffered serious injuries, police said.
   The pilgrims had taken many precautions to ensure their safety
along their walk, police said, including wearing fluorescent vests
and carrying blinking lights. The police escort was also intended
to ensure their safety.
   Police were trying to track down two cars that passed the group
seconds before the accident. Those two automobiles apparently were
traveling on the wrong side of the road after passing the pilgrims
and may have caused the man to lose control of his car, police said.
