<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Reagan-Byrd-Fourth     07-02 0243</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Byrd-Fourth,230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan, Democrats Offer Same Holiday Advice: Vote</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan and Senate Democratic leader
Robert C. Byrd on Saturday both offered the same election-year
Fourth of July advice for Americans: Vote.
   ``It's up to each of us to preserve, protect and defend
America's precious heritage,'' the president said in his weekly
radio address.
   ``Some of us have done just that on the battlefield. But all of
us can do it each and every day.
   ``We can vote at election time. We can volunteer to help
political campaigns for the candidates of our choice, as well as
volunteer for work that's needed around our community. And we can
simply raise our children well, do our jobs well and live in God's
light.''
   Byrd, the Senate majority leader from West Virginia, said in the
Democratic response to the president's speech that Independence Day
in 1988 ``is different because this year we must choose a new path
for America.''
   ``This is an election year,'' Byrd said. ``We are about to
choose a new president.''
   ``Celebrate your freedom in the most meaningful way this year,''
he said. ``Participate. Exercise that most important uniquely
American privilege. Vote.''
   Reagan spoke from Camp David, the presidential retreat in the
Catoctin Mountains of Maryland, where he and first lady Nancy
Reagan are spending the weekend. The Reagans will return to
Washington Monday and watch the traditional capital fireworks show
from a balcony of the White House.
</TEXT>
