<1ST_LINE>u i PM-SAfrica-Blast 3rdLd-Writethru   07-02 0577</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SAfrica-Blast, 3rd Ld - Writethru,a0566,0591</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Blast Outside Stadium Kills Two, Injures 26</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with four grafs to UPDATE with two confirmed dead, 26
hurt, other detail; picks up 5th pvs: Sportswriters covering...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A car bomb exploded today
outside a crowded Johannesburg sports stadium, killing at least two
people and injuring 26, police said.
   The blast occurred on a street alongside Ellis Park stadium
minutes after the end of the rugby match between Transvaal and
Orange Free State, said police spokesman Pierre Louw.
   Louw said the two men killed were white. Among the injured, 23
are white, two are black and one is Asian, Louw said.
   The stadium seats about 75,000 people and is the largest
sporting facility in the Johannesburg area. The attendance figure
was not immediately available, but Saturday afternoon matches
generally attract at least 25,000 fans.
   Sportswriters covering the match said they saw flames leaping 60
yards into the air following the explosion, the South African Press
Association reported. They said the blast occurred just outside an
entrance gate to the stadium, SAPA said.
   Several surrounding buildings in the downtown area were set
ablaze, but were extinguished by firemen within several minutes,
witnesses said.
   Metal from the car that exploded was found up to 200 yards away
from the blast, witnesses added. Several additional cars also were
damaged they said.
   Police immediately blocked off the area and began checking
nearby parked cars for additional explosives.
   Rugby is the most popular team sport among white South Africans,
and tens of thousands of whites regularly attend weekend matches at
Ellis Park.
   The bombing was the latest in a recent series of attacks aimed
at civilian targets. There have been more than 90 bombings since
the government declared a natinwide state of emergency in June
1986, including some 25 this year.
   Police have blamed virtually all the attacks on the outlawed
African National Congress guerrilla group, the main black
organization attempting to overthrow the white-led government.
   The group, based in Lusaka, Zambia, seldom confirms or denies
involvement in specific attacks. However, recent statements by
African National Congress leaders have suggested that the
organization approves of attacks on civilian targets.
   On Thursday, 13 whites and one black were hurt by a bomb that
exploded outside a fast food restaurant in a Johannesburg shopping
center at the Poyntons Building, which houses the air force and
prison service headquarters on upper floors.
   Hospital officials said none was hurt seriously. Two of the
injured people were children.
   The country is run under a system of apartheid, a policy of
segregation that preserves power and privilege for South Africa's 5
million whites and denies rights and a voice in national affairs to
its 26 million blacks.
   On Friday, the government proposed tough measures to enforce
residential segregation, and critics said it could mean mass
eviction of blacks from white areas. The bills are to be debated in
August.
   The government has not strictly enforced the 35-year-old act
Group Areas Act in recent years, which restricts blacks to certain
areas. The proposed amendment to the act calls for the hiring of
inspectors to check violations of the law.
   It would make it easier for authorities to confiscate property
and to evict and prosecute people living in areas not designated
for their race group.
   On June 10, President P.W. Botha extended for a third year the
country's state of emergency.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
