<1ST_LINE>r w AM-DefenseProbe-Chronology     07-02 0939</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Defense Probe-Chronology,940</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>How the Story Unfolded</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Defense Probe-Justice</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are major events in the investigation of
alleged procurement fraud and bribery involving government
officials, defense contractors and consultants:
   JUNE 14: Pursuing what FBI spokesman Gregory Jones calls
``allegations of fraud and bribery,'' FBI and Naval Investigative
Service agents raid the offices of Pentagon officials, defense
contractors and consultants.
   More than 30 locations are searched in 12 states and the
District of Columbia. Law enforcement sources say the searches are
part of a two-year probe that has included wiretaps.
   Targets include Melvyn Paisley, a former assistant Navy
secretary who became a consultant to several aerospace contractors
immediately upon leaving the Pentagon. Also searched are the
Pentagon offices of Victor Cohen, a top Air Force acquisitions
official, and James Gaines, deputy assistant Navy secretary for
acquisitions, as well as offices and plants of some of the
country's largest defense contractors, among them McDonnell Douglas
Corp. in St. Louis, United Technologies Corp. in Washington and
Unisys Corp. in Minneapolis and New York.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   JUNE 16: A search warrant issued in the investigation states
that McDonnell Douglas improperly received large amounts of
confidential Pentagon information from Paisley. Law enforcement
officials say some 275 subpoenas have been served.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   JUNE 17: Reps. Roy Dyson, D-Md., and Bill Chappell, D-Fla., deny
reports that they are under scrutiny in the investigation. Two more
defense contractors _ LTV Corp. and Martin Marietta Corp. _
acknowledge that they have been served with subpoenas.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   JUNE 18: A second search warrant reveals that the FBI believes
Pratt & Whitney obtained confidential documents that rival jet
engine maker General Electric Co. had given to the Defense
Department in bidding for engine contracts worth hundreds of
millions of dollars.
   The warrant is used to search the offices of Eugene Tallia, vice
president of Pratt & Whitney and head of the company's Washington
office.
   Also reportedly under investigation are the activities of the
late Rep. Joseph Addabbo, D-N.Y., who was chairman of the House
Appropriations defense subcommittee.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   JUNE 20: Three other congressmen _ Rep. Thomas Downey, D-N.Y.,
Andrew Ireland, R-Fla., and Sam Stratton, D-N.Y. _ are reported on
the list of those under scrutiny, but not targets, in the case.
   Three more defense contractors: Hercules Inc., Gould Inc. and
the Electronic Data Systems Corp., say they have been served with
subpoenas.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   JUNE 21: Pentagon spokesmen say Defense Secretary Frank C.
Carlucci has issued a directive specifying that any Pentagon
employee under scrutiny in the bribery probe must be reassigned.
   President Reagan, in a news conference in Toronto at the end of
the economic summit, said he was ``very upset'' about reports of
wrongdoing. But he praised investigators for ferreting out the
misdeeds and said it was ``understandable how such things'' could
happen in a government bureaucracy.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   JUNE 22: House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas, says after a meeting
with the prosecutor in the Pentagon probe that ``no member of the
House is under investigation'' in the case.
   Former Defense Secretary Caspar Weinberger, in an interview,
denies responsibilty for whatever corruption may be found. ``No
matter how careful you are, you're not going to be able to
eliminate dishonesty,'' he says.
   BDM International Inc. of McLean, Va., is reported to have been
served with a subpoena. Paisley's wife, Vicki, is an employee of
the company.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   JUNE 23: The Los Angeles Times reports that investigators
believe Gaines was a principal supplier of Pentagon documents to
Paisley. The newspaper says Paisley allegedly passed the
information to McDonnell Douglas, which paid him ``staggering
fees.'' An attorney for Paisley denies the allegations.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   JUNE 24: The Senate Armed Services Committee considers
legislation to allow the government to suspend payments to defense
contractors under investigation in the case. Sen. Ted Stevens,
R-Alaska, offered the proposal but later withdrew it.
  
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   JUNE 26: Sources say investigators videotaped meetings in which
Defense Department officials allegedly took payoffs from
consultants. The sources say Gaines and Cohen appear on some of the
videotapes, as does Paisley.
   The Washington Post, meanwhile, reports that Cohen is
cooperating in the investigation.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   JUNE 27 _ Carlucci says the government may terminate as many as
100 contracts suspected of being tainted in the investigation into
alleged fraud and bribery. However, Carlucci warns against
prematurely condemning and abandoning the entire procurement system
before ``all the facts are in.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   JUNE 28 _ Justice Department officials acknowledge that Attorney
General Edwin Meese III recused himself from the Pentagon fraud
investigation a day earlier because his own defense lawyers are
representing clients involved in the case.
   The Associated Press obtains a copy of a May 5 memo written by
Robert Costello, undersecretary of defense for acquisition, to
Carlucci suggesting that top Pentagon officials be given veto power
over searches of contractor facilities.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   JUNE 29 _ Henry Hudson, the U.S. attorney heading the
investigation, says in court papers that he has learned of several
instances of documents being destroyed by people under
investigation in the probe. No details were given on who destroyed
documents or how they may have related to the investigation.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   JUNE 30 _ Court documents unsealed in federal court in Dallas
reveal that FBI agents eavesdropped as a Navy procurement official,
George Stone, read to a private defense consultant the sealed bids
from 10 companies competing for a $120 million air control
contract. Stone is one of six Pentagon officials transferred to
other duties after their offices were searched.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   JULY 1 _ Carlucci announces that he is acting on information in
the documents unsealed in Dallas by suspending payments on $1
billion worth of contracts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
