<FILEID>AP-NR-07-02-88 1337EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Dukakis-PrisonProbe Bjt   07-02 0852</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis-Prison Probe, Bjt,850</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Controversial Dukakis Prison Siting Enters Presidential Politics</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW BRAINTREE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   On a hilltop overlooking this tiny
town is what Gov. Michael Dukakis believes is the perfect site for
a new prison and what opponents of that plan say is the centerpiece
of a corrupt land deal.
   The 782 acres in rural New Braintree, home of a defunct
religious academy and perhaps a future prison, is the battlefield
for a two-year war over the prison plans that is intensifying as
the state moves to buy the property and Dukakis, now the certain
Democratic presidential nominee, eyes the White House.
   Dukakis spent much of 1986 defending his choice of the site and
was drawn back into the fray last month, when the FBI acknowledged
it was conducting a preliminary inquiry into allegations by prison
opponents that developers who bought the property for $3.2 million
and quickly offered it to the state for $9.5 million were given
inside information about the plans.
   Dukakis, who the FBI said was not a subject of the
investigation, and administration officials have flatly rejected
allegations there were improper deals and suggested prison
opponents sharpened their attack to get attention during the
presidential campaign.
   ``I don't have any interest in that,'' insists Dorothea
Thomas-Vitrac, the vocal leader of New Braintree's opposition group
_ Conserve Our Small Town. ``We are going after our sitting
governor, not after a presidential candidate.''
   Dukakis' Republican opponent in the fall election, Vice
President George Bush, has steered clear of the controversy.
``Given the fact that it is under some kind of investigation, we
would have no comment,'' said Bush spokewoman Alix Glen.
   But it has drawn national attention because it involves a
central element of the Dukakis candidacy _ a pledge to bring
integrity and competence to the White House _ and offers a glimpse
at his handling of a complex and controversial issue.
   Dukakis named the site for a prison in 1986 and opponents, who
had organized when the state first considered the land two years
earlier, complained that a facility for 500 inmates and several
hundred staff members would overwhelm the town of barely 800 people.
   Thomas-Vitrac concedes opponents have no hard evidence that the
developers were tipped off but contends there ``have to be smoking
guns'' among more than 100 documents Dukakis refuses to make
public, citing executive privilege.
   ``The governor, for reasons known only to him, has lied about
his knowledge of this siting,'' Thomas-Vitrac said last week.
   Dukakis has repeatedly said he did not know who owned the land
when he picked it and requested up to $10 million to buy it. Notes
of an administration aide appear to show one of the developers
names came up twice during a meeting with prison opponents in
Dukakis' office, but the governor has said he does not recall that
and aides have said the name was mentioned only is passing.
   ``The bottom line is that this is a `not in my backyard issue'
and the rest of it is frankly nonsense,'' said James Circo, a
former Dukakis aide who handled the project. ``You'd have to have
been in an igloo somewhere to not know we were looking for prison
space across the state and that New Braintree was one.''
   Thomas-Vitrac contends the withheld documents contain some
reference to developers Daniel Striar and Gary Jacobson. The town
had an agreement with the Seventh Day Adventists Church that the
land would not be sold for a project not in the town's interests.
Thomas-Vitrac contends Striar and Jacobson were Dukakis allies used
to serve as middlemen so the state could get the land without a
fight and reward the developers would with a triple return on their
investment.
   Dukakis denies any deal took place and has said he met Striar
only once. Massachusetts Republicans have been distributing a photo
of that meeting _ on a crowded platform during a 1986
groundbreaking for a community center named for Striar's parents.
Jacobson grew up in the same neighborhood as Dukakis and has
donated to his campaigns, but both men said they are nothing more
than casual acquaintances.
   Striar and Jacobson say they learned of the state's interest
through their broker and that they only considered selling to the
state after local officials rejected their plans to build a
psychiatric hospital.
   An unlikely Dukakis defender, Republican U.S. Attorney Frank
McNamara, said Thurday that he confirmed publicly that Dukakis was
not under investigation ``because I felt it was necessary to
respond to the gossip, innuendo and smear that might sully an
otherwise unsullied reputation.''
   Two appraisals estimate the site's worth between $5 million and
$6 million, according to three Dukakis administration aides, all of
whom requested anonymity. A third appraisal will be completed this
week.
   Negotiations with Striar and Jacobson then will begin, and the
state plans to offer much less than the $9.5 million sought by the
owners two years ago. The two sides may end up in court if no
agreement is reached and the state seeks to take to land by
emminent domain.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
