<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Reagans-Chapel     07-02 0223</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagans-Chapel,200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagans Participate in Chapel Ground Breaking Ceremony</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan and first lady Nancy Reagan
participated in a ground breaking ceremony for a chapel at Camp
David Saturday, the White House announced.
   The Reagans are spending the weekend at the presidential retreat
in the Catoctin Mountains of Maryland.
   The interfaith chapel, scheduled for completion in early 1989,
will have seats for 150 persons.
   Worshipers will enter the chapel through a bell tower with a
bell from the U.S.S. Endicott, a destroyer that saw action in World
War II.
   Funds for construction of the chapel are being raised by a
non-profit corporation known as the Camp David Chapel Fund Inc.,
organized by Kenneth Plummer Sr.,a semiretired construction
contractor from Chambersburg, Pa.
   Plummer camped in the area that now makes up Camp David when he
was a Boy Scout, before it was opened as a presidential retreat for
President Franklin D. Roosevelt, under the name ``Shangri-La,'' in
1942.
   The first donation to the chapel fund, in the amount of $1,000,
was made by the president and Mrs. Reagan.
   Attending the ground breaking ceremony, in addition to the
Reagans and Plummer, were Wayne Smith of Bethesda, Md., and Dr.
Arthur L. Peterson of St. Petersburg, Fla., both directors of the
fund, and the Rev. James Farmer of Toms Creek Methodist Church.
</TEXT>
