<FILEID>AP-NR-07-02-88 1410EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-US-NewZealand     07-02 0506</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-New Zealand,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Danish Formula' Suggested for Ending ANZUS Nuclear Dispute</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. officials say New Zealand may be able to
restore military cooperation with the United States with a formula
similar to that which keeps anti-nuclear Denmark in the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization.
   The subject came up after both U.S. and Australian leaders
voiced regret here the past week at the absence of New Zealand from
the third straight annual ministerial meeting of ANZUS, the
military alliance formed by the three Pacific countries after World
War II.
   U.S.-New Zealand military ties deteriorated after Prime Minister
David Lange in 1985 barred a visiting U.S. warship under his new
Labor Party government's decision to close New Zealand territory to
nuclear-armed ships. The United States later read New Zealand out
of ANZUS in order to protect its policy of refusing to confirm or
deny whether any ship carries nuclear weapons.
   ``There must be a formula, if New Zealand would only look for
it, that would make it possible for them to come back into the
fold,'' U.S. Secretary of State George Shultz told reporters last
Wednesday after a two-day meeting with Australian leaders.
   Asked to elaborate on Shultz's remark, another high U.S.
official told reporters Friday, ``One formula they might look at, I
suppose, is the Danish formula.''
   Another State Department official described the Danish formula
as ``informing their allies by letter that Denmark does not permit
calls at their ports by ships armed with nuclear weapons and leave
it at that.''
   The U.S. officials spoke on condition they not be identified.
   Denmark and the United States have announced settlement of a
dispute similar to the U.S.-New Zealand controversy that erupted
when the Danish Parliament in April adopted a resolution requiring
the government to notify visiting warships of Denmark's 31-year-old
ban on nuclear weapons.
   After new, but inconclusive, elections waged partly on the
issue, Denmark's coalition prime minister, Poul Schlueter, told the
Parliament on June 7 that allied governments had been informed of
Denmark's general policy banning atomic weapons during peacetime,
and that in cases of specific ship visits foreign governments would
be told that Denmark assumes the visit is in compliance with Danish
rules.
   ``The government considers that this procedure respects both the
Danish non-nuclear policy and the views of our allies,'' Schlueter
said.
   State Department spokesman Charles Redman said June 7 the United
States had noted the prime minister's statement and one by Danish
Foreign Minister Uffe Ellemann-Jensen that the formula ``respects
the policy of our allies neither to confirm nor to deny the
presence of nuclear weapons on their naval vessels.''
   U.S. officials have said a similar arrangement is used on U.S.
port visits to Norway.
   New Zealand has not recently suggested using the Danish formula
and it would be up to it to take the initiative on the matter, said
one of the State Department officials. Prime Minister Lange in the
past has likened New Zealand's nuclear ban to those of the
Scandinavian NATO allies.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880702-0106 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-02-88 1418EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Pope-Excerpts     07-02 0600</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pope-Excerpts,0611</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Excerpts of Pope's Apostolic Letter</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Vatican-Lefebvre, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The following are excerpts of Pope John Paul
II's apostolic letter released Saturday, as translated from Italian
by The Associated Press:
   With great distress the church has observed the illegitimate
ordination of bishops performed June 30 by Archbishop Marcel
Lefebvre, who made useless years of efforts to assure that the
priestly Fraternity of St. Pius X ... was in full communion with
the church. ...
   This act of disobedience _ which signifies the outright
rejection of the Roman primate _ constitutes a schismatic act. In
carrying out this act, despite the formal `monitum' (warning) sent
to them by the cardinal prefect of the Congregation for Bishops
last June 17, Monsignor Lefebvre and the priests Bernard Fellay,
Bernard Tissier de Mallerais, Richard Williamson and Alfonso de
Galarreta have incurred the grave penalty of excommunication as
foreseen under ecclesiastical discipline. ...
   The results of the movement promoted by Monsignor Lefebvre
should and ought to be the motive for all Catholics to reflect
sincerely on their own faithfulness to the tradition of the church.
...
   I would also like to call the attention of theologians and other
experts in ecclesiastical science, in order that these also feel
summoned by the present circumstances. In fact, the ... teachings
of the Second Vatican Council call for a renewed examination (of
the faith), which brings to light the Council's continuity with the
tradition (of the church), especially on those points of doctrine
which, perhaps because of their novelty, have not yet been
understood well by some sectors in the church. ...
   Under the present circumstances, I would like above all to
appeal solemnly and from the heart, in a fatherly and brotherly
way, to all those who have in some way been linked to the movement
of Archbishop Lefebvre, so that they understand the serious
obligation to remain united with the Vatican of Christ in the unity
of the Catholic Church, and not continue to aid that movement in in
any way. ...
   No one should ignore that formal adhesion to the schism
constitutes a grave offense to God and leads to excommunication
established by the right of the church. ...
   To all these Catholic faithful, who feel close to some older
liturgical forms and disciplines of the Latin tradition, I would
like to express my will ... to facilitate their spiritual unity
with the church, through the means necessary to guarantee respect
for their just aspirations. ...
   Keeping in mind the importance and complexity of the problems
referred to in this document, and in virtue of my apostolic
authority, I establish the following:
   a. The creation of a commission, with the responsibility of
working with the bishops, the departments of the Roman Curia and
interested groups to facilitate complete unification with the
church of the priests, seminarians, religious communities or
individuals that have been linked to the fraternity founded by
Monsignor Lefebvre and who would like to remain united to the
successor of Peter in the Catholic Church, preserving their
spiritual and liturgical traditions, in line with the protocol
signed last May 5 by Cardinal (Joseph) Ratzinger (head of the
Congregation for the Doctrine of the Faith) and Monsignor Lefebvre.
   b. This commission will have a cardinal as its president and be
composed of other members of the Roman Curia ...
   c. Moreover, the spirit of those who feel tied to the Latin
liturgical tradition must be respected, through a broad and
generous application of the directive ... allowing use of the Roman
Missal such the typical edition of 1962.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
