<DOCNO> AP880702-0110 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-02-88 1433EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BrawleyCase Bjt   07-02 0817</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brawley Case, Bjt,0836</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tawana Brawley: Lost in the Shuffle</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note language in 11th graf</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICK HAMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As the Tawana Brawley case becomes ever more
complicated, the focus has shifted from the black teen-ager to her
three advisers and their racial politics. And the crucial question
_ What happened when she disappeared for four days last year? _ has
been obscured.
   Although she has maintained an almost complete public silence,
Tawana Brawley is famous. She has made the cover of People magazine
and was the subject of a ``Donahue'' program. Her picture is all
over the newspapers, whether she attends the theater on the arm of
an adviser or visits the church where her mother has sought
sanctuary.
   But the Brawley case has become less and less about Miss Brawley
and more and more about the tactics and motives of her publicist,
the Rev. Al Sharpton, and her lawyers, Alton Maddox and C. Vernon
Mason.
   Miss Brawley disappeared from her home in Wappingers Falls,
N.Y., for four days last November. She was found in a garbage bag,
her hair cut and her body smeared with excrement and marked with
racial slurs.
   She has said she was abducted and sexually molested by six white
men, one of whom had a badge, but questions have been raised about
her story, including suggestions that Miss Brawley was at a party
during part of the time she was missing.
   Her mother, Glenda Brawley, has said that the family initially
cooperated with authorities, but they stopped assisting after she
and the advisers felt that local and state officials were trying to
protect the guilty.
   The advisers say that the Tawana Brawley case illustrates how
the state's criminal justice system consistently discriminates
against blacks.
   The case has been unorthodox from the start, but in recent weeks
a series of bizarre developments has diverted attention from the
alleged victim to those around her.
   First, since the teen-ager would not talk, investigators
subpoenaed her mother to testify before a grand jury. Rather than
cooperate, she sought sanctuary in a church in Brooklyn's black
Bedford-Stuyvesant section.
   Sharpton challenged the special prosecutor, state Attorney
General Robert Abrams, to arrest her and ``show the nation the
moral beast you are.'' Abrams stayed put, and so did Glenda Brawley.
   That was when Sharpton aide Perry McKinnon defected. He charged
that Sharpton, Mason and Maddox, in fact, had no evidence that
would shed light on what happened to Miss Brawley, and that they
were using her case to fuel a political movement. He quoted
Sharpton as saying the case could make the advisers ``the biggest
niggers in New York.''
   McKinnon characterized the Brawley advisers' claim to evidence
of what really happened ``a pack of lies,'' and said, ``The Tawana
Brawley story may be that there is no Tawana Brawley story.''
   Sharpton counterattacked, denouncing McKinnon as a gofer who had
no access to the Brawleys or their advisers' deliberations.
Sharpton also described McKinnon as a killer (he was a soldier in
Vietnam), a psychopath (McKinnon received psychiatric treatment
after returning from Vietnam) and a bigamist (McKinnon did not
complete divorce proceedings to end his first marriage).
   A week later an unemployed former Navy technician, Samuel
McClease, claimed to have been promised $11,000 by Sharpton to bug
Mason's home and office and Sharpton's home in order to protect
Sharpton if the case began to unravel.
   McClease told WCBS-TV he had tapes that substantiated his
allegations, which generally supported McKinnon's.
   Polls showed that New Yorkers, including an overwhelming share
of whites and a majority of blacks, believed that Glenda Brawley
and her advisers had not handled the case responsibly, and that the
latter were lying.
   But then came another jolt _ the FBI said the tapes McClease
produced were blank and appeared never to have been used, and
charged McClease with obstruction of justice and perjury.
   Investigators who thought they had seen everything rolled their
eyes and shook their heads. R. Scott Greathead, first assistant
state attorney general, was more restrained than most, calling the
blank tapes ``another unexpected development in a case that has
been full of many surprising twists and turns.''
   Sharpton was jubilant. ``We are coming to get our deed papers,''
he said, referring to what he said would be a $100 million libel
suit against WCBS. ``We gonna go see what color curtains we want in
our new building.''
   But the flamboyant preacher also had reason for concern: he
reportedly was being investigated by the Internal Revenue Service
for not filing tax returns.
   At the end of the week a standoff again seemed to have been
reached, with both sides overwhelmed by the absurdity and
unexpectedness of developments.
   It was left for Gov. Mario Cuomo to state the obvious: The case
will be resolved only if ``Tawana Brawley or her mother would
speak. ... Just tell us what happened.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
