<HEAD>Eight Die In Election-Day Violence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least eight people were killed and 28
injured in violence that plagued village council elections in
northern Uttar Pradesh state, the Press Trust of India said
Saturday.
   The news agency said one person was killed and eight injured in
clashes between rival groups in Agra district, 112 miles south of
New Delhi, during the elections on Friday.
   Some of the injured suffered gunshot wounds, it said.
   The agency said four people were killed and 20 injured in
fighting in Muzzafarnagar district, north of New Delhi, and three
deaths were reported from other areas in the state.
   More than 25,000 villages voted in elections to the councils on
Friday, and another round of polling is scheduled Tuesday.
   Candidates are not formally affiliated with political parties
but are supported by various political groups.
   Press Trust said more than 65 people were arrested in connection
with the violence.
