<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--NaturalFireworks     07-02 0157</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Natural Fireworks,0161</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nature May Provide Its Own Fire Works Despite State-Wide Ban</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Holiday Rdp</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADISON, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most Fourth of July fireworks have been
banned in Wisconsin because the drought has raised the risk of
fire, but nature may provide its own display of colors and lights,
an entomologist says.
   Fireflies and glowworms might help brighten the holiday
festivities across Wisconsin.
   ``There'll be a little bit of natural fireworks this weekend,''
said Phillip Pelliteri Jr., an entomologist with the University of
Wisconsin Extension in Madison.
   The firefly population has been down the last three years but
has increased recently with a population growth of glowworms the
last three weeks, he said. Glowworms are the larval stage of
fireflies.
   The fireflies may also be an asset for holiday celebrations
because they feed on pesky insects.
   Pellitteri said wasp and mosquito populations are also down and
``it's one of the few blessings of the drought.''
</TEXT>
