<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WimbledonNewspage 1stLd-Writethru a0620 07-02 0226</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wimbledon Newspage, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0620,0227</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Graf Defeats Navratilova for Women's Title at Wimbledon</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 3-4-5 to correct spelling of Graf</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WIMBLEDON, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nineteen-year-old Steffi Graf defeated
eight-time Wimbledon winner Martina Navratilova on Saturday to
capture her first Wimbledon crown and continue her domination of
women's tennis this year.
   The West German's 5-7, 6-2, 6-1 victory at the All England
Tennis Championships stopped Navratilova from winning a record nine
singles titles on the famed grass courts.
   Graf's win follows victories at two earlier Grand Slam events
this year, the Australian and French Opens. If she takes the U.S.
Open in September, she will become the first person in 18 years to
sweep the Grand Slam circuit in the same year.
   Graf, who took over the No. 1 ranking in the world from
Navratilova last August, became the youngest Wimbledon women's
champion since 17-year-old American Maureen Connelly won in 1952.
She is the first German woman to win since Cilly Aussem in 1931.
   American Navratilova, 31, did not lose without a fight, winning
six games in a row to wrap up the first set and taking a 2-0 lead
in the second. But then Graf used her stinging forehand and
devastating speed to take the final two sets.
   West Germany's Boris Becker and Sweden's Stefan Edberg meet
Sunday in the men's final.
</TEXT>
