<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SolutionSearch     07-02 0273</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Solution Search,0283</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Finding The Solution</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Retransmits to fix cycle designator</NOTE>
<DATELINE>VICTORIA, British Columbia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Canadian Search and Rescue
Coordination Center found the Solution this week _ three times.
   The Solution, a fishing boat, was put back on course twice when
it reported itself lost, said Canadian Coast Guard spokesman
William Frowd.
   But the third time, the vessel was towed into port.
   The saga began Wednesday, when the Solution's captain radioed
that he was lost on a trip from Cape Scott to Hakai Passage, north
of Vancouver Island.
   An aircraft went to the area along with another fishing vessel
and helped the Solution get back on the course, but Thursday
morning search and rescue officials got another call.
   This time, a Canadian Forces tracker plane used directional
equipment to find the Solution. The boat's captain decided to head
for Port Hardy on the northeastern tip of Vancouver Island, and was
helped to get on that course.
   But 4{ hours later, yet another call came in.
   The Solution eventually was found, again, by another fishing
vessel, about 20 miles from where it was during the preceding call.
   The vessel was then taken in tow by another boat to Hartley Bay.
   Coast Guard Cpl. Randy Young said Friday that the vessel
appeared to have problems with equipment that wasn't working, an
oil leak that caused the engine to break down and a depth sounder
that did not work.
   Young said he hoped the Royal Canadian Mounted Police would
``have a chat'' with the Solution's captain.
   ``We've got a line on her now,'' said Frowd. ``There's no way
she can get lost.''
</TEXT>
