<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel     07-02 0517</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel,0532</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israeli Troops Clash With Arab Protesters; Palestinian Youth
Reported Killed</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel-Pilgrimage, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONI RABIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli troops clashed with Arab youths in at
least seven towns and refugee camps in the occupied territories
Saturday. Hospital officials and radio reports said a 17-year-old
Palestinian was killed.
   An army spokeswoman denied the youth was shot by soldiers and
said troops used only tear gas and rubber bullets to break up the
protests.
   The death brings the number of Palestinians killed to 215 since
an uprising against Israeli rule in the occupied territories began
Dec. 8. Four Israelis also have been slain.
   Police also fired tear gas to disperse Palestinian youths
blocking a road in the Arab town of Shufat, outside Jerusalem,
police spokesman Rafi Levy said.
   The army said two unidentified tourists were wounded slightly
when a bus was stoned in the biblical city of Bethlehem.
   In the Gaza Strip, attackers hurled a firebomb at a military
patrol in Gaza City and residents in nearby Nusseirat showered a
patrol with rocks, the army said. It said one soldier was injured
by a rock.
   Also Saturday, Israeli television reported that military
prosecutors have charged an Israeli soldier with manslaughter in
the slaying of a Palestinian youth. The report said the
unidentified soldier shot a rubber bullet at a Ramallah boy's face
and killed him four months ago. It did not elaborate.
   In the West Bank town of Jenin, Nael Yousef Muhamad Hamaisi died
of a gunshot wound in the head after a demonstration by students
erupted into a stone-throwing clash with soldiers, Israel radio and
hospital officials said.
   The military spokeswoman said the army was investigating reports
of a body brought to Jenin Hospital, but she said soldiers did not
use live ammunition in Jenin.
   Hospital officials also reported a youth was shot in the leg in
Qalandya, north of Jerusalem, and that a man was hit with a bullet
in the hand in Nablus.
   But army spokesmen said they were unaware of either those
clashes or the injuries. The military spokesmen and hospital
officials spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Soldiers dispersed protesters in three other villages and two
refugee camps in the West Bank, and curfews were imposed on Jenin,
Kalkilya and the Jelazoun refugee camp, the military said.
   Hundreds of villagers took part in the clash with soldiers in
Kalkilya after troops entered a school, Arab reports said.
   In southern Israel, about 50 Israeli writers and artists staged
a demonstration near the Ketziot military prison, calling for the
release of the 2,500 Arabs detained without trial, many of them
held in the prison.
   ``If the people got their rights then the artists, Jewish and
Palestinian, would not have to come here,'' said Suleiman Mansour,
a Palestinian artist. ``We demand the release of Palestinian
prisoners, but our biggest demand is self-determination and a state
for the Palestinian people.''
   Israeli author Amos Keinan said several of those jailed are
Palestinian writers who were among the 25 Arabs and Jews signing a
symbolic ``peace treaty'' at a June ceremony in Jerusalem.
</TEXT>
