<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CandidateMistakes 2ndLd-Writethru a0630 07-02 0646</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Candidate Mistakes, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0630,0658</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Missing Initial Could Keep Congresswoman Off Ballot</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 11th graf, ``Schneider signed her xxx, to CORRECT that
STREET, sted Avenue, is her address</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FLIPPEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A congresswoman seeking her fifth term
could be removed from the ballot because of two minor discrepancies
on her declaration of candidacy, authorities said Saturday.
   Two Democratic candidates said they would decide this week
whether to ask the state Board of Elections to invalidate
Republican Rep. Claudine C. Schneider's candidacy because of a
missing middle initial and an address that said ``avenue'' instead
of ``street.''
   Stephen Robertson, a convicted murderer running as an
independent candidate in the district, said Saturday that he had
filed a formal objection with the board based on the two errors.
   Schneider was the second Rhode Island Republican congressional
candidate to encounter a filing error last week. Former state GOP
chairman John A. Holmes Jr. had to withdraw from the race in the
state's other district Thursday after a campaign aide failed to
file his declaration of candidacy by the 4 p.m. deadline.
   Holmes was automatically disqualified because the law setting
the filing deadline allows no exceptions. But Schneider will remain
on the ballot unless the Board of Elections upholds an objection
against her, election officials said. There was no one in the
elections board office Saturday to confirm that Robertson had filed
his petition.
   If Schneider is removed from the ballot, she would have to wage
a write-in campaign. She is unopposed on the Republican ticket.
   An aide, Robert Rendine, said he did not know how the error
occurred but he believed Schneider will remain on the ballot.
   ``The intent of the law is to remove any confusion and make sure
that a candidate is who he says he is,'' Rendine said. ``In the
case of a four-term incumbent congresswoman, I don't think there's
any doubt.''
   The Democratic-controlled Board of Canvassers in Schneider's
hometown of Narragansett voted Friday along party lines to
invalidate her filing form because her signature and address on the
form did not match those on her voter registration card.
   State law requires the form and the registration to match
exactly. In March, the Board of Elections threw a would-be Jesse
Jackson delegate off the presidential primary ballot because of the
same middle-initial problem faced by Schneider. That case is now in
federal court.
   Schneider signed her form with her middle initial, which does
not appear on her registration, and listed her address as 56
Central Ave., although her registration gives her address _
correctly _ as Central Street.
   ``We thought it was kind of trite ourselves, but we thought it
was our job to determine whether they matched to the letter of the
law,'' said Walter V. Boyle, one of two Democrats on the
three-member Board of Canvassers.
   After the Narragansett board's vote, Secretary of State Kathleen
S. Connell, a Democrat whose office is responsible for elections,
said she would issue Schneider nomination papers anyway.
   ``We were not elected to knock people off the ballot,'' Connell
said. ``I don't think the electorate wants elections decided by
initials and periods.''
   Boyle said the Narragansett board will not file a formal
objection, but Ruth Morgenthau and Paul O. Iacono, the two
Democrats competing in the Sept. 14 primary for the right to
challenge Schneider, said they might do so.
   ``It doesn't make any difference whether it's George Bush or
John Holmes or Claudine Schneider or John Doe in the street. The
law is the law,'' Iacono said. ``If you start making exceptions,
then all those other people in past years who have not had
exceptions made will be left out.''
   Morgenthau took a somewhat softer line. ``I expect to win this
election on my merits and I don't like to see a candidate
disqualified on technicalities,'' she said.
</TEXT>
