<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Fatah-Israel     07-02 0180</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fatah-Israel,0184</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arafat Deputy Criticizes Call For Direct Talks With Israel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TUNIS, Tunisia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The deputy chairman of Yasser Arafat's
Fatah organization said Saturday a call by an Arafat aide for
direct negotiations with Israel was premature.
   Salah Khalaf, the No. 2 man in Fatah _ the largest group in the
Palestine Liberation Organization _ criticized the timing of the
proposal made last month by Bassam Abu Sharif, Arafat's spokesman.
Arafat is chairman of the PLO, an umbrella organization of
different Palestinian factions.
   ``My objection is less to the substance of Bassam's declaration
than to the language and the concessions expressed,'' Khalaf said
in an interview on Radio Tunis. He said he was speaking only for
himself and not on behalf of Fatah.
   Sharif's statement ``came at the moment when the Palestinian
people are in insurrection against the Israeli occupiers who
exercise an implacable oppression against this people,'' Khalaf
said. He referred to the uprising by Palestinians in the
Israeli-occupied West Bank of the Jordan River and Gaza Strip.
   Arafat has not said if he authorized Sharif's statement.
