<FILEID>AP-NR-07-02-88 1631EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Robeson-Indians     07-02 0457</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Robeson-Indians,0472</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Rules In Favor Of Hatcher, Jacobs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBIN P. TEATER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court ruling could lead
to the release of two Tuscarora Indians who have been held without
bond for six months while awaiting trial on hostage-taking charges,
an attorney said Saturday.
   Attorney William Kunstler said the 4th U.S. Court of Appeals
ruled Thursday that a federal magistrate did not provide a timely
detention hearing for Eddie Hatcher and Timothy Jacobs last
February.
   ``Imagine, they have lost a half-year of their lives,'' Kunstler
said.
   Kunstler, in a telephone interview from New York, said he
received a copy of the opinion on Saturday. The appeals court in
Richmond, Va., was closed for the holiday weekend and the ruling
could not be independently confirmed.
   The court ruled that the magistrate failed to hold a detention
hearing within the required five days, Kunstler said. The appeals
court sent the case back to U.S. District Court in Raleigh for
``prompt determination of appropriate conditions of pretrial
release,'' Kunstler said.
   Hatcher, 30, and Jacobs, 19, are set to go on trial July 11 on
federal charges of hostage-taking and manufacturing illegal
firearms. The two held up to 20 people hostage Feb. 1 at The
Robesonian newspaper offices in Lumberton, near the South Carolina
border.
   The hostages were freed after the two negotiated a deal that
included the establishment of a state task force to investigate
their charges of alleged corruption among Robeson County officials.
No one was injured in the incident.
   Hatcher and Jacobs were being held Saturday in held in the
Craven County Jail in New Bern, about 120 miles east of Lumberton.
   The two men had gone before Magistrate Wallace Dixon on Feb. 2
but didn't have their detention hearing until Feb. 17. At that
time, Dixon ordered them held without bond.
   Kunstler said Dixon contends the two Indians waived their
detention hearing, saying they were afraid to be released. But
Kunstler said defendants cannot legally waive their own hearing.
   Attorneys for Hatcher and Jacobs appealed in April before U.S.
District Court Judge Terrence Boyle, but he upheld the magistrate's
decision.
   ``A lot of the delays here are the judges ... they just don't
give a damn about the Indians,'' said Kunstler, who is with the
Center for Constitutional Rights.
   Kunstler said attorneys would seek a hearing before Boyle next
week on the release of Hatcher and Jacobs.
   Another attorney for the two men, Bob Warren of the Christic
Institute South of Carrboro, N.C., was trying to reach Assistant
U.S. Attorney John Stuart Bruce on Saturday to discuss the matter,
said Gayle Korotkin, also of the institute.
   Telephone calls to Bruce's home on Saturday were not answered.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880702-0134 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-02-88 1635EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-Reaction Bjt   07-02 0748</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Reaction, Bjt,0768</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Party Conference The Talk of the Town in Moscow</HEAD>
<BYLINE>With AM-Soviet Party Rdp, Bjt
^By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   From a woman wearing a button showing fallen
reformer Boris Yeltsin to a spirited conversation between shoppers
in a food store, the Communist Party conference encouraged ordinary
Soviets to speak their minds.
   ``It was a lesson in democracy,'' proclaimed Alexei Medvedev, a
35-year-old scientist encountered Saturday by a reporter in
downtown Moscow.
   Excitement over the four-day conference that ended Friday was
evident. When a reporter asked one Soviet in the street for his
reaction, at least 100 other people gathered to listen or join in.
Many carried newspapers with extensive reports on the proceedings.
   The hottest sensations of the conference, according to about a
dozen Soviets gathered in 86-degree heat, were speeches Friday by
Yeltsin and the No. 2 man in the Kremlin, Yegor K. Ligachev, who
skewered Yelstin's appeal for rehabilitation.
   In his speech, Yeltsin continued the blunt talk that made him
popular among Muscovites but that led to his ouster as Moscow party
boss in November and from his non-voting seat on the ruling
Politburo in February.
   Yeltsin complained the party's reform proposals didn't go far
enough and said his only mistake in speaking out last October
before the party Central Committee was that he spoke too soon.
   But Ligachev, a rival of Yeltsin and considered a conservative
counterweight to Gorbachev on the Politburo, said Yeltsin was full
of ``destructive energy'' and hadn't learned his lesson.
   At one Moscow food store, several Soviets were overheard
condemning Ligachev. The scene was similar on Pushkin Square.
   ``Yeltsin's speech was superb,'' a woman shouted to a reporter.
``Then Ligachev spoke, and he's a scandal monger.'' The woman then
stalked off.
   Former political prisoner and dissident journalist Lev Timofeyev
said the conference was the most lively and democratic Communist
Party meeting in recent times, but that it skirted key issues.
   ``For us, practical results will be whether they release
political prisoners, how they treat the independent press and
whether they end repression against people in independent groups,''
Timofeyev said by telephone.
   A man who would identify himself only as Roger called The
Associated Press bureau in Moscow to read a statement saying, ``The
conference has been a total collapse of all our hopes.
   ``It marks the start ... It is the start of a new era of
repressive regime,'' the man said.
   Yuri Mityunov, a spokesman for the Democratic Union, a fledgling
political group offering itself as an alternative to the Communist
Party, said by telephone the conference was ``a victory of
conservative revolutionists.''
   ``It is not the radical reform that people expected,'' Mityunov
said. ``It is only restructuring of the system of bureaucratic
management of the country, and I think it won't help solve the very
difficult problems.''
   Noting that Gorbachev's call for more openness is not a
guarantee of free speech, Mityunov said three members of his group
were detained Friday night and fined or jailed for seeking
signatures on a petition demanding that jailed Democratic Union
activists be released.
   The crowd on Pushkin Square, which has become a gathering place
for political activists and those curious enough to want to watch
demonstrations, was grateful for the chance to hear Ligachev on
television.
   ``Yesterday we saw who Ligachev really is,'' Medvedev said. ``
He's a demagogue.'' Medvedev lived in Sverdlovsk while Yeltsin was
party boss there before coming to Moscow, and he remains a Yeltsin
partisan.
   Irina Bogantsyeva, a teacher, displayed a button she said she
made after Yeltsin got in trouble in October. She had typed
Yeltsin's name on a newspaper photograph, encased it in plastic and
affixed it to her blouse.
   ``The only reason I haven't turned in my party membership
card,'' Bogantsyeva said angrily, ``is that I belong to the same
party to which Boris Nikolayevich Yeltsin belongs.''
   Another woman proposed forming a ``Yeltsin Defense Committee''
and a third, Nina P. Shumilkina from Alma Ata, capital of the
Kazakhstan republic, claimed: ``If we started a petition in defense
of Yeltsin, millions would sign it.''
   Ligachev denied in his speech that he opposed perestroika,
Gorbachev's program to modernize the political and economic system.
But Shumilkina said that ``if Ligachev were at the wheel,
perestroika would come to a standstill.'' Medvedev said the
conference and broadcasts of its activities were landmarks.
   ``Yesterday was a historic day,'' he said. ``We finally got real
political debate, and it was shown on television.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
