<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DefenseProbe-Lyons     07-02 0437</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Defense Probe-Lyons,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ex-Pacific Fleet Chief Accuses Military Officials of Trying To
Smear Him</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The former commander of the U.S. Pacific
Fleet denied that he is involved in the Pentagon bribery and fraud
scandal being investigated by the Justice Department and accused a
``very vindictive clique'' of trying to destroy him and former Navy
Secretary John F. Lehman.
   Retired Adm. James A. ``Ace'' Lyons Jr. retired last Oct. 1
after serving two years as commander of the Pacific fleet.
According to Pentagon sources, Lyons was prodded into retirement by
Lehman's successor as Navy secretary, James Webb. Lyons has worked
as a consultant to the McDonnell Douglas Corp. since at least last
December.
   Lyons said in an interview published in Saturday's editions of
the Los Angeles Times that top Navy officials approved the
consulting contract with McDonnell Douglas at a time when they knew
the FBI was investigating alleged fraud within the defense industry.
   The Navy confirmed to the newspaper that Lyons was cleared to
work for McDonnell Douglas.
   ``I'm not associated with this other crap,'' Lyons said,
referring to allegations that defense consultants have used
classified information to help companies win military contracts.
``So why in the hell was I even brought into this other than to
discredit me.''
   Neither Lyons nor Lehman is a target of the ongoing fraud
investigation.
   However, Lyons' name appeared on a search warrant served at
McDonnell Douglas' St. Louis headquarters stated that investigators
were seeking any contracts, agreements, reports, payment records or
any other documents ``relating to the work of Ace Lyons for the
McDonnell Douglas from December 1987 through 1988.
   Lyons said his job with McDonnell Douglas was to convince the
South Koreans that they needed an all-weather, night fighter-attack
plane such as the F-18 produced by McDonnell Douglas.
   Lyons told the Times that Navy officials gave McDonnell Douglas
the go-ahead to hire him so that he and Lehman would be embarrassed.
   ``We've got a very vindictive clique who wants to destroy Lehman
and me, certainly with Lehman being the real target,'' Lyons was
quoted as saying.
   Both Webb and Justice Department chief spokesman Patrick S.
Korten denied the retired admiral's allegations.
   ``That's an odd combination of ignorance and meglomania,''
Korten said.
   Webb told the Times that the accusations were ``absolutely
ridiculous'' and that he had nothing to do with any effort to
discredit Lehman.
   ``There are people who don't like Lehman, people who don't like
me,'' Webb said. ``That is the name of the game when you go into
government. If people are using this against Lehman, it has nothing
to do with me.''
</TEXT>
