<FILEID>AP-NR-07-02-88 1652EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DroughtRdp     07-02 0673</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought Rdp,0688</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Some Drought Areas Get Rain But Not Enough</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Rain fell Saturday over some sections of the nation's drought
belt, but not enough to break the back of the dry spell, and
Virginia farmers who were helped two years ago by donated hay
returned the favor to an Ohio village.
   And the drought created a mini religious dispute in Illinois,
where Gov. James R. Thompson declared Sunday ``a day of prayer for
rain.''
   Thompson's action angered American Atheists, based at Austin,
Texas. ``Government must stop telling citizens when to pray, what
to pray, how to pray or even if they should pray,'' the group said
in a statement Saturday.
   Showers and thunderstorms spread during the morning from
northwestern Texas and the Texas Panhandle into southwestern
Oklahoma and from Arkansas across western Tennessee, northern
Mississippi and Alabama.
   More than an inch of rain fell on parts of central and northern
Arkansas, flooding some streets in North Little Rock, and the
storms knocked out electricity to thousands of customers.
   ``It certainly has helped out an awful lot,'' meteorologist Mike
Thompson in Little Rock said of the rain. But he added that some
parts of the state haven't had a drop in weeks and ``We're still
anywhere from two to 12 inches below normal in the state.
   ``We're going to need a couple of more weeks of weather like
this to really make a dent in the drought, and it doesn't look like
that will be the case.''
   In Michigan's central Upper Peninsula, crews reported about 85
percent containment Saturday of a fire that burned 1,200 acres in
the tinder-dry Hiawatha National Forest, a U.S. Forest spokeswoman
said.
   The fire forced about 60 families to evacuate their homes
overnight along Lake Michigan's Little Bay de Noc, but they were
allowed back early Saturday, said spokeswoman Mary Mumford. Two
outbuildings were destroyed, she said.
   A section of U.S. 2 east of Rapid River and nearby Wisconsin
Central Railroad tracks were closed for about five hours Friday
night before crews extinguished flames along both routes, Mumford
said.
   Trucks carrying some 2,000 bales of donated hay for
drought-stricken farmers arrived at Coldwater, Ohio, on Saturday as
Virginia farmers returned a favor. The hay was divided among about
50 farmers who were involved in the 1986 haylift to Virginia, when
the Southeast suffered its own drought.
   ``At the time, (1986) I had a lot of hay in my barn and I
thought it was the thing to do,'' said farmer Ralph Heyne, who
donated about 1,500 bales to Virginia. ``It was an easy thing to do
when my barn was full. I wish we were sending it down this time.''
   A Wisconsin official estimates his state's 2-month-old drought
may bankrupt more farmers and slash crop yields and dairy herd
sizes more than any other aspect of the sluggish farm economy of
the 1980s.
   ``It has singly done more damage than anything since the 1930s.
There's nothing that compares to what the drought has done so far,
even if we get good weather from here in,'' said Richard Rodefeld,
an economist with the state Department of Agriculture, Trade and
Consumer Protection.
   Fish biologists in Wisconsin are urging fishermen to use
restraint while officials consider the possibility of curtailing
trout fishing altogether because of the drought. Trout populations
were down 40 percent to 60 percent on two rivers in the Antigo area
surveyed recently.
   ``One of the things that's really important out here is tourism
and the outdoors and when the trout fishermen know the fishing is
down, they don't spend as much money on bait and tackle and hotel
rooms,'' Max Johnson, Wisconsin Department of Natural Resources
fish manager at Antigo, said of the Eau Claire River. ``People come
from all over to fish this stream.''
   An estimated 5 million trout swim in about 8,900 miles of trout
stream in Wisconsin, according to the DNR. Each year, about 200,000
anglers take about 1.75 million trout, said Lee Kernen, DNR chief
of the fisheries section.
</TEXT>
