<HEAD>Thunderstorms Continue In The South</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Rain was widely scattered from Colorado to Florida on Saturday
and temperatures dipped to record lows from the Great Lakes to the
East Coast.
   Showers and thunderstorms extended over Colorado and from Texas
across the lower Mississippi Valley, the central Gulf of Mexico
states, southern Tennessee, northern Georgia, the Florida Panhandle
and southern Florida.
   Rain also was scattered over northern New England and the Oregon
coast.
   Overnight temperatures were unseasonably cool over the
northeastern quarter of the nation.
   Low temperature records included 44 at Asheville, N.C.; 59 at
Augusta, Ga., a tie; 62 at Beaufort, S.C.; 44 at Beckley, W.Va.; 48
at Bristol, Tenn.; 56 at Cape Hatteras, N.C.; 62 at Charleston,
S.C., a tie; 50 at Cincinnati; 55 at Columbia, S.C.; 48 at
Columbus, Ohio; 34 at Elkins, W.Va.; 49 at Greensboro, N.D.; 58 at
Greer, S.C.; 47 at Huntington, W.Va.; 49 at Lynchburg, Va.; 47 at
Mansfield, Ohio; 45 at Muskegon, Mich., a tie; 47 at Parkersburg,
W.Va.; 51 at Providence, R.I., a tie; 47 at Roanoke, Va., ties July
record; 49 at South Bend, Ind.; 46 at Toledo, Ohio; 43 at Traverse
City, Mich., a tie; 55 at Wilmington, N.C.; 47 at Worcester, Mass.,
a tie; and 43 at Youngstown, Ohio, a tie.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 56
degrees at Limestone, Maine, to 107 at Needles, Calif. The low for
the day was 37 at West Yellowstone, Mont.
   For Sunday, scattered showers were forecast over northern Maine.
Scattered rain was forecast over the northern Pacific Coast and
northwestern Montana, with widely scattered showers and
thunderstorms over central Arizona. Widely scattered showers and
thunderstorms also were forecast from southern Tennessee across
Alabama, Georgia, southwestern North Carolina, western South
Carolina and Florida.
   Highs only in the 60s were predicted over northern New England,
along the northern Pacific Coast and along the central coast of
California; in the upper 80s and low 90s over Florida and along the
Gulf of Mexico; in the 90s from the Plains across the upper
Missouri Valley, the Rockies and the Great Basin of Nevada and
western Utah; in the 90s to about 115 over the desert Southwest;
and generally in the 70s and 80s over the remainder of the nation.
