<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Syria-Missiles     07-02 0195</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Syria-Missiles,0199</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Syria Denies Reports It Plans to Buy Chinese Missiles</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DAMASCUS, Syria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A military spokesman on Saturday denied
reports Syria was planning to buy advanced surface-to-surface
missiles from China.
   News reports last month quoted Israeli officials as saying the
government of President Hafez Assad was discussing with China the
possibilty of purchasing the missile that is still in the
experimental stage.
   ``The real fact which is very well known to the Israelis is that
there is no such deal between Syria and China and there is no
discussion about it,'' said the Syrian military spokesman speaking
on condition of anonymity.
   He said Syria has the missiles needed for its defense and
accused Israel of spreading the rumor as a ploy to get more
American aid.
   The news reports said Syria was intending to buy the M-9
missile, which has an estimated range of 375 miles. China may have
tested the missile for the first time in June, according to the
reports.
   Israeli officials said the missile could be a serious threat to
Israel and could be armed with chemical weapons. But they said they
had no information of an imminent sale.
