<FILEID>AP-NR-07-02-88 1720EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-EpiscopalConvention     07-02 0444</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Episcopal Convention,0458</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Episcopalians To Address Issues On Gays, AIDS</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Episcopal Church's 69th General Convention
opened Saturday with a church official saying that while marriage
among homosexuals and the AIDS epidemic are on the agenda they
shouldn't dominate the meeting.
   Presiding Bishop Edmond L. Browning asked about 4,000 people in
his opening address to ``look beyond particular issues to what
unites us,'' expressing concern that the church could become a
``single-issue church.''
   ``I hope that we do not let any one particular issue dominate
the convention. That is not to say that issues are not important,''
he said.
   The triennial convention will look into the issue of setting a
policy to recognize ``single-sex marriages.''
   ``We have a ministry to the gay community,'' Browning said. ``We
are struggling to find out what that means. We are not going to
back away from it, because there are some voices that question
whether this is the thing to do.
   ``The way we can be more understanding is to stay in
communication and avoid a judgmental approach in this ministry.''
   The Rev. David B. Collins, deputy president of the convention's
House of Deputies, said the church should recognize all
relationships regardless of sexual preference.
   ``We have been supportive of (single-sex) marriage and we have
to get back to that,'' Collins said. ``We're being unfaithful to
marriage.''
   Gay rights became an open issue in the church in 1976 when the
general convention affirmed gays as ``children of God,'' decried
violence and prejudice against them and asked a special church
commission to study whether they should be ordained to the
priesthood.
   In 1979, despite a positive recommendation of the special
commission, the convention narrowly defeated a proposal to open the
priesthood to gays. Twenty-one bishops, including Browning,
immediately declared their opposition to the ban.
   Despite the ban, gays continued to be ordained since bishops had
a wide latitude in interpretation within their dioceses.
   Also on the convention's agenda are women's roles in the church
and compassion toward AIDS victims.
   Earlier Saturday, in his address to the opening session of the
House of Deputies, Collins said ``the greatest shame of the
Episcopal church is the lack of intensity of faith.''
   Collins cited a survey by the Washington Post-L.A. Times news
service that showed Episcopalians are less likely than members of
other denominations to say religion is ``very important'' in their
lives.
   ``Overall, 55 percent of Americans and 61 percent of
Protestants, but only 41 percent of Episcopalians, said that
religion was very important,'' Collins said.
   The Episcopal Church has 2.6 million members and 15,000 ordained
clergy in 7,500 parishes in the United States, church officials
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880702-0143 </DOCNO>
