<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FireDeaths     07-02 0437</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fire Deaths,0449</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Investigators Search For Cause Of Fire That Killed Five
Firefighters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HACKENSACK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Flags flew at half staff throughout the
city Saturday for five firefighters killed in one fire, and
condolences came in from other firefighters from around the nation.
   The men killed Friday in a car dealership fire were the first
firefighters killed in action in Hackensack, and their department
brought in counselors to help its 91 members cope with their loss.
   Fire Chief Anthony Aiellos said a police captain from Fort Lee
and two assistants who have had counseling experience met twice
with Hackensack firefighters in an effort to alleviate ``this type
of stress. This hasn't happened in the city before.''
   ``This only happens in other cities, you know?'' he said at a
news conference.
   Firefighters and law enforcement officials from across the
country sent messages of condolence, Aiellos said.
   ``We've had calls from Texas, Atlanta, Georgia, the New York
City Fire Department, It's very touching,'' Aiellos said.
   Flags throughout the city were lowered to half-staff, black
bunting draped a firehouse and Aiellos began meeting with the
victims' families Saturday to try to comfort them.
   ``I'd just like to say there may be as good firefighters in the
country, in the world. There's no better, absolutely none better,''
Aiellos said.
   ``I've seen these guys in operation. When the time comes, they
do their job, no matter the risk involved,' he said.
   The firefighters were killed instantly when the building's
interior roof collapsed at Hackensack Ford and Mazda. The
firefighters were trying to cut a hole in the ceiling so they could
extinguish the fire burning between the false ceiling and the roof.
   Aiellos said the dealership, which he estimated was 30 years
old, met existing building codes when it was constructed. But
revised codes probably would have forced the owners to rethink the
design, he said. He did not say how the construction might have
been different under current fire codes.
   The Bergen County Arson Task Force joined the city's fire
department in investigating the cause of the blaze, but preliminary
investigation indicated that arson was not to blame, Aiellos said.
   Company officials declined to comment and Aiellos said
authorities could not put a dollar figure on the damage.
   Killed in the blaze were Capt. Richard Williams, 54, a 24-year
firefighter who had four children; Lt. Richard Reinhagen, 48, with
23 years in the department and two children; firefighter William
Krejsa, 52, with 24 years' experience and three children;
firefighter Leonard Radumski 38, a 13-year firefighter with one
child; and firefighter Stephen Ennis, 30, a five-year veteran with
one child.
</TEXT>
