<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Jackson     07-02 0419</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson To Take Minority Planks To Floor Of Democratic Convention</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES J. GANS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson said Saturday he will go to the
floor of the Democratic National Convention to push for including a
dozen of his policy proposals in the party's platform.
   ``We ... are determined at this point to take all 12 of our
minority planks to the floor in Atlanta ... in order to inform,
inspire and open up the process, to make our convention one of
substance,'' Jackson said at a news conference on the lawn of his
home.
   The convention's Platform Committee last week overwhelmingly
rejected the planks proposed by Jackson, including a call for
boosting taxes on the wealthy, freezing defense spending, pledging
no first use of nuclear weapons and doubling the money spent on
education.
   ``We will take to the convention ... the kind of program agenda
that will expand our party and make us stronger,'' Jackson said.
   Asked whether he thought his decision might divide the party,
Jackson said that was ``an unfair accusation ... we can have unity
without uniformity.''
   Jackson said he looked forward to discussing the convention and
party platform at his Fourth of July meeting in Boston with
Dukakis, when the candidates and their wives are to have dinner
together and attend a concert.
   Jackson made his remarks after meeting at his home with a group
of key advisers, including his campaign chairman, Willie Brown, the
California Assembly speaker, platform committee chairwoman Eleanor
Holmes Norton, and Walter Fauntroy, the District of Columbia's
non-voting delegate in Congress.
   Dukakis supporters contended that the Jackson proposals would
cost the party support among moderate voters and provide campaign
ammunition to Vice President George Bush.
   Jackson said the Pentagon defense contract procurement scandal
had encouraged him to go to the convention floor with his defense
spending freeze proposal.
   He said ``no one feels any more insecure'' after Defense
Secretary Frank Carlucci announced Friday his decision to freeze
$1.1 billion worth of contracts thought to be tainted.
   ``If we in fact cut our military budget without cutting our
defense and more effectively use our resources for long-term health
care, affordable housing and education, we will be a better and
stronger nation,'' he said.
   Jackson said there had been ``good negotiations'' so far with
the Dukakis camp, which would continue prior to the July 18 start
of the convention, but he said he could not imagine a convention
``where there is simply no floor debate.''
</TEXT>
