<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-Yeltsin     07-02 0628</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Yeltsin,0646</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Full Yeltsin Speech Published, Includes Strong Criticism Of
Leaders</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet Party Rdp</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Newspapers published on Saturday what television
had not shown the day before _ a fired Communist Party official's
stinging criticism of some of the most powerful men in the Soviet
Union.
   Boris N. Yeltsin, the former Moscow Communist Party chief who
was fired in November, denounced Politburo member Mikhail S.
Solomentsev and others who served under the late President Leonid
I. Brezhnev. Brezhnev now is blamed for leading the country into a
period of stagnation and corruption during his rule from 1964-1982.
   But Yeltsin also demanded that such hidden subjects as Communist
Party finances be made public along with detailed biographies of
the nation's leaders and information about their luxurious summer
homes and guest houses.
   Yeltsin made he speech Friday at the final day of the four-day
Communist Party conference.
   Television showed segments of his address, including his appeal
for political rehabilitation but ignored his critical comments.
   Yeltsin was fired as Moscow party chief and removed as a
non-voting member of the ruling Politburo because of his remarks at
a party Central Committee meeting last October. His comments at
that meeting have never been published, but officials said he
blamed the bureaucracy for slowing the pace of reform planned by
Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   In his speech Friday as carried by the Soviet press, Yeltsin
said:
   ``Today it turns out that the only one guilty in the stagnation
was Brezhnev. But where were they who for 10, 15, 20 years, now as
well as then, were on the Politburo? Each time they voted in favor
of various programs.''
   He said those Politburo members brought the country to the brink
of crisis by electing a gravely ill Konstantin U. Chernenko party
leader in 1984. Chernenko died a year later and was succeeded by
Gorbachev.
   Yeltsin accused Solomentsev, 74-year-old head of the party's
Control Commission that is responsible for reviewing allegations of
misconduct by party members, of being soft on officials suspected
of corruption.
   ``I have to say this liberalism from Comrade Solomentsev toward
people who took bribes in the millions raises anxiety.''
Solomentsev was made a non-voting member of the Politburo in 1971
and a full member in 1983.
   Yeltsin said several Politburo members, who he did not identify,
should be made to answer for their part in creating serious
problems and then removed from the ruling body.
   That remark drew applause from some of the 5,000 delegates at
the conference, according to the transcripts published by the
Communist Party newspaper Pravda and government daily Izvestia.
   While Soviet television did not carry Yeltsin's critical
comments, it did cover in full Yegor K. Ligachev's attack on
Yeltsin. The two are political rivals and Yeltsin has urged that
Ligachev, the Kremlin's No. 2 man, quit.
   Yeltsin told the conference he knew how much money local party
organizations contribute to the Central Committee but he didn't
know where it all went.
   ``I only see that besides rational expenditures, they (party
leaders) build luxurious guest houses, sanatoriums and dachas of
such a size that it's embarrassing when people visit from other
(foreign) parties,'' he said.
   He called for open publication of biographies, incomes and other
information about ruling party officials.
   Yeltsin did not directly criticize Gorbachev, but he said he did
not understand the general secretary's proposal to make party
leaders also the head of the corresponding government council. The
plan apparently would ensure continued party dominance of the
government.
   Yeltsin also said that despite Gorbachev's efforts to open up
the party to greater debate and criticism, members of the Central
Committee still were afraid to express their views if they differed
from the party leader.
</TEXT>
