<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Zimbabwe-SAfrica     07-02 0298</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Zimbabwe-SAfrica,0305</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Say South African Commandos Planned To Free Jailed Suspects</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South African commandos failed in a plan
to free four South Africans held in a maximum security prison and
accused of terrorist attacks, security sources said Saturday.
   The sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said an
unspecified number of commandos had planned to intercept a police
convoy carrying the four detainees from a Harare magistrate's court
to the Chikurubi maximum security prison 12 miles outside of Harare
on Thursday.
   They gave no reason why the purported plan failed, but said
weapons and tear gas grenades were found near the route to the
prison.
   The four arrested whites are accused of involvement in five
attacks on African National Congress facilities in Zimbabwe. The
predominantly black ANC is the main guerrilla organization fighting
South Africa's white-dominated government.
   The four suspects appeared briefly Thursday before Harare
Magistrate Leonard Chitunhu and were remanded in custody to July
29. They are identified as Kevin Woods, 35, a former Zimbabwe
central intelligence officer; Michael Smith, 34; Barry Bawden, 30,
and Guy Bawden, 32.
   They were arrested after a car bomb demolished part of a house
occupied by ANC officials in the city of Bulawayo on Jan. 11. The
driver of the car carrying the explosives was killed in the blast.
   There was no official comment from the government on the report
by the security sources that South African commandos had planned to
free the four.
   The sources said that after attacking the police convoy the
commandos intended to use a stolen Zimbabwe air force helicopter to
fly the freed prisoners to an airstrip near the town of Kwekwe, 125
miles southwest of Harare, where a South African transport plane
was waiting to take them out of the country.
</TEXT>
