<FILEID>AP-NR-07-02-88 1908EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Smyrna-Geographic     07-02 0377</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Smyrna-Geographic,0389</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Some In Atlanta Suburb Offended By Magazine's `Redneck' Remark</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SMYRNA, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some folks in this northwest Atlanta suburb
aren't taking too kindly to being called ``redneck'' by National
Geographic.
   In a story about Atlanta in the magazine's July issue, Erla
Zwingle writes of the city's relative youth: ``No matter where I
went, from redneck Smyrna in the northwest to downtown's black
Atlanta University to the old-money bastions of Ansley Park,
Atlantans described their town indulgently as `adolescent.'''
   Former Smyrna Mayor Harold Smith, president of the Smyrna
Historical Society, is spearheading an effort to get the magazine
to apologize.
   ``If the lady had said some people refer to Smyrna as a `redneck
area,' that would be one thing,'' Smith said Saturday. ``But to
categorize our whole town as `redneck' just burned me up.''
   Smith has drafted a resolution of complaint, pointing out that
Smyrna is a booming business center, with corporate headquarters,
major shopping centers and industrial parks, and says that
``redneck'' is ``as derogatory as ... racial slurs ... you
certainly would not print.''
   The Optimist Club of Smyrna passed the resolution Friday, and
Smith plans to present it to the City Council at its next meeting
Tuesday.
   Smith, a subscriber to National Geographic for more than a
decade, said he was especially disappointed in the source.
   ``You might expect it from the (National) Enquirer, but you do
not expect it from National Geographic _ to let a writer
characterize a town like that,'' he said.
   Calls to the Maryland home of National Geographic Society
spokeswoman Mary Jeanne Jacobsen went unanswered Saturday afternoon.
   Ms. Zwingle, who lives in New York, told the Marietta Daily
Journal on Friday that she didn't mean to offend anyone, saying she
had heard many people in Smyrna call the town ``redneck.''
   ``I am sorry to think that someone is upset by something I
wrote,'' she said, adding that she was attempting to show ``the
variety in Atlanta.''
   The writer added that to her, ``redneck'' conveys ``obviously
something rural, the country versus the city'' and an ``educational
level ... a rather limited view of the world.''
   ``I am sure there are some people in very nice homes in nice
sections of Atlanta who share these attributes,'' she said.
</TEXT>
