<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ElvisShow     07-02 0317</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Elvis Show,0327</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Elvis: His Life and Times, in Multimedia Show At Las Vegas Hilton</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT MACY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It takes not one but three Elvis Presley
impersonators to depict the king of rock 'n' roll in a new musical
depicting his life and times.
   The multimedia show ``Elvis: An American Musical'' premiered
Friday night at the Las Vegas Hilton, the resort where the late
entertainer was a top attraction in the late 1960s and early '70s.
   The show, which was developed in association with the Presley
estate, is an elaborate mixture of old movie footage, video and
live performances.
   Among the 40 cast members are three impersonators who depict
Presley at various times of his life _ as a teen-ager getting
started in Memphis, Tenn., as a young man at the height of his
career, and as an older Elvis in the closing years.
   The three sing 40 of the songs made famous by Presley from the
time he graduated from high school in 1953 until his death in
August 1977.
   The show is interspersed with film clips depicting the times of
the entertainer, ranging from racial segregation in the South to
the civil rights unrest, Vietnam War, peace protests and the
assassination of Robert Kennedy.
   There are also clips of Elvis himself, including the famous
appearance on the Ed Sullivan Show, where he first gained national
stardom in the mid-'50s.
   The show ends with film of Presley's funeral cortege and
newscaster David Brinkley proclaiming ``he changed our lives. He
changed the way teen-agers thought about America.''
   The cortege was followed by a montage of Presley and other rock
'n' roll stars for whom he paved the way.
   Among those attending Friday night's premiere were singer Robert
Goulet.
   The show runs through Aug. 28 at the Las Vegas resort, where
Presley established attendance records from 1969 to 1977.
  
</TEXT>
