<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DrunkenDrivers     07-02 0265</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drunken Drivers,0272</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Law Restores Drunken Drivers' Licenses Earlier</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new law restored Colorado driver's licenses to
530 convicted drunken drivers in time for the Fourth of July
weekend.
   The law, which went into effect Friday, says that first-offense
drunken drivers whose licenses had been revoked for at least four
months could apply to get their driving privileges back immediately.
   For those convicted of drunken driving in the future, the
license revocation period for a first offense will be three months.
   The revocation period had been one year.
   The chance for an early return to the road, before their year
was up, drew hundreds of people to the Denver Motor Vehicle
Division office even before it opened Friday.
   ``We processed 214 in less than two hours,'' said Richard
Georgeson, state driver control section chief. ``The line was
outside and around the block.''
   ``It makes me sick,'' said state Rep. Scott McInnis, a former
policeman who opposed the amendment making the shorter revocation
period retroactive. ``Putting 500 convicted drunken drivers behind
the wheel sooner than they should _ it's definitely a step
backward.''
   The new law aims to toughen drunken-driving enforcement by
reducing the legal blood-alcohol threshold defining drunkenness
from 0.15 to 0.10 percent. Amendments attached to the bill
shortened the license revocation period and provided for the
shorter period to apply retroactively.
   The bill's original sponsor, Sen. Jim Lee, said he didn't like
the idea of reducing the revocation period for first offenders
retroactively. However, he said, studies show that very few first
offenders go on to become multiple offenders.
</TEXT>
