<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Matlovich 1stLd-Writethru a0594 07-02 0554</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Matlovich, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0594,510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gay Vietnam War Hero Buried With Full Military Honors</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS lead to restore AP logo; SUBS 3rd graf pvs, bgng: ``He
was ...'' to CLARIFY that salute was 3 volleys by 7 riflemen sted
21-gun salute.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leonard Matlovich, a Vietnam War hero whose
1975 discharge from the Air Force for his avowed homosexuality
became a rallying point for gay rights activists, was buried here
Saturday with full military honors.
   Matlovich, 44, died June 22 in Los Angeles, from complications
associated with AIDS, a fatal virus-borne disease whose chief
victims have been homosexual men and intravenous drug abusers.
   He was buried in Congressional Cemetery just 20 blocks from the
U.S. Capitol in a ceremony that mixed the military pomp of a
horse-drawn caisson and a traditional three-volley salute by seven
riflemen with eulogies from gay rights activists.
   ``The Air Force finally did it right and on Leonard's terms
today,'' said Frank Kameny, a Washington gay rights activist who
was instrumental in counseling Matlovich on testing the military's
ban on homosexuality.
   ``It's a pity that they didn't do it 13 years ago,'' Kameny said
as an Air Force color guard departed the cemetery.
   Matlovich, who was awarded a Purple Heart after stepping on a
Viet Cong land mind and the Bronze Star for killing two Viet Cong
soldiers attacking his post, first challenged the Air Force's rules
on homosexuality in 1975.
   At the time, he was a technical sergeant working as a drug and
alcohol abuse counselor at Langley Air Force Base outside
Washington with nearly 12 years of service.
   ``After some years of uncertainty I have arrived at the
conclusion that my sexual preferences are homosexual as opposed to
heterosexual,'' Matlovich said in a memorandum to his commanding
officer. ``I have also concluded that my sexual preference will in
no way interfere with my Air Force duties.''
   Following a hearing, Matlovich was given a general discharge
from the service. His challenge of the action in court put his face
on the cover of Time magazine, and in 1980 the Air Force was
ordered to reinstate him with back pay.
   Months later, Matlovich and the Air Force reached an
out-of-court settlement in which he was paid a total of $160,000 in
back pay and other compensation and given an honorable discharge.
   ``When Leonard lived in the neighborhood, he would come over
here and walk,'' Lee Jenny, the administrator of the cemetery where
many members of the nation's first Congresses are buried, recalled
Saturday. ``He loved the history. He was one of the most patriotic
men I ever met.''
   Ms. Jenny helped design the tombstone that Matlovich wanted for
his grave as a memorial to gay and lesbian Vietnam veterans. It is
located on a plot less than 20 yards from where former FBI Director
J. Edgar Hoover and Hoover's longtime associate and friend, Clyde
Tolson, are buried.
   Matlovich's tombstone includes in the top corners pink triangles
that were used by Nazis during World War II to identify homosexuals
in concentration camps and that have since been adopted as a symbol
in the gay rights struggle.
   Under the triangles is the inscription:
   ``A Gay Vietnam Veteran''
   ``When I was in the military they gave me a medal for killing
two men and a discharge for loving one.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880702-0158 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-02-88 1929EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Philippines     07-02 0469</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines,0486</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Third Human-Rights Lawyer Killed In Manila</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By YASMIN ARQUIZA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gunmen on Saturday assassinated a
human-rights lawyer at a busy intersection near the presidential
palace. He was the third human-rights lawyer killed in the
Philippines in two weeks.
   A nationwide coalition of civil rights groups condemned the
killing and suggested police or the military might be behind the
attacks.
   Emmanuel Mendoza, 57, was killed as his car was stopped at an
intersection about a half a mile from the palace, according to
police.
   Two men on a motorcycle opened fire on Mendoza, police Cpl.
Porfirio Olais said. The lawyer was taken to a nearby hospital
where he died an hour later, police and hospital authorities said.
   Mendoza was killed two days after a close associate, Nemesio
Prudente, survived an assassination attempt in the same area. It
was the second attempt on Prudente's life.
   Mendoza was a professor at the state-run Polytechnic University
of the Philippines, where Prudente is president.
   On June 18, gunmen killed human-rights lawyer Ramon Cura in his
home near the U.S. Clark Air Base north of Manila. A colleague,
Alfonso Surigao, was shot and killed in his residence in the
central island of Cebu last week.
   Mendoza was a legal counsel of the left-wing People's Party-PNB
and chairman of the Manila Solidarity Alliance, a federation of
slum residents' groups in the capital.
   The secretary-general of the Philippine Alliance of Human Rights
Advocates, Redempto Anda, said Mendoza may have been killed because
he represented slum residents whose communities were being raided
by police in search of communist rebels.
   ``This series of killings has victimized personalities who have
been associated with the legal left,'' the alliance said in a
statement.
   ``That this could go on without the government being able to
solve any single case raises the strong possibilities that certain
segments of the police and the military could be involved in
them,'' the statement said.
   Cura was the lawyer of jailed communist leader Rodolfo Salas,
while Surigao was a chapter president of Amnesty International in
the central Philippine island grouping called Visayas.
   Surigao and Mendoza were both defeated candidates in last year's
congressional elections.
   Prudente, a human rights activist, has been accused by the
military and police of using his school to shelter communist
guerillas. Prudente has denied the allegation.
   President Corazon Aquino has ordered an investigation into the
attempts on Prudente's.
   Investigators have yet to publish their findings on the first
attempted ambush of Prudente in November 1987.
   Human rights groups blamed rightist death squads for that
attempted assassination, which occured a week after soldiers and
policemen chanted ``Kill Prudente!'' during a funeral for a police
captain and three other people killed by communist gunmen in the
capital.
   Security forces have been fighting communist guerrillas since
1969.
</TEXT>
