<HEAD>Jane Fonda, Robert DeNiro to Appear at Agent-Orange Benefit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WATERBURY, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actress Jane Fonda, who has recently
tried to pacify veterans still angry over her 1972 trip to Hanoi,
will appear at a benefit for children with birth defects linked to
Agent Orange, a veterans group announced Saturday.
   Fonda, whose plans to film part of a movie in Waterbury later
this summer sparked protests by some veterans, apologized on
national television last month for posing for photos on a North
Vietnamese anti-aircraft gun during her 1972 trip and for saying
prisoners of war were lying about having been tortured.
   Money raised at the July 29 benefit will go to the Brandy Schieb
Children's Fund, a project of the Stamford-based Vietnam Veterans
Victims of Agent Orange, said the Rev. John A. McColley, rector of
St. Michael's Episcopal Church in Naugatuck and a Vietnam veteran.
   Actor Robert De Niro is also slated to attend the benefit,
organizers said.
   Fonda and De Niro are slated to appear in the movie, ``Union
Street,'' about a working-class woman fighting her way up the
social ladder who teaches an illiterate man to read.
   Holyoke, Mass., and Waterbury were chosen as filming locations
because of their industrial look. But there were protests by
veterans in both towns after the plans for the film were announced.
   The day after the apology was broadcast on ABC's ``20-20'' news
program, Fonda met at St. Michael's with about 25 Vietnam veterans
from Connecticut and Massachusetts. The benefit ``grew out of the
spirit of reconciliation and good'' exhibited during the meeting,
McColley said.
   ``Afterward, a lot of us were standing around saying wouldn't it
be great if now we could all do something together,'' he said.
   The event is being sponsored by a group of Vietnam veterans
calling themselves Veterans Who Care, which includes some of
Fonda's former and present critics, McColley said.
   Exact details of the benefit were not all worked out, but
activities may include a booth where people can get their pictures
taken with Fonda and De Niro, said Stephen Rivers, a Fonda
spokesman.
   ``Jane spoke to De Niro last night and called me to confirm that
he was on board as well,'' Rivers said.
</TEXT>
