<1ST_LINE>r i AM-NicaraguaPhones     07-02 0171</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua Phones,0175</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rates on International Telephone Calls Increased 700 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rates on international telephone calls
have been increased an average 700 percent and on national calls
300 percent, the Sandinista newspaper Barricada reported Saturday.
   Anastasio Gonzalez, vice minister of the Telecommmunications and
Mail Institute, told the newspaper a three-minute call to the
United States, Mexico or Canada that cost 240 cordobas until
Thursday now is 1,920 cordobas.
   The increase would be from $3 to $24 at the official rate of 80
cordobas to the U.S. dollar. On the black market a dollar sells for
more than 300 cordobas.
   Gonzalez said the monthly telephone rate was increased from 200
to 800 cordobas, or from $2.50 to $10 at the official rate.
   The rates, which took effect Friday, follow economic measures
announced June 14 that included devaluation of the cordoba from 10
per dollar to 80.
   Bank interests were increased and salaries boosted 30 percent.
Government controls on salaries of industrial workers were lifted
and prices freed.
</TEXT>
