<1ST_LINE>u a AM-TankExplosion 1stLd-Writethru a0670 07-02 0416</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tank Explosion, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0670,0422</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>At Least Six Injured When 2,500-Gallon Gas Tank Explodes</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with hospital saying number of people
treated numbered six, sted 20; names of injured, description of
explosion, other detail. No pickup. Lake Ozark as name of town, and
Lake of the Ozarks as name of lake are cq</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LAKE OZARK, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 2,500-gallon gasoline tank ruptured and
exploded in flames outside a restaurant Saturday, injuring at least
six people, one critically, authorities said.
   The tank outside Que's Place Restaurant, three miles north of
here, sprang a leak and burst into flames about 3:45 p.m., said
Darrell Cook of the Miller County Sheriff's Department.
   Cook said that based on estimates from officers at the scene,
about 20 people were injured in the accident, but officials at two
hospitals said they treated only six people.
   David Kopriva, 30, of Eldon was flown to the University of
Missouri Hospital in Columbia, said Sgt. Jim Glover of the Missouri
State Water Patrol. He was reported in critical condition with
third-degree burns over 55 percent of his body.
   Dorothy Collins, nursing supervisor at Lake Ozark General
Hospital, said two children were admitted to that hospital: Lauren
E. Wimmer, 10, and Shawn Neville, 12, both of Belleville, Ill. Both
were listed in stable condition.
   Three other people were treated and released from the hospital,
she said.
   Glover said the explosion occurred after a worker began filling
a gasoline tank near the restaurant and noticed that a seam had
broken and gasoline was spilling onto the ground.
   ``The worker went down and advised someone at the restaurant,
and they started to evacuate the area,'' he said.
   The gasoline ignited near the edge of Lake of the Ozarks after
the evacuation was in progress and most of the people were out of
the restaurant, Glover said. Seconds later, there was an explosion.
   ``The restaurant and the dock it was on and five boats were
destroyed in the explosion and resulting fire,'' Glover said. He
said he did not know what caused the explosion.
   A number of people were found in the water after the explosion,
but it was not known whether they were blown into the water by the
force of the blast or if they had jumped, he said.
   Damage from the fire, which was contained about an hour later,
were estimated at more than $100,000, Glover said.
   Lake of the Ozarks is a popular resort attraction in central
Missouri.
</TEXT>
