<FILEID>AP-NR-07-02-88 2242EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CableDescramblers     07-02 0298</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cable Descramblers,0306</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FBI Cable Probe Nets Four</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four men accused of illegally selling
millions of dollars worth of cable television and satellite
descramblers have been following a two-year FBI investigation.
   Howard Pirofsky, 43, and Jack Pirofsky, 37, both of Clifton
Park, Edward Zibro III, 34, of Cohoes, and Mark Fournier, 36, of
Troy, pleaded innocent at their arraignments Thursday and were
released on their own recognizance.
   The illegal sale and manufacture of descramblers is a
misdemeanor, punishable by up to one year in prison and a $10,000
fine.
   Officials said the illegal sales ring was among the largest in
the country, and sold the components in the United States, Canada,
Puerto Rico and New Guinea.
   ``Indications are that this one is one of the largest, if not
the largest,'' said Jim Allen, director of the Office of Cable
Signal Theft, based at the National Cable Television Association in
Washington.
   Descramblers decode signals to certain cable television pay
channels, allowing viewers to watch the channels without paying for
them.
   Allen said the typical user saved between $30 and $40 a month,
which otherwise would have been paid to so-called ``premium'' pay
channels. Allen said the industry loses $250 million annually to
descrambling pirates.
   Also named in the 86-count indictment were six corporations run
by the men under the names P.G. Video Corp., State Satellite Corp.,
Starview Inc., Sone Associates, Consumer Video Corp. and Trend
Video Corp., according to Frederick Scullin, U.S. attorney for the
northern district of New York.
   The ring allegedly operated between January 1984 and August
1986, violating federal laws that outlaw the manufacture,
distribution and use of cable descramblers by unauthorized
individuals, FBI and federal prosecutors said.
   Descramblers can be sold legally to authorized individuals such
as cable television companies.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
