<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Carlos Salinas de Gortari of the government's
Institutional Revolutionary Party ended his presidential campaign
Saturday with a pledge to modernize Mexico's political and economic
structures.
   ``I am committed to change,'' Salinas de Gortari told throngs of
people from throughout the country gathered at the historic Zocalo
Plaza in downtown Mexico City. ``We must modernize to create a
stronger and sovereign Mexico,'' he said.
   Police estimated the crowd at more than 250,000 while organizers
claimed the rally was the largest in their party's history and said
as many as 700,000 people attended.
   Presidential and congressional elections will be held Wednesday.
   Many of the people at the rally were peasants and labor union
members bused into Mexico City the night before by party organizers.
   Manuel Clouthier, presidential candidate of the opposition
National Action Party (PAN), also closed his campaign with a late
afternoon rally at the Zocalo.
   A crowd estimated by reporters at about 140,000 people gathered
for the windup of the PAN campaign.
   The third major contender in the presidential race is Cuauhtemoc
Cardenas, backed by the National Democratic Front that includes
several leftist parties. Cardenas packed the Zocalo last Saturday
with a similar rally.
   During Salinas de Gortari's speech, the colonial four-story
buldings on both sides of the Plaza were draped with large pictures
of Mexico's revolutionary heroes.
   ``During the campaign you have showed me what to change, what
not to change and how to carry out the changes,'' said the
candidate whose party has been in power for 60 years.
   He promised to eliminate inflation, advance economic development
with the help of private industry and pull Mexico out of its
economic crisis.
   ``We will forge a Mexico our children will be proud of,'' he
said.
