<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Satra-Coke     07-02 0223</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Satra-Coke,0230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grand Jury Subpoena's Coke Trading Partner's Records</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal grand jury investigating the
Coca-Cola's dealings with the Soviet Union has subpoenaed the
records of a trading partner in the deal, an official of the
partner company said.
   New York-based Satra Corp. has delivered the records, Satra
Chairman Ara Oztemel said in a story published Saturday in joint
editions of The Atlanta Journal and The Atlanta Constitution.
   He said he did not know the focus of the probe.
   The newspapers said the Atlanta grand jury is investigating
Coca-Cola for possible illegal activity under the 1977 Foreign
Corrupt Practices Act, which prohibits U.S. companies and
individuals from bribing foreigners or political parties, in
connection with its 1986 agreement to sell Coke in the Soviet Union.
   Coca-Cola has denied any wrongdoing.
   ``I'd like to think they will not find anything,'' Oztemel said
in a telephone interview with the newspapers from his company's
London offices. ``They are wasting valuable time, mostly theirs.''
   Since Soviet law prohibits foreign companies from selling
products for cash and taking the money out of the country,
Coca-Cola and Satra have a three-way deal.
   Under the agreement, Satra buys Soviet-made Lada automobiles to
sell in the United Kingdom and Ireland. The Russians then use the
British currency to buy Coke concentrate made at Coke's plants in
Ireland.
</TEXT>
