<2ND_LINE>AM-Deaths, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0658,0385</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS Riesman obituary. An AM separate on Gradl moved as
a0619.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Johann Baptist Gradl</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Johann Baptist Gradl, a former West German
government minister devoted to reunification of Germany, died
Friday. He was 84.
   Gradl helped found Berlin's Christian Democratic Union party in
1945. He was a member of Parliament from 1957 to 1980 and minister
for German exiles in 1965-66.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Maxwell Sergis Alberts</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Portrait photographer Maxwell Sergis Alberts,
whose subjects included Greta Garbo, Eleanor Roosevelt, Elizabeth
Taylor and Howard Hughes, died Tuesday at age 76.
   Alberts, the son of Hollywood portrait photographer Sergis
Alberts, opened his first studio at 18 with the silent-screen vamp
Theda Bara his first subject. He took over his father's business in
1940 upon the elder Alberts' death.
   Alberts' grandfather had been court photographer to Russian Czar
Nicholas II.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Abelardo Barbosa</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Abelardo Barbosa, a freewheeling
comic who liked to say his goal was to confuse everything but who
worked to forge a distinctly Brazilian style of television, died
Thursday. He was 70.
   Barbosa was known on his amateur hour as Chacrinha, Portugese
for barnyard. He was a medical school graduate who never practiced
as a doctor, gravitating instead to radio and later television.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Hermann Volk</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MAINZ, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cardinal Hermann Volk, the former
Roman Catholic bishop of Mainz and an advocate of ecumenism, died
Friday. He was 84.
   Volk served as bishop from 1962-82 and was known for efforts to
build ties between the Catholic and Protestant churches. Pope Paul
VI named him a cardinal in 1973.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Patsy Nasher</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Patsy Nasher, who with her husband, Raymond
Nasher, assembled one of the finest private art collections in the
world and helped lift the city's reputation in the arts, died of
cancer Friday. She was 59.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Paul Riesman</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NORTHFIELD, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paul Riesman, a professor of
anthropology at Carleton College here since 1961, died of a
ruptured pancreatic aneurysm Wednesday. He was 50.
   Riesman, son of Harvard University professor and author David
Riesman, did extensive fieldwork in West Africa and was published
widely on a variety of topics.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
