<FILEID>AP-NR-07-02-88 0546EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DigestBriefs     07-02 0736</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Digest Briefs,0763</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Yegor K. Ligachev, the No. 2 man in the Kremlin,
provided an unprecedented look into the inner workings of the
Soviet leadership with his description of the events that brought
Mikhail S. Gorbachev to power.
   Ligachev said Friday at the Communist Party conference that
Gorbachev had crucial support from himself, Andrei A. Gromyko and
KGB chief Viktor G. Chebrikov when he became party general
secretary in March 1985. Gromyko, now president, was foreign
minister at the time.
   Ligachev, recounting emotions and experiences in a manner rare
for a member of the traditionally stoic party Politburo, disputed
claims from ousted Moscow Communist Party boss Boris N. Yeltsin
that he had slowed reform.
   He said he had been deeply worried about the fate of the country
during the final days of Leonid I. Brezhnev, who ruled from 1964 to
1982 in a ``time of stagnation.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The commander of Soviet troops in Afghanistan said
they served with honor and were not defeated, but two influential
officials criticized the decision to intervene in the fight against
U.S.-backed rebels.
   ``We came to Afghanistan not to win battles, but to defend women
and children, villages and cities. And we have performed our duty
with honor,'' Lt. Gen. Boris Gromov told the national Communist
Party conference on Friday.
   The Red Army entered in Afghanistan in December 1979, and more
than 100,000 troops were helping the Marxist government fight the
Moslem guerrillas until a withdrawal agreement was signed in April.
   Gromov, who told reporters this week that the Red Army is no
longer taking active part in the fighting, rejected claims that the
Soviet force was beaten.
   Grigory Baklanov, editor of the literary journal Znamya, said
the decision to intervene was made ``in defiance of the machinery
of democracy.'' He said some non-voting members of the ruling
Politburo learned about the decision only by reading the newspapers.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Costa Rica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Negotiations are the only road to
peace in Nicaragua, President Oscar Arias of Costa Rica told
Secretary of State George P. Shultz, who reportedly is considering
a new aid program for the rebels.
   Arias said he told Shultz on Friday that negotiating between
Nicaragua's leftist Sandinista government and the rebels, known as
Contras, was still possible despite a breakdown in talks last month.
   ``I am sure that the offer of the Sandinista government is not
their final offer,'' Arias told reporters at his home moments after
Shultz's departure for Washington.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   People who received unsolicited pornography
sparked an investigation that authorities said resulted in federal
charges against companies responsible for much of the country's
sexually oriented mailings.
   Indictments unsealed Friday in eight states charged 20 people
and 14 companies under a section of federal law that makes it a
crime to use the mails for advertising or distributing obscene
material.
   ``Project Postporn,'' the official moniker for the Justice
Department-Postal Service probe, specifically targeted hard-core
pornography, which depicts actual sexual acts.
   Mailings usually arrived at homes addressed to adults, children
or simply ``resident,'' said Brent Ward, U.S. attorney for Utah and
chairman of the attorney general's subcommittee on obscenity.
   ``They arrive unsolicited in innocuous-looking envelopes in the
homes of unsuspecting people who have never subscribed to
pornography, do not want it in their homes and are never going to
order any obscene material,'' Ward said at a Justice Department
news conference Friday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite rising teacher pay, the president
of the American Federation of Teachers warns that rough days lie
ahead for public schools unless there are radical changes in the
nation's education system.
   Albert Shanker said he would deliver that message in his keynote
address today to 3,000 AFT delegates at the start of their biennial
convention.
   Shanker's union released a report Friday that indicated U.S.
teacher salaries are at a record high _ $28,085 on average in
1987-88 _ and starting pay is up to $18,557 on average.
   But Shanker, an outspoken critic of traditional school
structures, argues that schools fail to deliver an adequate
education to 80 percent of all students. He recently proposed
allowing groups of six to 12 teachers experiment with running their
own schools-within-schools.
   He said in an interview that if teachers don't take the lead in
persuading the public to restructure schools, ``we're going to end
up being dismantled out of existence.''
</TEXT>
