<1ST_LINE>a a BC-TickerTalk Adv04   07-02 0592</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Ticker Talk, Adv 04,0608</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv04</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Monday, July 4, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Takeover Stocks Led Market Parade In First Half</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also on financial wires.</NOTE>
<HEAD>Lasergraphic planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Though a mood of caution and indecision
prevailed in the stock market for much of the time, there were
still a good many success stories to be told on Wall Street in the
first half of 1988.
   Indeed, in the waning days of June, 31 issues traded on the New
York Stock Exchange had doubled or more from their 1987 closing
prices.
   As any follower of the investment scene might expect, the list
of those winners was dominated by stocks of companies that became
the targets of takeover or buyout bids.
   Prominent examples: Murray Ohio Manufacturing, up 175 percent;
J.P. Stevens, 135 percent; Arkansas Best, 134 percent; York
International, 131 percent; Varo, 130 percent; Payless Cashways,
120 percent; Federated Department Stores, 119 percent; and American
Standard, 112 percent.
   While the overall averages posted gains for the first half of
the year, there were some notable laggards as the market struggled
to recover from the beating it took in the crash last fall.
   It was a test of patience for the 2.7 million-plus owners of
American Telephone & Telegraph, the nation's most widely held
stock, which closed June 30 at 26}, down 0.9 percent from the end
of 1987.
   AT&T holders fared much better than did the many fans of
Genentech, a high-flying leader in the promising field of
biotechnology.
   Genentech shares fell some 35 percent to rank among the first
half's biggest NYSE percentage change losers, as investors went
through a wrenching reappraisal of prospects for a Genentech drug
used to treat heart-attack patients.
   Still harder times befell Coleco Industries, the loss-plagued
toy and game manufacturer, whose stock fell more than 40 percent.
   Coleco shares, which traded as high as $65 a share in 1983 when
the company's Cabbage Patch Kids dolls were becoming a national
craze, reached mid-1988 in the neighborhood of $2.
   Aside from such individual cases, the market has had trouble
establishing any consistent themes so far in 1988.
   There was no standout strength, for example, either in stocks
that would benefit the most from an increase in inflation or in
issues that represent a ``disinflation'' play.
   Analysts said that betokened greater than usual confusion among
investors over the direction in which the economy was headed.
   The year began amid widespread recession fears in the wake of
Black Monday last Oct. 19.
   As it became clear that economic activity was running stronger
than almost everybody had forecast, the concern shifted to a
possible revival of inflation.
   By midyear, that scare seemed to have abated somewhat and, sure
enough, talk was stirring again of a business slump in 1989.
   In a compilation by Standard & Poor's Corp. of the comparative
performance of industry groups in the stock market through June 29,
many of the winners drew their strength from takeover bids or
battles that affected one or more of their component stocks: For
example, textile products, up 65 percent, and department stores, up
49 percent.
   Notable among the worst performers were some health-care groups
_ miscellaneous health care, down 30 percent, and medical products
and supplies, down 3 percent _ and high-technology entries like
computer software, down 11 percent, and electronic instruments,
down 4 percent.
   For those investors who bet on revived inflation, gold mining
stocks failed to pay off, falling nearly 5 percent.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Monday editions, July 4</NOTE>
</DOC>
