<NOTE>For Release Wed AMs, July 6, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Remember Summertime Security</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As millions of Americans hit the roads for
summer vacation, burglars and other crooks go into action for one
of their busiest seasons.
   Summer is one of the peak times for burglary, police statistics
show, thanks to the combination of closed schools and absent
vacationers.
   The insurance industry reports that most burglars turn out to be
school-age young people.
   That means, of course, that most burglars are not professionals,
just adolescents taking advantage of unguarded homes during their
idle time. A few simple precautions can discourage most of them,
according to the Insurance Information Institute.
   Lots of companies are advertising complex and costly alarm
systems, and many of them do a good job. They can turn on lights,
set off noisy bells and sirens and even alert a central office or
the police in the event someone tries to enter your home.
   Probably not everyone needs or can afford a high-tech system.
But there are still things they can do to help protect the home.
   To begin with, lock doors and windows, including the attic,
basement and garage. Sure, this sounds obvious. Yet police report
that many burglars get into homes through doors and windows
carelessly left unlocked.
   The insurance institute recommends deadbolt or double cylinder
locks for doors, and notes that a variety of good, inexpensive
window locks are on sale.
   In many areas, local police will do a free security audit of the
home and make recommendations.
   When away, try to make the home look lived in, the institute
says.
   For example, have someone mow the lawn, and ask a neighbor to
collect the mail and newspapers instead of stopping delivery. The
fewer people who know you're away, the better.
   Do not hide keys outside the home, burglars know where to look.
Leave a key with a friend or neighbor who can check on the house
from time to time.
   Get automatic timers for lights to keep the place looking lived
in. Keep ladders out of sight and locked up.
   Valuable items should be locked in a safe deposit box or other
secure storage.
   And, the insurers note, many home insurance policies have limits
on the coverage for items such as jewelry, furs, silver and other
valuables. If you have such property, an additional policy may be
needed.
   If a urglar does break in, stereos, televisions and such are
among the most popular items to steal.
   Permanently mark them in an inconspicuous place with initials,
Social Security number or some other identifying mark. Often,
police will lend an electric engraving tool for this purpose. With
this mark, if police do recover the stolen items, you will be able
to identify yours and get them back.
   When back from vacation, look for signs of burglary before
entering the home. Surprising a burglar could be a deadly mistake.
   And while on the road, remember you are not immune from crime
either. Be wary of pickpockets and setups, such as someone dropping
a handful of change to distract you while an accomplice steals
luggage or other property.
   Never leave luggage unattended, travel experts say, and always
be wary of problems in crowded areas, especially if bumped or
jostled.
   Wrap your wallet in rubber bands _ that makes it much harder to
slip out of the pocket, suggests the American Express Company. And
women should carry the purse tucked securely under their arm.
   Some thieves have adopted the strategy of putting up signs that
say ``Beware of Pickpockets,'' and watching people to see which
pocket they check on viewing the sign.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Wed AMs, July 6</NOTE>
