<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions July 2-3</NOTE>
<HEAD>Volatility Marks First Half Of '88; Economists More Bullish For
Remainder</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If the first half of 1988 is any indication of
what the rest of the year will be like for bonds and interest
rates, better hang on to your hats now.
   ``Anybody who survived the first half of '88 had to have had
their seatbelt on,'' said Irwin Kellner, chief economist for
Manufacturers Hanover Trust Co. ``The market was extremely
volatile.''
   Bonds started out the year on a strong note, with interest rates
continuing to decline following last fall's stock market crash. The
Federal Reserve had relaxed its credit policies on the widespread
belief the crash might affect spending habits and push the economy
into a recession. And declining oil prices also played an important
role in dampening any inflation concerns.
   But as the economy showed surprising resilience, interest rates
started to climb again and bonds lost their luster. Concern turned
to the possibility of higher inflation and the interest-rate
outlook overseas along with the dollar's instability in foreign
exchange.
   Those factors continue to plague the credit markets, although
rates have eased lately on the recent strength of the dollar. A
firm U.S. currency makes dollar-denominated bonds and notes more
attractive to foreigners and lessens the prospects of higher
inflation, which erodes the value of fixed-income securities.
   ``If you're a bond trader and you made money in the first six
months of the year, then you were a superstar,'' said Jay
Goldinger, who runs the Beverly Hills, Calif., investment banking
firm Capital Insight Inc. ``Most of us ended up about even.''
   ``The interesting thing is that with all the ups and down we've
had, we haven't changed all that much,'' noted Maury Harris, chief
economist for PaineWebber Inc.
   Bond prices and yields right now are about where they were at
the start of the year.
   For instance, the yield on the Treasury's 30-year bond, the most
widely-watched issue in the credit markets, stood at 8.93 percent
on Jan. 4. On the last day of June it was 8.85 percent, down from
8.92 percent in the previous session.
   And the Shearson Lehman Hutton Daily Treasury Bond Index, which
measures price movements on all outstanding Treasury issues with
maturities of a year or longer, looked at the end of June like it
had barely budged from early January.
   In the intervening months, however, prices and yields proceeded
on a veritable roller-coaster ride. The 30-year bond, which peaked
at 10.4 percent the day of the market crash last October, tumbled
to a low of 8.29 percent on Feb. 5 and jumped to a high of 9.35
percent on May 23.
   Commercial lending rates followed suit. Major banks lowered
their prime lending rates _ used to set rates on most corporate and
consumer loans _ a quarter of a percentage point to 8.5 percent on
Feb. 2, then raised them to 9 percent on May 11.
   Mortgage rates followed a similar pattern. For a conventional
30-year fixed-rate mortgage, rates ranged from a low of 9.84
percent in mid-February to a high of 10.58 percent in late May and
early June, according to the Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corp.
   The confusion in the marketplace scared away some municipal and
corporate issuers.
   For the first six months, the volume of municipal issues totaled
$52.76 billion, compared with $58.13 billion a year ago. The volume
of corporate issues fell to $141.4 billion from $157 billion in
1987.
   ``Right now, sentiment is cautiously bullish,'' based largely on
the dollar's recent strength, said Kellner of Manufacturers Hanover.
   But he said bond investors are keeping an eye on the Midwestern
drought and what effects that might have on food prices and
inflation _ although most economists say the drought's impact
probably won't be felt until the beginning of next year.
   Some economists predict a drop in interest rates for the
remainder of 1988, based in part on the declining oil market, the
firmer dollar and the feeling that the economy eventually will run
out of steam.
   But as PaineWebber's Harris concedes, what happened in the first
half of 1988 ``goes to show how difficult it is to predict.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions July 2-3</NOTE>
