<1ST_LINE>a f BC-Week'sBusiness Adv02-03 1stadd 07-02 0459</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Week's Business, Adv 02-03, 1st add,0475</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NEW YORK: with us.''</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   In other business news this past week:
   _Grain and soybean futures swung wildly in heavy trading on the
Chicago Board of Trade because of the drought, which has raised the
prospect of higher food prices and hurt the farm equipment business.
   _The Index of Leading Economic Indicators, the government's
chief economic forecasting gauge, dipped 0.1 percent in May, but
analysts said the decline did not suggest a threat to economic
growth at least for the rest of the year.
   _Reports on the interest-rate sensitive construction industry
suggested a mixed picture. One said existing home sales rose 3.1
percent in May while sales of new homes edged down 0.3 percent.
Another report said construction spending climbed 1.1 percent in
May.
   _U.S. factory orders for manufactured goods fell 0.6 percent in
May, but analysts weren't concerned, attibuting the drop to a
decline in demand for aircraft, which fluctuates from month to
month.
   _A Commerce Department report showed the United States
lengthened its lead as the largest debtor nation in 1987, when the
U.S. foreign debt burden climbed to $368.2 billion, up 36.8 percent
from 1986.
   _The Senate Labor Committee approved legislation to raise the
federal minimum wage to $4.55 per hour from the current $3.35 over
the next three years.
   _The Supreme Court issued a key civil rights ruling allowing
employees to use statistical evidence to prove their bosses are
guilty of illegal discrimination. The justices also ruled defense
contractors enjoy broad protection from lawsuits.
   _International Business Machines Corp. announced a $600 million
consolidation plan it said would probably result in the resignation
or retirement of 3,000 to 4,000 employees.
   _An Airbus A320 jetliner crashed during a demonstration flight
in France, and airline analysts said the accident could lead to
cancelled orders and lost sales for the European consortium that
makes the highly-touted plane.
   _Directors of two big companies approved management-led
leveraged buyouts, transactions financed with borrowed money repaid
through earnings and asset sales. Paper-products giant Fort Howard
Corp. will become a private company in a $4.08 billion leveraged
buyout, while Payless Cashways will go private in a $909 million
deal.
   _Federal officials have extended until Aug. 1 the negotiating
deadline for Texas billionaire Robert M. Bass, who is seeking to
take over troubled American Savings and Loan Association, the
nation's second largest thrift.
   _Motown Records, which launched the careers of such black
singers as Diana Ross, Michael Jackson and Stevie Wonder, was sold
to MCA Inc. and an investment banking firm for $61 million.
   _A former Continental Illinois National Bank & Trust Co. officer
and an ex-banker from Oklahoma accused of contributing to
Continental's 1984 near-collapse pleaded guilty to criminal charges.
</TEXT>
