<NOTE>$adv 03</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions July 2-3</NOTE>
<NOTE>Eds: will be followed later in cycle with ADD containing weekly
price trends</NOTE>
<HEAD>Rising Demand, Drought Fears Keep Pushing Sugar Prices Higher</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Rising demand from the Far East has helped push sugar futures
prices to 6{-year highs, and analysts say the Midwestern drought
has sparked an increase in bullish speculation that could drive
prices higher still.
   On the other hand, any hint that the rally is running of steam
could send the market plunging as nervous traders on New York's
Coffee, Sugar & Cocoa Exchange scurry to take profits _ or cut
their losses, experts say.
   Sugar prices have risen steadily since bottoming out at about
2.75 cents a pound in mid-1985 when world stockpiles stood at
record highs. Growing demand and declining production have
gradually reduced the surplus until it now stands just above the
critically low level of 30 percent of the anticipated 1988-89
demand, according to Judith Weissman Ganes, an analyst with the
investment firm Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in New York.
   In contrast to the slow, steady gains during much of the past 3
years, sugar prices for near-month delivery have skyrocketed in the
last two months, from about 8 cents a pound at the end of April to
more than 13 cents a pound at the end of June.
   Moves by China during the past year to increase the availability
of sugar in that country has had a profound impact on the market,
said Erik Dunlaevy, a trader with New York-based commodities and
brokerage firm Balfour Maclaine Corp.
   ``Basically, the government of China decided to let the Chinese
fulfill their desires for sugar,'' he said. ``They decentralized
the purchasing to a certain extent, so you have different entities
buying sugar instead of one central purchasing agency.''
   He said China ordinarily buys its sugar from Thailand,
Australia, the Philippines and other exporters in the Eastern
Hemisphere. But the increased demand from the Chinese has forced
those producers to raise their prices, prompting China and other
Far Eastern consumer nations to shop for lower-priced sugar in the
West.
   Caribbean nations supply much of the Western Hemisphere's sugar,
and Caribbean sugar is traditionally the type that gets delivered
on the Coffee, Sugar & Cocoa Exchange, Dunlaevy said. Thus, China's
increased demand is largely responsible for the sharp rise in sugar
futures prices.
   Exacerbating the situation is the drought, which threatens to
substantially reduce yields of sugar beets in the Red River Valley
region of Minnesota and North Dakota, analysts said.
   ``That's the largest beet crop in this country, so the beet crop
here could be down 500,000 to 700,000 tons,'' said Thomas Oxnard,
vice president of commodities trading for PaineWebber Inc. in
Clifton, N.J.
   ``On a worldwide basis, that's not a huge number but it's a
further drawdown in stocks,'' he said.
   The drought has also increased bullish speculation in sugar
futures, just as it has in virtually every other market for U.S.
agricultural products.
   ``I know there are traders who have one eye on soybeans and one
eye on sugar and when beans go up, they buy sugar,'' Oxnard said.
``To some degree all these markets have just piggybacked on top of
each other.''
   One measure of market speculation is ``open interest,'' the
number of buy or sell orders that have not been canceled out by an
offsetting order. Since late April, open interest in sugar futures
has expanded from less than 130,000 to nearly 170,000.
   ``A large part of the open interest is speculative in nature,
representing a lot of fund and commission-house speculators,'' Ms.
Ganes said.
   Although many analysts, including Ms. Ganes, expect sugar prices
to climb higher in the near term, they acknowledged that prices
could also fall very rapidly.
   ``If the market does show signs of weakening, (speculators) will
be fairly quick at taking a profit and that could result in a sharp
turn in the market,'' Ms. Ganes said. ``The people who got in at
the higher levels are going to be quicker to get out, and that
could exaggerate the correction.''
</TEXT>
