<HEAD>UNDATED: the correction.''</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Here are some commodity price trends for the past week:
   Wheat futures advanced but other grain and soybean futures lost
ground on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Wheat for delivery in July settled Friday at $4.00{ a bushel
compared with $3.80{ a week earlier; July corn slipped to $3.42 a
bushel from $3.42{; July oats dropped to $3.32 a bushel from $3.63;
July soybeans dipped to $9.88{ a bushel from $10.29{.
   Cattle futures advanced while pork futures retreated on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   August live cattle finished the week at 64.60 cents a pound
compared with 62.77 cents; August feeder cattle rose to 73.67 cents
a pound from 70.85 cents; July hogs fell to 44.82 cents a pound
from 44.92 cents; July frozen pork bellies dropped to 35.25 cents a
pound from 38.20 cents.
   Precious metals posted losses on the Commodity Exchange in New
York.
   August gold fell to $439.60 a troy ounce from $446.00; July
silver ended the week at $6.703 a troy ounce, down from $6.810.
   Energy futures retreated on the New York Mercantile Exchange.
   August West Texas Intermediate crude oil plunged to $14.94 a
barrel from $16.01; August heating oil fell to 41.02 cents a gallon
from 43.41 cents; and August unleaded gasoline dropped to 48.35
cents a gallon from 49.21 cents.
